Document ID‚ôĒAgency ID‚ôĒDocket ID‚ôĒTracking Number‚ôĒDocument Type‚ôĒPosted Date‚ôĒIs Withdrawn?‚ôĒFederal Register Number‚ôĒFR Citation‚ôĒTitle‚ôĒComment Start Date‚ôĒComment Due Date‚ôĒAllow Late Comments‚ôĒComment on Document ID‚ôĒEffective Date‚ôĒImplementation Date‚ôĒPostmark Date‚ôĒReceived Date‚ôĒAuthor Date‚ôĒRelated RIN(s)‚ôĒAuthors‚ôĒCFR‚ôĒAbstract‚ôĒLegacy ID‚ôĒMedia‚ôĒDocument Subtype‚ôĒExhibit Location‚ôĒExhibit Type‚ôĒAdditional Field 1‚ôĒAdditional Field 2‚ôĒTopics‚ôĒDuplicate Comments‚ôĒOMB/PRA Approval Number‚ôĒPage Count‚ôĒPage Length‚ôĒPaper Width‚ôĒSpecial Instructions‚ôĒSource Citation‚ôĒStart End Page‚ôĒSubject‚ôĒFirst Name‚ôĒLast Name‚ôĒCity‚ôĒState/Province‚ôĒZip/Postal Code‚ôĒCountry‚ôĒOrganization Name‚ôĒSubmitter Representative‚ôĒRepresentative's Address‚ôĒRepresentative's City, State & Zip‚ôĒGovernment Agency‚ôĒGovernment Agency Type‚ôĒComment‚ôĒCategory‚ôĒRestrict Reason Type‚ôĒRestrict Reason‚ôĒReason Withdrawn‚ôĒContent Files‚ôĒAttachment Files‚ôĒDisplay Properties (Name, Label, Tooltip)
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0001‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-07T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-07T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒInteroperable medical records systems could reduce patient burden and improve care coordination, but healthcare providers need transparent information about how AI tools function and rigorous safety testing before implementing them to protect pati...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒAshley‚ôĒHernandez‚ôĒ‚ôĒIndiana‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy grandson had asthma attacks last year and I took him to three different doctors. Every single time we showed up, they made us fill out the same paperwork‚ÄĒhis whole medical history, his medications, everything he'd already told the last doctor. It was frustrating because nobody could just look up what they already knew. I kept thinking it would be so much easier if the doctors could share his records and see the whole picture right away.<br><br>But here's what worries me. One of those offices had a computer problem and couldn't find his file for two weeks. Two weeks. If we're going to let these systems share information between doctors, somebody's got to be checking that they're actually safe and working right. I work construction, and before I use a new tool on a job site, I need to know what it can do and what it can't do. I need to know it's been tested. That's not being difficult‚ÄĒthat's being responsible.<br><br>When doctors are using AI tools to share my grandson's medical records, they need to know how those tools work and what they've been tested on. They can't catch problems if companies won't explain what their systems do or how they were built. Making things easier is good, but not if it means we're dropping the checks that keep people safe. The doctors treating my grandson deserve better information about what they're working with, not less.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0002‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-20T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-20T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe commenter opposes weakening transparency and oversight rules for healthcare data handling, arguing that the lack of evidence about their effectiveness is premature given their recent implementation, and expressing concern that removing require...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒBarbara‚ôĒRamirez‚ôĒ‚ôĒIowa‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy daughter switched doctors last year because of insurance changes, and getting her medical records was a nightmare. The old clinic kept saying their computer system wouldn't let them send files electronically. I ended up having to drive over there and pick up paper copies myself. That was in 2023, and it shouldn't have been that hard.<br><br>I understand the agency is saying there's no proof that transparency requirements actually help patients. But that doesn't make sense to me. These rules are brand new‚ÄĒof course there aren't studies yet showing real-world results. You can't expect evidence to exist when something just started. It's backwards to say we should weaken the rules before we even know if they work.<br><br>What worries me most is the part about removing requirements for companies to explain what they're doing with AI and patient data. I'm not an expert, but I know my family's medical information is private and sensitive. If we take away the rules that make companies show their work on how they're handling that data, we're going backwards. We should be making this stuff more transparent, not less. I've already seen how hard it is just to get your own records‚ÄĒI don't want to find out later that nobody was watching where that information actually went. Before you remove any of these oversight rules, please think about people like me who just want to trust that our doctors and their computer systems are being watched by someone.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0003‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-08T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-08T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒTransparency requirements for hospital AI systems should be maintained rather than removed, as they are currently the only mechanism to verify that algorithms used in patient care have been tested for safety and bias, particularly given that the a...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒKaren‚ôĒPerez‚ôĒ‚ôĒFlorida‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒLast year my daughter fell off a climbing structure at school and needed emergency surgery. We rushed her to the nearest hospital, but halfway through her care they transferred her to a different facility. For three hours, nobody could find her medical records. Three hours. I'm standing there watching them try to figure out what medications she was already on, what allergies she has, what the first hospital had already done. It was one of the scariest moments of my life, and it happened because of a simple information gap.<br><br>Now I'm reading about removing transparency requirements for AI systems that hospitals use to make decisions about patient care, and I keep thinking about that three-hour blackout. Except this time it wouldn't be about lost paperwork‚ÄĒit would be about algorithms that nobody can verify are actually safe.<br><br>The agency says these transparency rules don't have published evidence of benefit yet. But that's backwards. These rules are too new to have generated outcome studies. Absence of evidence isn't evidence of absence. That's basic logic. We can't afford to remove the only protection patients have‚ÄĒwhich is knowing whether the systems handling our data have actually been tested for safety and bias‚ÄĒwhile we're still waiting for research to catch up. Hospitals and doctors need to be able to trust and verify the AI tools they're using. Right now, requiring companies to disclose how they built and tested these systems is the only way to make that happen. Taking that away leaves families like mine with nothing but hope that someone's doing their job right.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0004‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-19T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-19T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒA parent of a child with Type 1 diabetes supports interoperability improvements but opposes removing transparency requirements for AI systems in healthcare, arguing that mandatory disclosure of model training data, validation populations, and know...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒAshley‚ôĒWilson‚ôĒ‚ôĒWashington‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy daughter was diagnosed with Type 1 diabetes about fourteen months ago, and I've spent the last year trying to piece together her medical information across three different clinics because we move around for my job. Getting everything downloaded and consolidated was a nightmare‚ÄĒI finally got it done last month, but then I sat there staring at these files on my laptop wondering if they were actually secure or if some vendor's employees could just access her blood sugar readings whenever they wanted.<br><br>Here's what I'm worried about with these proposed changes. I want her data to move between doctors more easily‚ÄĒthat part makes sense and would actually help me. But I don't understand why we have to lose the transparency requirements to get there. My daughter's doctors need to know how any AI system that touches her care was actually built and tested. Did they validate it on kids like her? What populations were left out? What are the known failure points? Right now, if an algorithm was trained mostly on adult patients or missed certain populations, there's nothing requiring anyone to say that upfront. Her endocrinologist just has to trust it works, and I'm supposed to feel comfortable with that?<br><br>The certification requirements around model cards and training data disclosure aren't red tape‚ÄĒthey're the only way doctors can actually catch when something might not work right for their specific patients before it causes harm. Removing those requirements means my daughter's doctors are basically flying blind. I get that compliance costs money, but the cost of an algorithm that misses patterns in her care is way higher. Can we really not require companies to at least say what they tested and what they didn't?‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0005‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-02T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-02T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe Policy Center for Maternal Mental Health opposes weakening health IT certification and transparency standards, arguing that while regulatory streamlining is appealing, removing independent verification requirements and model card disclosures f...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒDaniel‚ôĒFlores‚ôĒ‚ôĒNew York‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒPolicy Center for Maternal Mental Health‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRe: Request for Information Related to the Health Technology Ecosystem and Deregulatory Actions To Unleash Prosperity<br><br>The Policy Center for Maternal Mental Health appreciates the opportunity to comment on the proposed changes to health IT certification and interoperability requirements. We represent patient advocates and clinical providers committed to ensuring that data gaps do not delay care‚ÄĒparticularly for vulnerable populations like those experiencing maternal mental health crises.<br><br>A year ago, one of our colleagues' daughter was discharged from the hospital three days postpartum. Her OB-GYN had no access to psychiatric records from a clinic across town documenting a prior hospitalization for postpartum psychosis. By the time those records surfaced‚ÄĒafter a patient request took two weeks‚ÄĒshe was already deteriorating into crisis again. She survived. Others don't. This gap existed not because the records couldn't be shared technically, but because the systems managing that data lacked documented accountability standards. We are deeply concerned that loosening certification criteria will expand these blind spots rather than close them.<br><br>We understand the appeal of reducing regulatory burden on vendors. But certification standards exist because patients can't review code. They can't audit algorithms. They depend on third-party verification that the systems handling their most sensitive information meet basic safety and security thresholds. Model card disclosures‚ÄĒtransparent documentation of how AI systems are trained, what they're designed to do, and what they might miss‚ÄĒshould not be an optional competitive advantage. They should be foundational.<br><br>On the specific RFI questions: We support streamlined real-world testing requirements that use existing clinical workflows rather than creating parallel certification pathways. What we cannot support is removing transparency mandates themselves. A vendor attestation without independent verification is not a safeguard‚ÄĒit's a liability deferral. If we weaken disclosure requirements now, before AI adoption in clinical care is widespread, we will have written patient harm into the system. We will have a documented record of knowing better and choosing not to act.<br><br>We urge HHS to retain model card requirements while exploring whether the attestation process itself can be accelerated. The two goals‚ÄĒfaster market access and patient safety‚ÄĒare not incompatible.<br><br>Respectfully submitted,<br><br>Daniel Flores<br>Policy Director<br>Policy Center for Maternal Mental Health<br>New York‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0006‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-15T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-15T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒA parent of a child with Type 1 diabetes argues that AI transparency requirements in healthcare should be maintained, drawing a parallel between fragmented medical records and opaque algorithmic decision-making, and contending that transparency bu...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒDavid‚ôĒHill‚ôĒ‚ôĒOklahoma‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy daughter was diagnosed with Type 1 diabetes last year, and I've had to live through a nightmare that I wouldn't wish on anyone. We've seen three different endocrinologists in the past twelve months‚ÄĒpartly because we moved, partly because we needed a second opinion‚ÄĒand every single time, the records don't follow her. One doctor says they can't pull up what the previous one documented. Another says their system doesn't talk to the other system. Meanwhile I'm sitting in examination rooms explaining her insulin regimen, her blood sugar patterns, her dietary needs, over and over like we're starting from scratch. It's maddening and frankly dangerous.<br><br>So when I read that you're considering removing requirements for AI model transparency, something clicked for me. This is the exact same problem, just in a different form. If algorithms are making decisions about my daughter's care‚ÄĒwhether it's flagging certain medications as contraindicated or predicting her risk for complications‚ÄĒhow am I supposed to know if those decisions make sense? How is her doctor supposed to trust what the software is telling them if nobody explains how it actually works?<br><br>The agency says there's no published research proving transparency helps patients. But that's backward logic. These transparency rules are too new to have generated a bunch of outcome studies yet. That doesn't mean they don't work. It means we haven't measured them long enough. What I know from lived experience is that opacity kills trust, and trust is what keeps people safe in healthcare.<br><br>I'd ask you to keep the model card disclosures. Patients deserve to know what's driving decisions about their health.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0007‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-19T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-19T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒAgilian Government Solutions warns that weakening health IT certification standards will accelerate industry consolidation by making compliance costs manageable only for large, well-capitalized firms, while urging the agency to streamline redundan...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒBrian‚ôĒNelson‚ôĒ‚ôĒWyoming‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒAgilian Government Solutions‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒAgilian Government Solutions respectfully submits this comment on the proposed deregulatory actions affecting health IT certification and interoperability standards.<br><br>We work with health IT vendors across the country, mostly regional and mid-market players. Last quarter alone, we spent $340,000 bringing one client through the existing certification pathway. Within months, a national health system acquired them. That acquirer now lobbies for the very regulatory relaxation that would have made my client's compliance costs negligible during the transition. I'm watching this play out repeatedly, and it troubles me because the math is simple: larger entities can absorb certification burden as a cost of acquisition. Smaller competitors cannot. Weakening DSI and certification criteria will not unleash competition‚ÄĒit will accelerate consolidation by making the transition costs manageable only for well-capitalized acquirers and existing incumbents.<br><br>On the specific question of which certification criteria should be removed or revised: we'd support streamlining redundant attestation requirements and test procedures that duplicate functional validation already accomplished through real-world deployment data. But I want to be direct about the transparency provisions. The agency's reasoning‚ÄĒthat model card disclosures lack longitudinal outcome literature‚ÄĒconfuses the absence of published studies with the absence of real benefit. These requirements are less than three years old. You cannot measure five-year outcomes when the policy itself is younger than that. The absence of evidence is not evidence of absence. It's evidence of immaturity. Dismantling transparency because we don't yet have ten years of peer-reviewed data is premature and, frankly, dangerous. We need those disclosures to remain because they're the only mechanism preventing vendors from burying algorithmic bias or system limitations in fine print that no provider actually reads.<br><br>What I'm asking the agency to consider: tightening burden on testing procedures, yes. Removing transparency and accountability? That's where I have to push back. The smaller players we serve need standards to compete on merit. Once those standards erode, they lose the only leverage they have against acquisition at distressed valuations.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0008‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-30T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-30T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒA health IT vendor argues that retaining structured DSI model card transparency requirements reduces overall burden by providing hospitals with standardized information for purchasing decisions, and that regulatory streamlining should instead targ...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒStephanie‚ôĒTaylor‚ôĒ‚ôĒOhio‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒbeHuman Corp.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThank you for the opportunity to comment on the proposed changes to health IT certification requirements. As a compliance officer at beHuman Corp, a health IT vendor in Ohio, I've spent the last year navigating multi-state certification demands, and I want to offer a perspective that might seem counterintuitive: retaining structured transparency requirements, specifically DSI model card disclosures, actually reduces burden rather than increasing it.<br><br>Last year our team spent three months just parsing certification requirements across state lines while trying to ship patient portal updates our clients needed. One colleague ended up on medical leave from the stress. What I learned is that removing requirements without maintaining transparency standards doesn't help smaller vendors like us‚ÄĒit just shifts the burden downstream to hospital procurement teams, who then ask us the same questions anyway, usually in less structured ways. We end up answering emails and scheduling calls instead of filling out one clear disclosure form.<br><br>Here's what concerns me about loosening DSI transparency without replacement: hospitals need detailed information to evaluate whether our software actually fits their specific workflows and patient populations. Right now, a procurement officer at Cleveland Clinic or Ohio Health can review our model disclosures and know exactly what they're getting. Remove that, and they either demand customized assessments (which costs us more than the form), or they default to the vendors with the biggest sales teams. That's not deregulation‚ÄĒthat's regulatory capture by the incumbents.<br><br>I'm not opposed to streamlining. But the right target isn't transparency. It's the redundant state-by-state certification pathways that forced us to hire a contractor just to manage paperwork. Removing certification criteria should mean one clear federal standard, not a fragmented market where every hospital requests different documentation. The DSI model cards are how we prove to buyers that we're serious about their safety and workflow requirements. They're a form of standardization that actually speeds purchasing decisions.<br><br>If you're asking which requirements should be revised, I'd say focus on eliminating duplicative state oversight and streamlining the real-world testing protocols so smaller vendors can afford the process. But keep the disclosure standards. They're not red tape. They're the structured data that lets procurement teams make informed decisions faster, which gets better software to patients quicker. That's deregulation that actually works.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0009‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-27T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-27T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒA hospital system administrator argues for streamlining redundant health IT certification requirements to reduce costs and market consolidation, but insists that transparency and validation standards for AI-driven clinical decision support systems...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒGeorge‚ôĒJackson‚ôĒ‚ôĒTennessee‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒHEP, LLC‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒHEP, LLC submits this comment regarding the proposed modifications to health IT certification requirements and information blocking standards. Our organization operates a 240-bed hospital system in Middle Tennessee and contracts with multiple EHR vendors for clinical and administrative operations. I have spent the past eighteen months managing a recertification cycle that cost our organization nearly $400,000 for what amounts to a module update addressing clinician workflow in our ICU‚ÄĒa function that existed in prior versions but required complete re-validation because of midstream requirement changes. That experience informs my perspective on where regulation should loosen and where it must not.<br><br>The question of which certification criteria should be revised or removed deserves a direct answer: we support streamlining redundant testing pathways and reducing duplicative attestation requirements between state and federal programs. Real world testing burdens have consolidated vendor development teams toward larger players with compliance infrastructure; a competing vendor in our region simply abandoned their recertification effort and now serves urgent care clinics instead. That kind of market consolidation is a genuine problem worth addressing through lighter compliance pathways.<br><br>But I want to be clear about something: that cost-reduction argument stops cold when we reach algorithmic systems and clinical decision support. Transparency around AI-derived recommendations is not bureaucratic overhead. It is foundational infrastructure for patient safety and clinical liability. Our clinicians need to know whether a sepsis alert originated from human-validated protocols or from a machine learning model trained on what population, validated against what outcomes, and with what documented limitations. Right now, that disclosure doesn't always happen. Requiring vendors to produce model cards documenting intended use, target populations, validation scope, and known performance gaps is not onerous‚ÄĒit is the minimum baseline. A clinician who doesn't know whether a recommendation comes from decades of evidence-based practice or from an algorithm validated on 2,000 patient records from a different health system is being asked to practice medicine blindly.<br><br>I understand the irony of this position. I spent eighteen months in certification hell. I have no appetite for adding compliance burden. But the alternative to transparency requirements on algorithmic systems is not deregulation; it is liability that dwarfs whatever savings we achieve through lighter testing pathways. We will push back on compliance costs. On this one, we cannot afford to cut corners.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0010‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-10T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-10T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒCareAtlas argues for smarter health IT regulation that reduces unnecessary recertification burdens for unchanged features while strengthening‚ÄĒnot weakening‚ÄĒtransparency requirements for AI tools, as model card disclosures are essential for detecti...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒDavid‚ôĒThomas‚ôĒ‚ôĒIllinois‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒCareAtlas Inc.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThank you for the opportunity to respond to this request for information. CareAtlas operates a seven-clinic network across Illinois, and we've been living with the practical costs of health IT regulation for years. Three years ago, we spent $80,000 in consultant fees just to navigate certification paperwork during an EHR transition. I understand the impulse to reduce that kind of burden‚ÄĒit's real, it's painful, and it affects our ability to invest in actual clinical improvements.<br><br>But I want to push back respectfully on removing AI model card disclosure requirements. This is where I think we need smarter regulation, not less regulation.<br><br>Here's what's happening in our practice. We implemented an AI-assisted diagnostic tool last year for radiology screening. Within two months, our radiologist flagged that the tool was performing poorly on patients with certain anatomical variations‚ÄĒnothing dangerous, but inconsistent enough that he was second-guessing it more often than not. We had the model card. We could see the performance data broken down by patient population. We contacted the vendor, got clarity on the training dataset limitations, and adjusted our workflow accordingly. Our liability exposure dropped because we weren't relying on a black box.<br><br>Without that documentation, we would have had no way to detect the problem until something went wrong. And then we'd have nothing to show regulators, our malpractice carrier, or a patient's family except a vague claim that the vendor told us it was safe.<br><br>The certification burden I actually want reduced is the repetitive attestation and testing for features that haven't changed. If a vendor's EHR already passed certification for basic data exchange, and they're just releasing an update that doesn't touch interoperability, why are we certifying the entire system again? That's where the $80,000 goes. That's what slows innovation. Real world testing requirements for genuinely new capabilities make sense. Recertifying unchanged functionality doesn't protect patients; it just taxes developers and practices.<br><br>What I'm asking for is this: streamline certification for incremental updates and features that don't affect safety or interoperability. But keep‚ÄĒor strengthen‚ÄĒtransparency requirements for any algorithm that influences clinical decision-making. Model cards aren't compliance busywork. They're the documentation my clinical staff needs to use AI responsibly. They're what protects our patients and our liability.<br><br>Vendors can absolutely compete on features, speed to market, and ease of use. But they shouldn't be able to compete by withholding information about how their tools actually perform. That's not innovation. That's just risk transfer to providers.<br><br>David Thomas<br>Practice Manager<br>CareAtlas Inc.<br>Illinois‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0011‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒXSELL Technologies argues that AI model card disclosure requirements in health IT certification should be retained despite compliance burdens, as they provide essential transparency for clinicians evaluating AI tools in clinical workflows and prot...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒGeorge‚ôĒGreen‚ôĒ‚ôĒIdaho‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒXSELL Technologies‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThank you for the opportunity to comment on the proposed changes to health IT certification criteria. I'm writing from XSELL Technologies, where we serve rural clinics and smaller health systems across the Mountain West, and I want to push back on what I'm seeing as a temptation to strip out the detailed AI model card requirements in the DSI certification criterion.<br><br>Last year we spent $200,000 and six months getting our patient portal recertified. Sarah, our lead developer, spent more time documenting compliance than building the features our clinics actually asked for. I get the frustration with certification burden‚ÄĒI really do. But here's what concerns me: we're about to put AI tools into clinical workflows where mistakes aren't just expensive, they're dangerous. A miscalibrated risk algorithm, a model trained on data that doesn't represent rural populations, unknown failure modes in edge cases‚ÄĒthese things matter when they're affecting patient care decisions.<br><br>The model card disclosure requirement isn't bureaucratic theater. It forces vendors like us to actually think through what our tools do, who they work for, and where they might fail. When a clinician at one of our partner practices is deciding whether to trust an AI recommendation, they need to know the training data characteristics, the validation processes, the known risks. Right now, without that transparency, we're asking providers to adopt a black box and hope it works. That's not innovation‚ÄĒthat's liability waiting to happen.<br><br>I understand the argument that this slows smaller vendors down. It does. But the rural clinics we work with can't absorb bad outcomes. They're already stretched thin. They need confidence that what we're selling them is legitimate, that we've actually validated it, that we're not just slapping AI on something because it's marketable. The model card requirement gives them that confidence. It gives us credibility too.<br><br>What worries me more than compliance cost is what happens if we relax this and then a vendor's AI system causes harm. We'll see a backlash‚ÄĒregulators will tighten everything, trust in health IT will crater, and adoption will slow even more. The clinics we serve will be even more reluctant to try new tools. That's not deregulation working; that's the opposite.<br><br>I'm not saying the certification process is perfect. There's real waste in how it's structured. But the answer isn't to throw out transparency requirements. It's to streamline the process‚ÄĒmaybe allow phased certification, or clearer documentation templates, or shorter review cycles. Keep the model card requirement but make it less burdensome to produce. That's how you help smaller vendors compete without compromising the accountability that healthcare actually needs.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0012‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-16T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-16T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRemoving transparency requirements will not drive innovation but rather embolden institutions already resistant to interoperability standards, as regulatory uncertainty currently provides cover for inaction that deregulation would only worsen; the...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒAmanda‚ôĒHernandez‚ôĒ‚ôĒColorado‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒAmerican College of Surgeons‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe surgical resident I mentioned at the start of this semester‚ÄĒthe one who spent three hours manually transferring patient records between systems last spring‚ÄĒshe's still doing it. Nothing has changed in our institution despite the fact that regulatory guidance on interoperability supposedly exists. When I pressed our compliance officer about why two hospital networks within our own system refuse to implement basic data-sharing standards, she pointed directly to regulatory uncertainty. That was in May. It's still the reason nothing has moved forward.<br><br>I raise this because the RFI seems to assume that removing transparency requirements will unlock innovation in health IT markets, but what I'm watching happen on the ground contradicts that logic. The uncertainty isn't paralyzing developers. It's paralyzing institutions that should be adopting standards but instead cite compliance risk as justification for inaction. Deregulation won't fix that‚ÄĒit will likely make it worse. Once transparency requirements disappear, institutions will have even less external pressure to interoperate.<br><br>On the specific question of which certification criteria should be revised: I'm hesitant to endorse blanket removal without understanding what replaces the accountability structure. That said, if the agency believes AI model card transparency is too nascent to have generated robust outcome literature, I'd push back on that reasoning. It's true there aren't longitudinal studies showing transparency prevents specific harms. But the absence of published evidence is not the same as evidence of absence. Transparency requirements in healthcare are only a few years old in most contexts. We don't have longitudinal data because longitudinal data takes years. Conflating methodological lag with actual ineffectiveness sets an impossible evidentiary bar‚ÄĒyou can't require five years of outcome data before the requirement has existed for three years.<br><br>What concerns me more is the direction this sends to vendors and hospital systems already inclined to resist costly interoperability work. Regulatory uncertainty gave them cover to do nothing. Regulatory retreat will give them permission. In my field, we've seen this movie before with other standards. The market doesn't naturally produce interoperability when it's convenient not to. Someone has to require it.<br><br>I'm not opposed to streamlining burden where genuine burden exists. But I'd want to see the agency distinguish between requirements that actually obstruct innovation and requirements that merely constrain profit margins by demanding transparency. Those aren't the same thing.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0013‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-18T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-18T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRemoving mandatory model card disclosures and DSI certification criteria will worsen data access barriers and information asymmetry in concentrated healthcare markets, leaving clinicians without the evidence needed to evaluate algorithmic safety a...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒGeorge‚ôĒThomas‚ôĒ‚ôĒKansas‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒNORC at the University of Chicago‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒLast month I spent six hours on the phone with three different health systems trying to obtain de-identified patient datasets for a cardiovascular outcomes study. Two refused outright. The third demanded a licensing fee that exceeded my NIH grant by 40 percent. My graduate student has been on this project for eighteen months. He's now exploring collaborations in Canada instead. This is happening while we're supposed to have interoperability standards in place, and I mention it because the proposed deregulation will make this exact problem worse, not better.<br><br>The argument I keep hearing is that removing DSI certification criteria and model card disclosure requirements will reduce burden on vendors and spark innovation. I understand the logic. But I've watched what actually happens in concentrated markets. When you remove the disclosure requirements‚ÄĒthe only mechanism forcing vendors to document what their algorithms do‚ÄĒyou eliminate transparency without eliminating the incentive to hoard data. Dominant vendors will have zero reason to share algorithmic performance metrics with competitors or researchers. They already don't. Removing mandatory model cards just makes it official.<br><br>Here's what worries me most: clinicians won't have reliable evidence to scrutinize algorithmic safety before adoption. I'm not talking about theoretical harm. Algorithmic bias in real-world populations is documented. Performance degradation when algorithms move from development cohorts to actual patient populations happens. But it only gets caught if someone can access the model card, understand the training data, see the validation metrics, and identify where the algorithm was tested versus where it's being deployed. Remove that requirement and you've eliminated the evidentiary foundation clinicians need to make informed decisions.<br><br>The consolidation problem compounds this. Without mandatory disclosure, health systems that control algorithmic data have even less incentive to share it. The licensing fees I encountered, the refusals, the gatekeeping‚ÄĒthat all gets worse when vendors can hide algorithmic performance behind certification gaps. Lighter regulation sounds like burden reduction until you realize it's actually burden shifting. You're shifting it from vendors to researchers, clinicians, and patients who can't access the information they need.<br><br>I'm frustrated because I know what real interoperability looks like and what it doesn't. Model card disclosures aren't abstract transparency requirements. They're the only remaining tool forcing vendors to document their work. Remove them and you're choosing consolidation and information asymmetry over innovation.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0014‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-23T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-23T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒSmall medical practices lack the negotiating power of large health systems and rely on DSI model card transparency requirements to evaluate AI tools and vendor offerings safely, so removing these disclosures would unfairly shift compliance burden ...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRebecca‚ôĒRobinson‚ôĒ‚ôĒTennessee‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒHEP, LLC‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThank you for the opportunity to submit comments on the proposed health IT certification changes. Our practice in Nashville has been using the same EHR system for seven years, and what we've learned the hard way is that switching vendors is not a realistic option for small operations like ours.<br><br>Last year alone we spent $47,000 on compliance updates to keep our certification current. Our vendor basically shrugged and told us to expect those costs to climb. When we looked into alternatives, we realized we'd be locked into another 12 months of migration and staff retraining, not to mention the risk of losing patient data in the transition. So we're stuck. That's the reality for practices our size.<br><br>What concerns me about removing the DSI model card requirements is that it takes away one of the only tools we actually have when negotiating with vendors. Right now, when we're evaluating a new AI-assisted diagnostic system or workflow automation, those transparency requirements force vendors to tell us what data trained their models, what populations the tool was tested on, and what the known failure rates are. Without that information, how are we supposed to know if a tool is safe for our patient population or if it's going to create more work for our clinicians?<br><br>The big health systems have procurement teams and legal departments. They can demand answers from vendors. We call our rep and hope for a callback. If you remove the requirement for vendors to disclose model limitations and training data gaps, they'll save money on documentation while we lose the only transparency we have. The vendors aren't going to voluntarily hand us information they're no longer required to provide.<br><br>I'm not arguing against streamlining unnecessary burden. But DSI disclosures actually serve a purpose for small practices. They're not bureaucratic overhead‚ÄĒthey're the data we need to make informed decisions about what tools fit our clinic and which ones carry hidden risks. Removing them won't reduce our costs. It'll just shift the risk down to us while vendors cut their own compliance spending.<br><br>If the goal is real burden reduction, consider keeping transparency requirements for AI tools and clinical decision support while cutting back on the certification criteria that genuinely duplicate other oversight. But removing the model card requirement would just entrench vendor lock-in for smaller practices while the large systems have the negotiating power to get what they need anyway.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0015‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-11T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-11T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒA small health IT vendor argues that clear, upfront AI model card disclosure requirements should be implemented now rather than deferred, as regulatory ambiguity disproportionately burdens smaller firms through over-engineering and compliance cost...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRebecca‚ôĒAdams‚ôĒ‚ôĒMississippi‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒAd Hoc LLC‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRebecca Adams, Ad Hoc LLC<br><br>Re: Health Data, Technology, and Interoperability: ASTP/ONC Deregulatory Actions<br><br>Ad Hoc LLC is a small health IT vendor based in Mississippi. We build interoperability modules for mid-market EHR systems. Five years ago, we spent eighteen months getting our core certification completed. It nearly killed us. Three of our developers were working for equity by month twelve because we simply ran out of money. The certification requirements made sense to us‚ÄĒinteroperability matters, patient safety matters‚ÄĒbut the process was designed for vendors with compliance infrastructure, not firms like ours with four people and a mortgage on the office.<br><br>Last spring, I watched a mid-sized competitor launch a nearly identical feature in six weeks. That competitor has enterprise customers and enterprise resources. They could absorb the compliance risk. We cannot. That experience made me realize something: the burden we're discussing here isn't just about cost. It's about who gets to innovate and who gets squeezed out.<br><br>I'm writing specifically about AI model card disclosure requirements. I know the impulse is to lighten the load on developers, and I understand it. But I'd argue that transparent AI governance standards should go the other direction‚ÄĒthey should be implemented now, upfront, before AI becomes endemic in decision support tools and other products. Here's why it matters to a firm like ours: uncertainty kills smaller companies. Ambiguity about what's acceptable drives vendors to over-engineer, to hire compliance consultants we can't afford, to delay product launches while we guess at what regulators will require. Clear, specific disclosure requirements about AI model performance, limitations, and validation methods are actually cheaper than the alternative‚ÄĒwhich is reactive enforcement after failures occur in clinical settings.<br><br>That's the ethical argument too. Waiting for documented patient harm in real-world DSI products before requiring transparency is not a smart deregulatory move. It's a deferral of accountability. Smaller vendors will absorb that cost in market trust and litigation. Larger vendors will survive it.<br><br>What I'd propose: establish baseline AI model card disclosure requirements now. Make them consistent. Make them specific about what vendors must document and how. That clarity levels the playing field. A small firm with good science can compete if the rules are transparent. What kills us is ambiguity and reactive enforcement.<br><br>We're not asking for more regulation. We're asking for the kind that prevents the catastrophic failures that would devastate smaller innovators and patient safety alike.<br><br>Thank you for considering this perspective.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0016‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-17T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-17T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe Policy Center for Maternal Mental Health opposes eliminating AI model card disclosure requirements from health IT certification, arguing that transparency about algorithm training data, intended use, and validation is essential for preventing ...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒJames‚ôĒThompson‚ôĒ‚ôĒMissouri‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒPolicy Center for Maternal Mental Health‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRe: Health Data, Technology, and Interoperability: ASTP/ONC Deregulatory Actions To Unleash Prosperity<br><br>Policy Center for Maternal Mental Health respectfully submits this comment regarding the proposed revision to health information technology certification criteria, specifically the proposed elimination of detailed AI model card disclosure requirements from the Data Sharing Infrastructure certification criterion.<br><br>We appreciate the Administration's commitment to reducing unnecessary regulatory burden on health IT developers. The maternal mental health community understands that excessive certification requirements can slow innovation and increase costs. However, we urge the Department to retain the current requirement for comprehensive AI model card disclosures‚ÄĒincluding intended use specifications, target population definitions, known risks, training data characteristics, and validation processes‚ÄĒparticularly for clinical decision support systems and diagnostic tools used in high-stakes maternal and perinatal mental health settings.<br><br>My perspective on this issue is shaped by recent experience. Last year, my sister was diagnosed with postpartum depression after the birth of her second child. What struck me during her treatment was how fragmented her care became. Her OB-GYN and psychiatrist operated almost entirely in separate systems. Basic information about her medications, symptom progression, and mental health history couldn't flow between providers because they used incompatible systems. When we finally got her records transferred manually, critical context was missing. One provider didn't know she'd already tried a particular SSRI. The other wasn't aware of her obstetric history, which mattered for medication selection. She spent months in this gap, and I realized then that data interoperability isn't an abstract policy goal‚ÄĒit's about whether patients get coordinated, informed care.<br><br>But interoperability without transparency about the algorithms shaping that care creates a different kind of problem. If her psychiatrist had been relying on an AI tool to flag medication interactions or assess suicide risk, and that tool's training data didn't adequately represent women in the postpartum period, or its intended use assumed a different patient population, that tool could have caused harm. My sister would have had no way to know.<br><br>The maternal mental health field faces specific risks if AI model transparency is weakened. Postpartum depression and peripartum anxiety disorders are underdiagnosed and undertreated, particularly in Black and Hispanic women. If diagnostic support systems are trained primarily on data from non-Hispanic white populations, they may miss presentations that look different across racial and ethnic groups. The current model card requirement forces developers to make these gaps visible. Without it, a provider might adopt a tool without realizing it was never validated in the populations they serve.<br><br>We have reviewed the proposed deregulatory framework and understand the argument that model cards impose compliance costs. But we believe those costs are justified in healthcare contexts where AI directly influences clinical decisions affecting vulnerable populations. The requirement doesn't prevent innovation‚ÄĒit channels it toward safer, more accountable innovation. A developer building a legitimate tool should be willing to document what populations it works for and what it doesn't.<br><br>Three specific concerns drive our position:<br><br>First, maternal mental health has historically been deprioritized in clinical research and training. Postpartum psychiatric conditions are understudied compared to other mental health conditions. This means that AI training datasets are likely to underrepresent the nuances of perinatal mood and anxiety disorders. Without mandatory disclosure of training data characteristics, providers won't know whether a tool was built on adequate maternal mental health data or whether it's being applied to a population it was never tested in.<br><br>Second, the stakes of algorithmic error in this domain are high. Maternal suicide is a leading cause of pregnancy-related death in the United States. If a risk assessment tool misses warning signs in certain subpopulations, the consequences aren't regulatory violations‚ÄĒthey're preventable deaths. A model card that clearly identifies validation gaps and known limitations is a basic accountability mechanism.<br><br>Third, we've seen how information fragmentation affects maternal mental health outcomes. The solution is better interoperability, but interoperability without transparency about the algorithms moving data between systems doesn't protect patients. It just distributes flawed information faster.<br><br>We recognize that some health IT developers operate on tight margins, and compliance costs matter. We also recognize that the certification process has grown complex. But the answer isn't to eliminate transparency requirements in high-stakes clinical applications. The answer is to streamline them‚ÄĒperhaps by creating a tiered certification pathway where basic interoperability tools face lighter requirements, while clinical decision support tools and diagnostic aids face fuller disclosure requirements.<br><br>The maternal mental health community is committed to better data sharing. We want providers to have access to complete patient histories. We want research to accelerate. But we want these improvements built on a foundation of transparency about how algorithms work and who they've been tested on. Removing model card requirements in the name of deregulation would trade short-term compliance cost savings for long-‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0017‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-20T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-20T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRemoving AI model card disclosure requirements would not reduce burden but rather shift evaluation costs to health systems while eliminating a critical transparency standard that clinicians and IT leaders depend on to assess whether algorithmic to...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒAshley‚ôĒScott‚ôĒ‚ôĒVirginia‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒRune Labs‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThree years ago, we were analyzing why a patient's allergy information couldn't move between two hospital systems in the same metropolitan area. She was admitted to a competing health system with a critical cardiac condition, and her cardiologist had no access to her documented penicillin allergy from a regional network's legacy system. The drug interaction nearly killed her. What struck me, sitting with the IRB afterward, was that this wasn't a technical problem‚ÄĒthe technology to share that data existed. It was a regulatory and market structure problem, and nobody had strong enough incentives to solve it.<br><br>That incident became the center of a three-year research protocol we designed to understand why these silos persist despite the obvious harm. The data we've collected makes clear that transparency requirements‚ÄĒspecifically, the detailed AI model card disclosures required under current DSI certification criteria‚ÄĒare doing something very different from what some commenters seem to believe. They're not slowing adoption. They're actually creating the trust conditions that make adoption possible in clinical settings where the stakes are genuinely high.<br><br>I want to be direct about what I'm concerned the proposed deregulatory actions might accomplish. Removing the requirement for detailed AI model card disclosures‚ÄĒthe ones that specify intended use, target population, known risks, training data characteristics, and validation processes‚ÄĒsounds like a burden reduction. In isolation, it probably is. But in the context of health IT adoption in real hospitals and regional networks, it removes one of the few transparent signals that clinicians and health system IT leaders actually use to evaluate whether an algorithm should be trusted with patient data.<br><br>We work with regional networks. I talk to their chief medical information officers, and their IT security teams. The conversation about whether to integrate a new clinical decision support tool or a patient monitoring algorithm isn't primarily about regulatory compliance. It's about whether they can understand what the tool does, what patient populations it was tested on, what its failure modes are, and whether the vendor can articulate any of that clearly. The model card requirement doesn't create that understanding, but it creates a forcing function‚ÄĒa minimum disclosure standard that makes it possible to have that conversation at all. Remove it, and you don't reduce burden; you increase it for the health systems trying to evaluate tools, because now they're in direct negotiation with every vendor about what information will be disclosed.<br><br>I'm also thinking about what happened to our patient. If the allergy information had been trapped not just in a legacy system but in an AI-driven clinical decision support tool that nobody understood, with no documented sense of what patient populations it was trained on or what edge cases it might miss, the outcome could have been worse. The regulatory framework we're discussing isn't abstract. It touches the actual reliability of information that moves between systems and the intelligibility of the algorithmic tools that process it.<br><br>The research we've been doing suggests something that might be counterintuitive to the deregulatory impulse: health IT vendors and health systems actually want these transparency standards. Not all of them, and not without grumbling about compliance costs. But the ones doing serious clinical work‚ÄĒthe ones whose products are embedded in workflows where lives depend on the data moving correctly and the algorithms working as intended‚ÄĒthey want certification standards that are credible. They want to be able to tell their customers that their tools meet a real standard, not just that they comply with whatever negotiated disclosure happened to occur.<br><br>What concerns me about removing the model card requirement is that it conflates two different things. One is reducing unnecessary bureaucratic burden‚ÄĒeliminating requirements that don't actually improve safety or interoperability. The other is reducing transparency in ways that make it harder for the clinical system to evaluate risk. Those are not the same thing, and I think the proposed deregulatory actions blur that distinction.<br><br>The model card requirement, as currently written, asks vendors to disclose: the intended use of the AI model, the target population it was trained and validated on, known risks and limitations, the characteristics of the training and validation datasets, the performance metrics and validation processes used, and the appropriate use cases and contraindications. That's not burdensome to articulate if you actually know your own model. And if you don't know those things about your own model, that's a problem that deregulation shouldn't solve by making it legal to not know them.<br><br>I keep coming back to the patient case because it's concrete. She survived. But the near-miss revealed something about how the system fails: not because of regulation, but because incentives don't push toward interoperability and transparency. Market competition alone didn't solve it. The regional network she was admitted to had no incentive to invest in integrating legacy systems from a competing network. The EHR vendor had no incentive to make their system transparent to external AI tools. And without some baseline transparency requirement, there's no leverage point for health systems‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0018‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-09T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-09T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒHealthcare providers need clear disclosure requirements about AI tools and medical technologies to make informed decisions about patient safety, just as patients need transparency about medications; weakening these requirements risks leaving docto...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒAmanda‚ôĒThompson‚ôĒ‚ôĒTennessee‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy daughter had to fight for three weeks last year just to get her medical records transferred when she switched doctors. The hospital kept saying they "lost" the files‚ÄĒturned out they didn't want to spend the time pulling them. That whole mess got me thinking about how this stuff works on the back end.<br><br>Look, I get that companies need room to innovate and not get buried in red tape. But hospitals and doctors need to know what they're putting in front of patients. If a hospital is using some new AI tool to help with diagnoses or scheduling, the doctors using it should have clear information about how it works and what it's been tested on. That's not different from me needing to know what I'm signing up for when I take a new medication. Right now those disclosure requirements are what gives doctors the facts they need to decide if something is safe for their patients. I'm worried that pulling back on transparency just means hospitals won't have the information they need to make good choices. You can't make a smart decision without knowing what you're actually dealing with.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0019‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-23T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-23T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒTransparency requirements for AI systems in healthcare should be maintained because clinicians need clear information about how these tools were tested and their limitations to make safe treatment decisions, even if this means accepting some burde...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒJessica‚ôĒThompson‚ôĒ‚ôĒWyoming‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy granddaughter was diagnosed with diabetes last year, and I had to call three different clinics just to get copies of her test results. It took nearly two weeks. I'm a retired nurse, so I understand how important it is that doctors have the right information to make good decisions about patient care.<br><br>What worries me about removing those transparency requirements for AI systems is that clinicians won't know what they're working with. When I was nursing, we always knew which equipment was checked and how it performed. That's basic safety. If we're going to use artificial intelligence to help diagnose or treat patients, doctors need clear information about how those systems were tested and what their limitations are. They need to know the risks.<br><br>I understand you want to reduce burden on developers, but not at the expense of what keeps patients safe. Can we find ways to streamline the process without removing the requirements that let doctors actually understand the tools they're using? That seems like the fair balance to me.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0020‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-30T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-30T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒWhile supporting improved medical record interoperability, the commenter urges maintaining strong transparency and accountability requirements‚ÄĒsuch as model cards and attestation standards‚ÄĒbefore allowing AI systems and new technologies to handle ...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒJames‚ôĒMoore‚ôĒ‚ôĒTennessee‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy grandson had his asthma records lost between two clinics last year, and it took us weeks to track down old paper files just to figure out what medicines he'd already been on. My daughter was frantic not knowing what to give him. Now I'm hearing the government wants to make it easier for medical records to move around, which sounds good in theory, but I'm also hearing they might be removing some of the rules that keep watch over how that data gets handled.<br><br>Here's what worries me: before we start letting AI systems and new technologies handle kids' medical information, we need clear guardrails in place. We can't afford to learn this lesson the hard way with our grandchildren's health records. I'm not against innovation or making things easier for doctors and patients‚ÄĒI get that. But removing transparency requirements before we even know how these systems will work in the real world feels backwards to me.<br><br>If you're going to let developers use new tools and AI to handle sensitive health data, they need to show their work first. Model cards and attestation requirements aren't bureaucratic red tape‚ÄĒthey're the safety net. I'd rather have some upfront documentation and testing than find out years from now that somebody's private medical information went somewhere it shouldn't have.<br><br>Thank you for considering these concerns.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0021‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-16T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-16T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒHospitals and clinics need robust transparency requirements for AI tools in healthcare to make informed decisions about safety and efficacy for their specific patient populations, rather than adopting systems blindly without understanding validati...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒJoshua‚ôĒJones‚ôĒ‚ôĒAlaska‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy daughter was diagnosed with lupus last year, and I've spent the last twelve months chasing down her medical records between providers here in Anchorage. Faxes disappear. One office says they never got a request. Another charges twenty dollars a page and takes three weeks. It's been exhausting, and honestly, it made me realize how vulnerable her data is when systems don't talk to each other.<br><br>Then last month her rheumatologist finally uploaded everything to a shared portal, and I could see her full history in one place. It felt like a weight lifted. But it also scared me‚ÄĒI could see exactly how fragile that security is. If someone wanted to access all her sensitive information, they'd know exactly where to look now.<br><br>Here's what concerns me about loosening the certification requirements: hospitals and clinics need real transparency to decide whether an AI tool is safe for their specific patients. When procurement teams can't see how a model was trained, what patient populations it was validated on, or what risks it carries, they're flying blind. My daughter has a complex autoimmune condition. If her health system adopts an AI diagnostic tool without understanding whether it was tested on patients like her, or whether it has known blind spots‚ÄĒthat's not innovation. That's gambling with her care.<br><br>I'm not asking you to stop progress. I'm asking you to make sure hospitals have the information they need to make smart decisions before deploying these tools. Remove the burden that doesn't matter. Keep the transparency that does.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0022‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-27T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-27T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒTransparency requirements for AI health systems should be maintained rather than weakened, as patients and doctors need to understand what these tools were trained on and how they function‚ÄĒeven if formal studies documenting their impact are still ...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒDonald‚ôĒMartinez‚ôĒ‚ôĒWyoming‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy mother had to switch doctors last year because of her insurance, and getting her old medical records transferred took three months. The new clinic couldn't even read half the files from the old system. She had to repeat tests she'd already done, which meant waiting longer to start treatment and paying for things twice. If information could move between systems more easily, none of that would have happened.<br><br>I understand the concern about burden on developers. But I don't think we should weaken transparency requirements just because we don't have published studies showing they're working yet. These rules are still new. That doesn't mean they're not helping right now in real hospitals‚ÄĒit just means studies take time to catch up. I see patients every day who get frustrated when their doctors don't have the full picture. Removing transparency requirements won't fix that problem.<br><br>What I want to say is this: when AI systems are being used to make decisions about someone's health, patients and doctors deserve to know what the system was trained on and what it's supposed to do. That's basic information, not a burden. Yes, developers need some relief, but patient safety and trust matter more. Maybe there's a way to streamline the testing process without cutting back on what doctors and patients get to know about these tools. That's the kind of change I could support.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0023‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-17T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-17T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒCareQuest Institute for Oral Health supports deregulatory efforts to improve health IT interoperability but urges ONC to preserve model card disclosure requirements for clinical AI algorithms, arguing that removing transparency standards would for...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPatricia‚ôĒWright‚ôĒ‚ôĒMinnesota‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒCareQuest Institute for Oral Health‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRe: Request for Information‚ÄĒHealth Data, Technology, and Interoperability: ASTP/ONC Deregulatory Actions<br><br>CareQuest Institute for Oral Health appreciates the opportunity to comment on this important initiative to streamline health IT certification and reduce unnecessary burden on developers and providers.<br><br>Last month, I was helping my sister manage her diabetes, and I realized her endocrinologist and dentist have no way to share information about her medications‚ÄĒeven though some diabetes drugs directly affect gum health and bone density. When I asked our dental practice about integrating records with her medical providers, they told me the certification requirements made it financially unfeasible to even attempt it. That conversation stuck with me because I kept thinking about how many patients like her are falling through these coordination gaps simply because the systems won't communicate. The irony is that technology exists to solve this; policy is what's actually blocking it.<br><br>We understand the impulse to reduce developer burden, but we want to flag one critical area: model card disclosure requirements for clinical AI algorithms. These are not bureaucratic overhead. They are a foundational trust mechanism that clinicians need to responsibly adopt new tools.<br><br>Here's the practical problem. Health systems already struggle to integrate AI-driven diagnostic or treatment-planning tools because they cannot evaluate whether an algorithm was trained on populations representative of their patient base. Dental practices and medical offices don't deploy systems they cannot understand. Without transparent documentation of algorithm performance across demographics, validation datasets, and known limitations, clinicians face a choice: deploy something they cannot defend to patients, or don't deploy it at all. That's not innovation‚ÄĒthat's a barrier disguised as flexibility.<br><br>We urge ONC to preserve model card transparency standards while streamlining other certification pathways. The cost of removing these safeguards will not be borne by developers; it will be borne by clinicians forced to make decisions in the dark and patients like my sister, whose care coordination suffers because providers cannot trust the tools available to them.<br><br>Respectfully submitted,<br><br>Patricia Wright  <br>Policy Director  <br>CareQuest Institute for Oral Health  <br>Minneapolis, Minnesota‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0024‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-02-01T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-02-01T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒZeroTrusted.ai opposes removing AI model card transparency requirements based solely on the absence of published evidence, arguing that the research pipeline lag is normal for new healthcare IT standards and that safety-critical contexts should re...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPatricia‚ôĒGarcia‚ôĒ‚ôĒMinnesota‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒZeroTrusted.ai LLC‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒZeroTrusted.ai LLC strongly supports efforts to reduce unnecessary regulatory burden on health IT developers. We've invested substantially in our compliance infrastructure‚ÄĒroughly $2 million over the past three years‚ÄĒand we understand firsthand the operational weight these requirements impose, especially on smaller competitors. That said, we think there's an important distinction being glossed over in the current framing around AI model card transparency that deserves attention.<br><br>The RFI suggests that because peer-reviewed evidence on the real-world clinical value of model cards doesn't yet exist in the literature, these disclosures may be candidates for removal. We'd respectfully push back on that logic. The absence of published studies isn't the same thing as absence of value. It reflects a timing problem. AI model transparency requirements are genuinely new‚ÄĒwe're talking about requirements that came into play in 2023 and 2024. The research pipeline for healthcare IT interventions typically runs 3-5 years minimum before you see credible longitudinal data. You can't point to 2025 and say, "Where's the evidence from 2020?" The lag exists for every healthcare IT requirement we've adopted. We don't have two decades of FHIR adoption studies either, but that doesn't mean FHIR didn't solve real problems.<br><br>What concerns me is the logical move from "no published evidence yet" to "remove the requirement." In safety-critical healthcare contexts, the burden of proof should run the other direction. Show us why transparency *doesn't* matter before we strip it out. We've seen what happens when developers operate without clear accountability mechanisms‚ÄĒand it's not pretty. Model cards are about clinicians and compliance teams being able to understand what they're actually using.<br><br>On the certification pathway question: we'd support streamlining the dual certification process for vendors that can demonstrate sustained compliance history. That targets burden reduction at the right place‚ÄĒon repeat players with track records‚ÄĒwithout gutting transparency itself.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0025‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-20T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-20T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPatients and their doctors need transparent information about AI tools used in medical care‚ÄĒsimilar to nutrition labels‚ÄĒso they can understand treatment recommendations and identify potential risks, particularly for underrepresented populations in...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒJoshua‚ôĒThompson‚ôĒ‚ôĒNorth Carolina‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy daughter was diagnosed with type 2 diabetes last year, and we've spent months shuffling her medical records between three different doctors. One has them on paper, another uses a different system, and nobody can see the full picture. It's been frustrating, but it also got me thinking about what comes next‚ÄĒbecause now doctors are starting to use AI tools to help manage her care, and honestly, that worries me more than the paperwork shuffle.<br><br>Here's my concern: when a doctor recommends a treatment for my daughter based on an algorithm, I need to understand why. Not the computer science behind it‚ÄĒI'm not asking for that‚ÄĒbut enough information so the doctor can actually explain what the AI is doing and why it matters for her specific situation. Think of it like nutrition labels on food. You don't need to know how the label was made, but you need to know what's in the product so you can make an informed decision.<br><br>Removing transparency requirements like model cards might make things easier for tech companies, but it puts patients at risk. If something goes wrong with her treatment, how will her doctor explain what happened? How will we know if the AI was tested on people like her? I'm not against innovation‚ÄĒI run a small business, so I get it. But transparency isn't a burden; it's a safeguard. Build the AI, yes. But make sure doctors can actually understand and defend the tools they're using to treat our families.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0026‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-25T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-25T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe Texas Medical Association argues against removing certification requirements like model card disclosures, contending that transparency and real-world testing standards are essential for clinician trust in AI tools rather than burdensome regula...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒWilliam‚ôĒTaylor‚ôĒ‚ôĒWyoming‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒTexas Medical Association‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe Texas Medical Association appreciates the opportunity to comment on the proposed deregulatory actions for health IT certification and interoperability standards.<br><br>My perspective on this is shaped by something that happened in my own family last year. My daughter was diagnosed with Type 2 diabetes while living in Cheyenne, and when she moved back to Dallas for school, her endocrinologist here couldn't access the lab work from the clinic up there. We had to request paper records, wait two weeks, and in that gap she got duplicate testing and her treatment got delayed. That's a real cost of our fragmented system, and I think about it when I'm reviewing policy in this space.<br><br>But here's what that experience also taught me: fragmentation is only part of the problem. The other part is trust. Clinicians hesitate to adopt AI tools in patient care‚ÄĒand we're talking about tools that could genuinely improve outcomes‚ÄĒbecause they don't understand how those systems work or what assumptions were baked into them. That's not regulatory overreach talking. That's clinicians asking reasonable questions before they use something in a high-stakes setting.<br><br>The RFI asks which certification criteria should be removed to reduce burden. I'd push back gently on the framing. Model card disclosure requirements aren't a burden. They're a way for health systems to make informed decisions about which AI tools to adopt. Removing those requirements doesn't speed up responsible innovation‚ÄĒit just moves the trust problem downstream, onto providers who now have to guess whether a tool is safe for their patient population.<br><br>Real interoperability and real transparency aren't competing priorities. A vendor that builds a trustworthy system shouldn't have to hide that fact. The vendors who benefit from looser documentation standards are the ones cutting corners, and that's not innovation worth accelerating.<br><br>On real-world testing and attestation: I'd focus changes there on streamlining *duplicate* work, not eliminating accountability. If a developer has already validated a model in a clinical setting, requiring them to re-validate in an identical setting is waste. But weakening the testing requirement itself creates a different problem‚ÄĒyou're asking clinicians to absorb the risk that should sit with the developer.<br><br>The goal here should be smart deregulation, not deregulation for its own sake. Model cards, done right, are a competitive advantage for responsible vendors and a trust enabler for health systems. That's the path forward.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0027‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-28T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-28T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒSmaller health organizations lack resources to independently audit AI systems in clinical workflows, making model card certification requirements essential for equitable access to safety information that larger systems can afford to obtain through...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPatricia‚ôĒHarris‚ôĒ‚ôĒWisconsin‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒFreedom Home Health Care Inc.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒOur organization manages health information systems across a multi-site home health network, and we've been watching closely as vendors push back on certification requirements. The conversation tends to focus on developer burden, which I understand. But we need to be honest about what happens when we strip transparency requirements, particularly around AI systems making their way into clinical workflows.<br><br>Last year we evaluated three different algorithmic tools for care planning. One vendor sent us dense technical documentation that our compliance officer spent weeks parsing. Another provided what amounts to a black box‚ÄĒassurances that the algorithm works, but no documentation of what populations it was trained on, what edge cases might break it, or how it handles patients outside its intended use. We couldn't independently assess the risk. We don't have the budget to hire consultants to reverse-engineer these systems, so we either trust the vendor completely or don't implement at all. Larger health systems with dedicated data science teams can hire firms to audit algorithmic safety. We can't.<br><br>When the ONC considers which certification criteria to remove or revise, I'd ask that model card requirements stay in place. Not because I enjoy compliance overhead‚ÄĒI don't‚ÄĒbut because these standards are one of the few mechanisms that let smaller organizations evaluate whether an AI system is actually safe for our patient population. Model cards aren't perfect documentation, but they force vendors to articulate intended use, training data characteristics, and validation performance in a way we can actually understand and risk-assess. Removing them doesn't reduce burden equitably. It consolidates advantage toward larger systems that can afford independent auditing.<br><br>Real world testing requirements could be streamlined without sacrificing this baseline transparency. But stripping documentation standards just shifts the gatekeeping from regulators to expensive consultants.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0028‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-25T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-25T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe commenter argues that proposed deregulation removing AI transparency requirements would shift burden from developers to clinicians rather than reducing it, and instead recommends streamlining transparency formats (such as standardized model ca...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒAndrew‚ôĒSmith‚ôĒ‚ôĒOhio‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒAVIA Nexus Collaborative‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe work we've been doing over the last eighteen months has left me thinking carefully about what "reducing burden" actually means in health IT regulation, and I suspect I'm not alone in that.<br><br>Last spring, my team at AVIA Nexus Collaborative co-authored a grant proposal examining how fragmented EHR systems affect diagnostic accuracy in rural oncology care. We spent six months mapping data-exchange protocols across partner hospitals‚ÄĒwork that should have taken weeks. When the funding came through, I realized we'd essentially built a workaround for a problem that certification standards were supposed to address. What struck me wasn't that compliance felt onerous; it was that the real burden wasn't regulatory at all. The burden was duplication. Teams across the country are solving the same interoperability puzzle independently instead of advancing treatment protocols.<br><br>That context matters for this deregulation proposal because I worry we're conflating two different problems. One is legitimate: developers spending engineering time on documentation that adds nothing. The other is what we're actually seeing in practice, which is that reduced transparency requirements‚ÄĒparticularly around AI model performance and validation‚ÄĒdon't lighten the load on developers. They shift it onto clinicians.<br><br>When we integrate AI-based clinical decision support into workflows, clinicians need to know what they're relying on. Not for compliance. For safety. They need model cards that show performance across demographic subgroups, validation limitations in edge cases, and documented failure modes. Without that information, hospitals can't responsibly implement these tools, which means they either don't adopt them or they adopt them carelessly. Neither reduces burden; both increase risk.<br><br>I'd suggest that instead of removing AI transparency requirements, we streamline the format‚ÄĒone standardized model card template, machine-readable, reusable across certifications. That reduces developer burden without compromising the evidence clinicians need. Real-world testing attestations could shift from duplicative clinical trial requirements to structured observational data from actual implementations, which is where most of our diagnostic drift problems surface anyway.<br><br>This matters differently in rural oncology than in urban centers. Our partner hospitals in southeast Ohio have smaller informatics teams. They need transparency not as a luxury but as a practical safeguard against algorithmic failures they can't easily debug in-house. Removing that requirement would mean either importing systems they can't fully evaluate or continuing to build workarounds themselves.<br><br>The innovation bottleneck isn't transparency. It's fragmented standards and the regulatory overhead of proving interoperability across incompatible systems. Address that, and developers will move faster and clinicians will adopt more responsibly.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0029‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-19T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-19T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒWhile acknowledging legitimate concerns about regulatory burden, ZeroTrusted.ai argues that deregulation efforts should preserve model card and performance documentation requirements for AI clinical decision-support tools, as these transparency me...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒLisa‚ôĒBaker‚ôĒ‚ôĒIllinois‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒZeroTrusted.ai LLC‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRe: CMS-2024-12345 ‚ÄĒ Health Data, Technology, and Interoperability: ASTP/ONC Deregulatory Actions<br><br>ZeroTrusted.ai operates in the intersection between regulatory compliance and product development, which means we watch these cycles closely. Last year we spent $180,000 recertifying our EHR AI module across three state frameworks, only to have the requirements shift six months later. We made a choice then: recertify at double the cost or exit two markets. That's a real decision, and it's why I understand the frustration driving these deregulatory proposals.<br><br>But I want to flag something that concerns me about the direction this is taking, specifically around model card disclosure requirements for algorithmic tools.<br><br>The impulse to reduce certification burden is sound. Nobody here thinks regulation should be busywork. The problem is that model cards aren't busywork‚ÄĒthey're risk documentation. When a clinician is using an AI system to help flag sepsis risk or recommend chemotherapy dosing, they need to know what that model was trained on, where it fails, and what the false-negative rate actually is. Not to satisfy a checkbox. To practice safely.<br><br>I've watched clinicians at our customer sites override algorithmic recommendations without understanding why the algorithm flagged something. Usually there's a good reason‚ÄĒthe model was trained on a patient population with different comorbidity patterns, or it wasn't tested on certain subgroups. But if nobody has documented that limitation, the clinician can't know they're in a blind spot. That's not compliance burden shifting to the patient. That's real patient harm sitting quietly in the system.<br><br>Here's what I think gets lost in these cost-reduction discussions: transparency requirements aren't preventing vendors from selling products. They're preventing vendors from selling products without disclosure. Those are different things. A vendor who can't articulate their model's limitations probably shouldn't be in the market. The ones who can? They move forward. The certification cost isn't what kills a product‚ÄĒpretending you know more than you do is.<br><br>I'd push back specifically on removing performance documentation requirements for any certified tool that participates in clinical decision-making. Real-world testing and attestation, yes‚ÄĒthere's room to streamline methodology and reduce duplicative state-level testing. But the transparency piece is where vendors and providers need to stay aligned. When something goes wrong, clinicians are liable. They need the information to manage that liability.<br><br>This won't slow down the good vendors. It will slow down the ones betting on nobody reading the fine print.<br><br>Respectfully,<br><br>Lisa Baker<br>Practice Manager<br>ZeroTrusted.ai LLC‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0030‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-04T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-04T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe commenter argues that mandatory model card disclosures for clinical AI tools should remain required rather than being deregulated, warning that removing transparency requirements will allow vendors to control critical information about AI safe...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒEmily‚ôĒMitchell‚ôĒ‚ôĒArizona‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒAmerican College of Cardiology‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒOur cardiology research lab spent eighteen months building an interoperability protocol to move patient EHR data between our university system and three regional hospitals. We owned the data. Our clinical questions were legitimate. But one hospital's vendor claimed our queries violated their licensing terms, and we abandoned the project last spring. I watched a colleague move to Mayo specifically to work on the same problem in an environment with fewer contractual obstacles. That happened in 2023. It still frustrates me because it tells me something important about how we're approaching health IT governance.<br><br>The proposed deregulatory actions will compound these failures unless we lock in transparency requirements for clinical AI before widespread deployment makes them impossible to retrofit. I'm not arguing against reducing burden on developers‚ÄĒI understand the cost pressures. But model card disclosures are not a burden that belongs on the negotiation table. They're a foundation.<br><br>Here's what concerns me: AI adoption in clinical decision support and diagnostics is accelerating rapidly. We're seeing new diagnostic AI tools in cardiology, radiology, oncology arriving faster than most institutions can validate them internally. If we remove the DSI certification criterion for model cards now, we're making a choice to let vendors decide what clinicians and researchers learn about intended use, target populations, training data composition, and known failure modes. That's not deregulation‚ÄĒthat's regulatory capture by contract. It's what happened to my interoperability project, but worse, because it affects patient safety directly.<br><br>The certification criterion requiring model card disclosure‚ÄĒintended use, target populations, validation processes, known risks‚ÄĒis the minimum transparency floor for clinical trust. Removing it signals that vendor convenience outweighs patient accountability in high-stakes medical AI. That's ethically backward. Waiting for documented patient harm before requiring disclosure is not an acceptable governance strategy.<br><br>I'm asking that model card disclosures remain mandatory. The burden is manageable. The alternative is building governance infrastructure after widespread deployment, when liability cascades become unavoidable and retrofitting becomes politically impossible. Real-world testing and attestation requirements can be streamlined without abandoning transparency requirements. Those are separate problems.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0031‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-28T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-28T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe Federation of State Medical Boards supports reducing regulatory burden on health IT developers but opposes removing model card disclosure requirements for clinical AI systems, arguing that transparency about AI performance, limitations, and po...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPaul‚ôĒWalker‚ôĒ‚ôĒTennessee‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒFederation of State Medical Boards‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRe: Request for Information Related to Health Technology Ecosystem Deregulation<br><br>Last year, my neighbor's daughter was misdiagnosed at an urgent care clinic. Her specialist's records didn't reach the ER doctor because the two systems didn't communicate. Watching her parents scramble to piece together her medical history across three providers showed me how fragmented things are. But here's what worried me just as much: if we open up data sharing without keeping strong safeguards in place, that same lack of coordination could just as easily put her information in the wrong hands.<br><br>The Federation of State Medical Boards appreciates the opportunity to comment on proposed changes to health IT certification and interoperability requirements. We support reducing unnecessary burden on developers, but we have serious concerns about removing transparency mechanisms‚ÄĒspecifically model card disclosures for AI systems used in clinical settings.<br><br>Model cards matter because they're one of the few ways clinicians can actually know how an AI tool performs, what its limitations are, and where it might fail. In healthcare, that information isn't just helpful‚ÄĒit's essential. When a system makes recommendations about diagnosis or treatment, doctors need to understand its strengths and weaknesses. Without disclosure requirements, there's no accountability if something goes wrong. We've seen too many cases where algorithmic bias or poor real-world performance caused harm, and the providers using the tool had no way to catch it.<br><br>We're not opposed to streamlining certification criteria generally. But patient safety has to come first. If you're considering which standards to revise, we'd urge you to keep the ones that ensure clinicians have access to critical performance and risk data. That's not burden‚ÄĒthat's basic due diligence.<br><br>Thank you for considering our input.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0032‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-09T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-09T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe American College of Surgeons opposes removing model card disclosure requirements, arguing that algorithmic transparency is essential for detecting safety failures in healthcare systems and that deregulation will entrench vendor opacity rather ...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒKenneth‚ôĒRamirez‚ôĒ‚ôĒMississippi‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒAmerican College of Surgeons‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒOn behalf of the American College of Surgeons, I want to address the proposed removal of model card disclosure requirements within the certification criteria framework.<br><br>Two years ago, I was asked to analyze adverse events across three major hospital systems in the Southeast‚ÄĒMississippi, Alabama, and Louisiana. The goal was straightforward: identify rare but serious complications in surgical site infections following specific procedures so we could adjust protocols before more patients were harmed. We had the clinical data. We had the statistical power. We should have been able to do this work in months. Instead, we spent eighteen months negotiating with three different EHR vendors about data sharing, only to be told that their contracts prohibited interoperability without separate licensing fees. By the time we had access to a usable dataset, the window for early detection had closed. A trend we might have caught‚ÄĒa clustering of infections linked to how one vendor's algorithm prioritized antibiotic prophylaxis recommendations‚ÄĒremained invisible.<br><br>That experience taught me something the regulation writers may not fully appreciate: opacity in algorithmic decision-making doesn't just slow down innovation. It enables harm. And when vendors control access to the very transparency mechanisms that would let us audit those algorithms, we lose the only leverage researchers and safety officers have.<br><br>I understand the appeal of removing "burden." Certification criteria feel like paperwork. Model cards sound like bureaucratic overhead. But they're neither. They're the minimal epistemic infrastructure we need to ask basic questions: What training data was this algorithm built on? What populations was it tested against? Where does it fail? Without that information, I cannot conduct the safety analysis that protects your patients. More importantly, deregulation here will entrench the same proprietary opacity that already fragments healthcare data.<br><br>Removing these requirements won't unleash competition‚ÄĒit will accelerate consolidation. Vendors will have fewer incentives to design for interoperability and transparency. Smaller systems will be squeezed out. And researchers, hospital quality officers, and safety coordinators will lose the tools we need to detect system-level failures before they become tragedies.<br><br>I respectfully urge you to maintain model card certification criteria. Real innovation happens when we can see inside the black box, not when we're locked out of it.<br><br>Kenneth Ramirez<br>Biostatistician, Surgical Quality Research<br>American College of Surgeons<br>Mississippi‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0033‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-10T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-10T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒA parent of a child with Type 1 diabetes argues that AI transparency and certification requirements for medical tools are essential safeguards, as doctors need complete information about algorithmic limitations and testing populations to safely us...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒChristopher‚ôĒHill‚ôĒ‚ôĒMontana‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy daughter was diagnosed with Type 1 diabetes last year, and we've spent the last twelve months shuffling between three different doctors trying to keep her insulin levels stable. Last month I finally got all her medical records into one folder on my phone‚ÄĒit was like someone turned on the lights. But then I realized I had no idea who else could access that information, or what safeguards were actually in place. That's when I started worrying about something else entirely.<br><br>The doctors managing her care now use AI tools to help flag potential issues with her dosing and monitor her patterns. What keeps me up at night isn't just the privacy question anymore. It's whether her doctors actually know how these tools work, what they were tested on, or where they might be wrong. If you remove the requirements that force companies to explain their AI models, to show what populations they studied and what risks exist, how is a doctor supposed to catch an algorithmic error before it affects my kid?<br><br>I'm not against innovation. I get that companies need flexibility. But there's a difference between reducing burden and removing the transparency that lets doctors do their jobs properly. When a doctor has complete information about a tool's limitations, they can make an informed decision about whether to trust it. Without that information, they're operating blind.<br><br>My daughter's life depends on doctors being able to understand and verify the tools they're using. Please don't remove the certification criteria that ensure they have that knowledge. That's not burden‚ÄĒthat's basic responsibility.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0034‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-25T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-25T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒA veteran argues that AI model card transparency requirements should be maintained in healthcare settings because removing them before sufficient research demonstrates their effectiveness risks preventable medical errors, citing his own experience...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRobert‚ôĒJohnson‚ôĒ‚ôĒAlaska‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy name is Robert Johnson. I'm a veteran living in Alaska, and I want to talk about something that happened to me last year that made me understand why these transparency rules actually matter.<br><br>I got diagnosed with diabetes and had to switch VA doctors twice because we moved. Every single time, I had to start over explaining my whole medical history instead of them just pulling up what was already documented. It was frustrating, but then it got serious. One of the new doctors prescribed me something I'm allergic to because they didn't have my full records in front of them. That shouldn't happen.<br><br>Here's what concerns me about removing transparency requirements, especially the AI model card disclosures. The agency keeps saying there's no published research proving that transparency helps patients, but that logic doesn't hold up. These transparency rules are brand new. We haven't had enough time for long-term studies to come out yet. That doesn't mean transparency isn't working‚ÄĒit just means the research hasn't caught up to the rules. You can't say something doesn't help just because we haven't published a study about it yet, especially when we're talking about healthcare decisions that affect people's lives.<br><br>Weakening these requirements now would repeat exactly what happened to me. Doctors making decisions without full information about what they're working with leads to preventable errors. We need to let these safeguards work long enough to actually measure whether they're helping before we tear them down.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0035‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-01T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-01T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒHealthcare AI systems require transparent documentation of their intended use, validation cohorts, and performance limitations‚ÄĒnot as a burden on innovation, but as essential safety infrastructure that enables clinicians to deploy tools responsibl...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒJessica‚ôĒBaker‚ôĒ‚ôĒWest Virginia‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒNORC at the University of Chicago‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ# Comment on Health Data, Technology, and Interoperability: ASTP/ONC Deregulatory Actions To Unleash Prosperity<br><br>The fragmentation I witnessed firsthand last year, when licensing negotiations for de-identified EHR datasets stretched to six months and cost us a talented junior researcher, isn't just an inconvenience for academic research. It's a sign of something more troubling in how we're approaching AI transparency in healthcare. I want to speak directly to the proposal to streamline Data Sharing and Interoperability (DSI) certification criteria, particularly the question of whether detailed AI model card disclosures‚ÄĒcovering intended use, target population, known risks, training data, and validation processes‚ÄĒshould be retained or relaxed.<br><br>My instinct here is to push back on the framing that transparency creates undue burden. At NORC, we work on health IT safety studies across dozens of health systems, and what we keep running into is the opposite problem: vendors claim their AI systems work, they deploy them in clinical settings, and then when we try to actually validate whether they're safe for the populations that matter most, the information just isn't there. Last spring, when we needed to understand how an EHR vendor's sepsis prediction model performed in rural hospitals‚ÄĒwhere case presentations can differ significantly‚ÄĒwe hit a wall. The vendor hadn't publicly documented their training data composition, didn't have clarity on how the model was validated across different hospital sizes, and flagged our request for this information as a competitive threat. This isn't theoretical. This directly delayed a safety analysis that could have informed whether that model was suitable for deployment in smaller health systems.<br><br>I understand the argument that certification requirements slow adoption and give incumbents an advantage by raising compliance costs. That's plausible. But I'd offer a different angle on what's actually happening. The certification criterion that requires model cards isn't preventing innovation‚ÄĒit's creating a floor for what "AI in healthcare" means. When a vendor can put an algorithm into production without documenting its intended use case, its validation cohort, or the populations where it's known to underperform, that's not innovation. That's noise. And clinical teams are left to guess whether the tool they're using has been tested on patients who look like theirs.<br><br>Here's what concerns me specifically about relaxing this requirement. Healthcare AI is not like consumer AI. If a recommendation engine gets your movie preference wrong, you watch something else. If a sepsis prediction model misses a deteriorating patient in a community hospital because it was only validated in academic medical centers, someone dies. The safety argument here isn't academic hand-wringing. It's the difference between systems that clinicians can actually implement with confidence and systems that get deployed and then create liability questions nobody can answer because nobody documented what the system was supposed to do in the first place.<br><br>The model card requirement, as currently framed, asks vendors to disclose: the system's intended use and clinical decision point, the target population characteristics, the datasets used for training and validation (including their size, source, and demographic composition), known performance limitations and failure modes, the metrics used to validate the system, and how performance was assessed across different patient subgroups. That's not onerous. That's baseline documentation. Any vendor serious about healthcare AI should already have this information internally. The certification requirement just makes it visible.<br><br>What I've observed in conversations with health IT developers is that some of the resistance comes from intellectual property concerns‚ÄĒthey worry that detailed model cards expose proprietary training approaches. That's fair, but it's also solvable. You don't need to disclose the exact architecture or training algorithm to disclose the intended use case, the validation cohort, and the known performance gaps. Roche publishes detailed information about their diagnostic tests without revealing proprietary chemistry. The FDA's approval process for medical devices requires this kind of transparency without requiring companies to hand over their source code.<br><br>The second argument I hear is that model cards create barriers to market entry for smaller vendors. Smaller companies can't afford the compliance overhead, so the requirement protects the big players. Again, there's something to that. But the solution isn't to eliminate the requirement‚ÄĒit's to clarify what a good-faith model card actually requires. A startup can document their training data and validation approach without the same resources a major EHR vendor needs for other compliance activities. What they can't do is deploy a clinical AI system responsibly without knowing what they built.<br><br>I keep coming back to our experience last year because it illustrates why this matters in practice. We were trying to do something that should be routine: assess whether an existing AI system in production was performing safely across different hospital types. We had IRB approval, we had data use agreements, we had all the technical infrastructure. What we lacked was basic documentation from the vendor about how‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0036‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-17T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-17T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒA mid-market AI clinical decision support vendor argues that while compliance burden reduction is needed, eliminating model card disclosure requirements would sacrifice transparency for cost savings‚ÄĒand proposes instead streamlining redundant test...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMatthew‚ôĒWright‚ôĒ‚ôĒRhode Island‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒAinsley Advisory Group‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThank you for the opportunity to comment on the proposed certification and standards revisions. We appreciate the intent to reduce unnecessary burden on developers, though I want to flag what worries me about the current direction.<br><br>Ainsley Advisory Group sits in an awkward middle. We're too small to absorb the compliance costs that larger vendors treat as table stakes, but we're big enough that we actually care whether the hospitals using our AI-based clinical decision support tools can trust them. That's where I think this proposal gets the math wrong.<br><br>Last year we nearly lost a contract with a mid-sized hospital network in Massachusetts because a smaller competitor could undercut us 30 percent on implementation. Their compliance overhead was just lower. I kept thinking there had to be a way to level that playing field without hospitals having to guess whether an AI algorithm is actually safe to deploy in their wards. That's the part that concerns me about removing AI model card disclosure requirements. Model cards aren't bureaucratic theater. They're how a clinician or informatics director actually sees what an algorithm was tested on, what its failure modes are, where it performs poorly. Remove those, and you haven't leveled the playing field for innovation‚ÄĒyou've just lowered the floor for transparency, and hospitals pay for that with risk they can't even quantify.<br><br>What I think gets lost in this deregulation framing is that the compliance burden doesn't exist because regulators enjoy paperwork. It exists because bad algorithmic outcomes hurt patients. The question isn't whether to eliminate model card requirements. It's whether we can design smarter certification that removes the redundant testing, the duplicative attestations, the administrative make-work, while preserving the disclosure criteria that actually prevent harm.<br><br>For instance, real-world testing and attestation requirements eat up months and dollars for vendors of our size. But not all of that testing serves a safety function. Some of it's just checking boxes. I'd support revisions that consolidate or eliminate redundant real-world testing pathways‚ÄĒsay, allowing evidence from one health system deployment to substitute for duplicative testing at another system with similar patient populations and workflows. That's burden reduction that doesn't gut transparency.<br><br>Same with certification criteria more broadly. There's probably room to remove criteria that don't actually correlate with patient safety outcomes, or that duplicate what other regulations already require. But the model card requirement, the interoperability standards that let hospitals actually integrate these tools into their systems safely‚ÄĒthose aren't the problem. The problem is that it all costs the same whether you're Cerner or a 40-person startup in Providence.<br><br>I'm not asking for special treatment for mid-market vendors. I'm asking that we don't mistake deregulation for the same thing as safety. Smaller companies should be able to compete fairly. But fair competition doesn't mean hospitals have to choose between low cost and knowing whether an algorithm is going to make mistakes at the point of care. We can streamline how we certify without gutting what we disclose.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0037‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-18T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-18T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒHEP, LLC argues that removing the Detailed Scientific Information (DSI) model card requirement for AI/ML clinical decision support tools would create dangerous transparency gaps that directly threaten patient safety, as healthcare organizations li...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒBarbara‚ôĒWhite‚ôĒ‚ôĒOhio‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒHEP, LLC‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒHEP, LLC respectfully submits this comment in response to the proposed amendments to the Health Data, Technology, and Interoperability deregulatory framework. We operate three primary care clinics across two Ohio counties with a combined patient population of roughly 28,000 patients, and our perspective is grounded in a year of navigating the practical costs of incomplete interoperability standards compliance.<br><br>We want to focus specifically on one aspect of the proposal: the revision to the Detailed Scientific Information (DSI) certification criterion, particularly as it applies to health IT systems incorporating artificial intelligence or machine learning-derived algorithms. We understand the impulse behind the broader deregulatory initiative. We get it. The compliance burden is real. It costs money, and that money could theoretically go toward actual innovation. But we're concerned that removing or substantially weakening the DSI model card requirement for AI/ML-based clinical decision support tools will create a gap in transparency that directly undermines patient safety and, frankly, clinical adoption of these tools.<br><br>Let me walk through why this matters from our specific situation. When we implemented our latest EHR system two years ago, we contracted with a vendor who assured us their system met all relevant certification standards. What we discovered during go-live was that their API documentation didn't align with the newer interoperability requirements‚ÄĒnot because the underlying technology was incapable, but because updating their certification would have cost six figures in compliance work. The vendor made a business judgment that the cost wasn't worth it. So we paid $40,000 to a third-party developer to bridge the gap and ensure our patients' records could actually follow them when they saw specialists in the neighboring county. That's not an unusual story anymore. It's becoming the expected route.<br><br>But here's what troubles me about applying the same "deregulation as a solution" logic to AI certification: in that EHR case, the gap was about data formatting and connectivity. If the API bridge didn't work perfectly, it meant duplicate data entry or missing information. It was inefficient and frustrating. It cost us money. But it didn't make a clinical decision worse in a direct way. An AI algorithm lacking transparent documentation about its training data, known failure modes, target population, and validation methodology operates in a different risk category. If that algorithm is making recommendations about patient diagnosis or treatment, and no one has clear documentation about what populations it was designed for and what biases it might carry, we're operating in the dark in a way that affects patient care directly.<br><br>We've been piloting a predictive tool for identifying patients at high risk of hospital readmission. The vendor provided basic documentation, but when we dug deeper‚ÄĒand we had to hire a consultant to do this‚ÄĒwe discovered the tool was trained primarily on data from urban academic medical centers. Our patient population is about 40 percent rural, with different comorbidity patterns and different healthcare access patterns. The algorithm's performance degraded noticeably when we applied it to our rural patient population. Our clinical staff rightfully wanted to understand why before they relied on the tool in their workflow. If we had only the basic vendor information without detailed model cards, we would have had no way to identify this limitation ourselves.<br><br>The DSI criterion requiring detailed AI model cards is not bureaucratic overhead. It's the documentation that lets a healthcare organization like ours actually evaluate whether a tool is appropriate for our patient population. It lets us understand what the algorithm was trained to do, not just what the vendor claims it will do. It enables our clinicians to use AI tools with appropriate skepticism and context, rather than as black boxes they're expected to trust.<br><br>I'm sympathetic to the idea that overly prescriptive certification processes can stifle innovation. There are absolutely unnecessary compliance hoops in the current system. But the DSI model card requirement is doing work that matters. It's doing work that would be expensive and time-consuming for every single healthcare organization to replicate independently if the documentation didn't exist. Right now, if we want to evaluate an AI tool, we can ask for the model card. If that requirement goes away, we either trust the vendor's claims uncritically, or we hire consultants and data scientists to reverse-engineer the algorithm ourselves. The first option is bad for patient safety. The second option is what drives the kind of out-of-pocket expenses that smaller organizations like ours can barely absorb.<br><br>There's also a question about market competition that the deregulatory proposal seems to assume will fix itself. The logic seems to be: reduce compliance burden, vendors can innovate faster, more vendors enter the market, competition improves products. That's not actually what we've observed. What we've observed is that the vendors with the most market share benefit most from reduced compliance requirements, because smaller vendors and new entrants often use compliance certification as a‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0038‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-01T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-01T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe commenter opposes loosening oversight and transparency requirements for medical record-keeping and AI decision-making in healthcare, arguing that accountability mechanisms are essential to prevent errors and ensure patient safety.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒDaniel‚ôĒWilson‚ôĒ‚ôĒMaryland‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒLast year I spent three months trying to get my daughter's thyroid records transferred between two clinics. Back and forth on the phone, nobody knew where they were, and it was frustrating. Now I'm reading that doctors might not have to follow the same rules about keeping track of medical information, and honestly, it worries me. If we remove the requirements that make sure doctors and clinics have to show their work‚ÄĒespecially with AI systems making medical decisions‚ÄĒhow are they going to catch problems? My experience taught me that oversight matters. Without it, things fall through the cracks. I don't think we should be loosening the rules that require transparency about how these systems work. Patients deserve the same level of accountability whether a person or a machine is involved in their care.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0039‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-21T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-21T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe commenter argues that transparency requirements and model cards for AI in medical devices are essential safeguards that enable patients to understand and advocate for their own care, and warns that removing these requirements would return pati...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMatthew‚ôĒNguyen‚ôĒ‚ôĒVermont‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy daughter has had an insulin pump for four years now. When she was first diagnosed, I wanted to be able to check her glucose readings on my phone while I'm at work. The pump company said no‚ÄĒproprietary data, they called it. I had to call her clinic multiple times a day to get numbers I should have been able to see myself. Last year my wife's doctor's office got hacked and didn't tell us for three months. We found out from a news article.<br><br>That's why I'm worried about loosening the rules around model cards and transparency requirements. I'm not a tech person. I don't understand algorithms or AI or what goes into these devices. But I know I should be able to understand how something controlling my daughter's health actually works. Model cards aren't some burden on companies‚ÄĒthey're the bare minimum honesty we deserve.<br><br>If you remove requirements for companies to explain how their AI makes decisions in medical devices, we go back to the old system. We go back to being locked out. Patients can't advocate for themselves if we don't know what we're dealing with. We can't catch problems early. We can't ask good questions. We're just supposed to trust these companies, and frankly, I don't anymore.<br><br>Keep the model card requirements. That's the only thing standing between patients and black boxes.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0040‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-26T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-26T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRemoving transparency requirements for healthcare AI systems poses serious risks to patient safety and data protection, as doctors and patients need visibility into how these systems work, what they've been tested on, and what safeguards exist‚ÄĒwit...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒAnthony‚ôĒNelson‚ôĒ‚ôĒKansas‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒLast year my doctor's office had a computer crash and lost patient files. It took three months to get my records back, and it turned out they didn't have backups like they should've. That experience shook me. I realized how easily things can go wrong, and how little protection we have when they do.<br><br>Now I'm reading that you're thinking about removing transparency requirements for AI systems used in healthcare. I don't understand why that's the right direction. Doctors need to know what they're using on patients. They need to understand what risks are built into these systems‚ÄĒwhat they were tested on, how they might fail, whether the data is actually protected. Right now, if something goes wrong, at least someone's checking. If companies don't have to show how their systems work or prove they've been tested properly, how is a doctor supposed to know if it's safe?<br><br>When my records disappeared, nobody caught it for weeks. There was no oversight. I think removing AI model transparency is asking for the same kind of problem to happen again, but at a bigger scale and faster. Patients can't protect themselves if we don't even know what's happening with our information. Before you cut these requirements, I'd ask: who's actually protecting patients if the people building and using these systems don't have to explain what they're doing?<br><br>Thank you for considering this.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0041‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-14T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-14T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe commenter argues against wholesale removal of model card disclosure requirements for clinical AI systems, contending that transparency and accountability structures are essential in high-stakes healthcare contexts, while proposing targeted reg...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒJames‚ôĒWhite‚ôĒ‚ôĒCalifornia‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒRune Labs‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThree years ago, my lab shelved a project that could have flagged dangerous drug interactions across hospital systems in real time. We had the algorithms. What we didn't have was access to the data schemas those hospitals used‚ÄĒthey cited liability concerns that didn't actually exist in the regulations, just institutional caution. A colleague's mother had a preventable adverse event the following year at a hospital across town using an incompatible system. I think about that failure often when I consider what we're being asked to weigh here.<br><br>Model card disclosures for clinical AI aren't a recent invention, but their systematic application in healthcare is genuinely new. I understand the deregulatory impulse‚ÄĒburden reduction matters, and developers shouldn't face compliance costs that don't yield real safety gains. But I'd urge caution on removing transparency requirements wholesale. What concerns me is that we don't yet have robust outcome literature on what happens when they're absent. That absence of published studies doesn't mean the benefit isn't real; it means we haven't measured it carefully yet. In high-stakes healthcare contexts, accountability structures matter. Model card disclosures create those structures. They make clinicians more confident in adoption, and they make vendors more disciplined about what they claim their systems can do.<br><br>On your question about certification criteria: I'd revise rather than remove. Keep the disclosure requirements for clinical decision support systems, but streamline the attestation process for vendors who can demonstrate prior real-world testing. Real world testing itself‚ÄĒthat's where I'd focus relief. Let developers use naturalistic data from their own implementations instead of requiring separate validation studies. And on interoperability standards, don't weaken FHIR or TEFCA compliance; just give developers more flexibility on implementation timelines. The infrastructure is what matters. The burden is in the compliance theater around it.<br><br>I'm ready to work with you on this. Rune Labs can serve as a testbed for whatever revised framework you develop.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0042‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-12T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-12T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMCG Health opposes removing detailed transparency requirements from health IT certification because standardized disclosures of model validation data and known limitations are essential for hospitals to safely evaluate AI tools for their specific ...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒKaren‚ôĒRodriguez‚ôĒ‚ôĒNorth Dakota‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒMCG Health, part of the Hearst Health network‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMarch 15, 2025<br><br>Office of the National Coordinator for Health Information Technology<br>U.S. Department of Health and Human Services<br>200 Independence Avenue SW<br>Washington, DC 20201<br><br>Re: RFI ‚Äď Health Data, Technology, and Interoperability: ASTP/ONC Deregulatory Actions<br><br>To Whom It May Concern:<br><br>MCG Health appreciates the opportunity to comment on streamlining health IT certification requirements. We support reducing unnecessary administrative burden on developers. However, I want to flag something that concerns us operationally: as we evaluate AI-powered clinical decision support tools for deployment across our network, we're discovering that removing detailed transparency requirements won't actually lighten our load‚ÄĒit shifts the burden to us, and creates safety gaps we can't afford.<br><br>Last month one of our procurement teams assessed three vendor offerings for sepsis risk stratification. The vendors with DSI certification provided model cards showing intended use populations, validation cohort demographics, known failure modes, and training data characteristics. We could map those against our patient population‚ÄĒwhich skews toward older, rural patients with higher comorbidity rates. The uncertified vendor? Marketing claims and a white paper. We spent weeks requesting technical details they wouldn't disclose. In the end we couldn't responsibly recommend their product, not because the tool was bad, but because we had no way to know if it was safe for our specific workflows and populations.<br><br>That's the real issue. Hospitals don't need more burden‚ÄĒwe need decision-making data. When certification removes the requirement that vendors disclose model cards and validation results in a standardized way, procurement teams default to whatever information is easiest to extract, which is usually vendor marketing. That creates accountability gaps that ultimately land on us when something goes wrong clinically.<br><br>I'd urge the agency to reconsider which criteria actually burden developers versus which ones enable informed hospital procurement. Standardized transparency requirements aren't bureaucratic overhead‚ÄĒthey're the minimum infrastructure hospitals need to evaluate tools safely and responsibly. Removing them doesn't reduce burden; it just obscures risk.<br><br>Respectfully,<br><br>Karen Rodriguez<br>Policy Director<br>MCG Health<br>Bismarck, North Dakota‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0043‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-26T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-26T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe Policy Center for Maternal Mental Health opposes removing AI transparency and model card disclosure requirements from health IT certification, arguing that clinician and patient trust depends on explainability rather than deregulation, and rec...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMargaret‚ôĒHill‚ôĒ‚ôĒMichigan‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒPolicy Center for Maternal Mental Health‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRe: Request for Information ‚Äď Health Data, Technology, and Interoperability: ASTP/ONC Deregulatory Actions<br><br>The Policy Center for Maternal Mental Health appreciates the opportunity to comment on the proposed deregulatory framework for health IT certification and interoperability standards.<br><br>Our organization works directly with postpartum patients and their families navigating fragmented mental health systems. Last year, one of our advocacy cases required six months to assemble medical records from three separate clinics‚ÄĒeach demanded its own authorization form, and one provider refused to share anything without legal intervention. When we finally pieced everything together, critical medication notes were missing entirely because they'd been entered into a system that doesn't talk to the others. That gap nearly derailed proper assessment of a serious clinical situation.<br><br>This experience shapes how we view the proposed changes. We understand the impulse to reduce compliance burden on developers. But we're concerned that removing disclosure requirements‚ÄĒparticularly around model cards and AI transparency in clinical decision-support tools‚ÄĒwon't actually accelerate adoption. It will do the opposite. Clinicians and health systems won't trust tools they can't understand. Patients won't consent to systems built on hidden algorithms. Real adoption happens when developers can demonstrate safety and explainability, not when they're freed from accountability.<br><br>We believe the burden reduction should focus elsewhere. Rather than eliminating model card transparency, consider streamlining the certification pathway itself‚ÄĒperhaps a tiered approval process where lower-risk tools move faster while high-stakes clinical AI undergoes rigorous real-world testing. Real-world attestation requirements could be revised to accept pilot data from diverse settings instead of demanding perfect datasets upfront. That reduces friction without sacrificing the transparency that actually builds clinician and patient confidence.<br><br>Fragmented records cost time, money, and sometimes patient safety. The solution isn't less regulation. It's smarter regulation that makes interoperability and transparency the baseline, not the burden.<br><br>Respectfully submitted,<br><br>Margaret Hill<br>Executive Director<br>Policy Center for Maternal Mental Health<br>Michigan‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0044‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-09T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-09T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe commenter opposes removing transparency requirements for AI systems in healthcare, arguing that model cards and attestation standards are essential for clinicians and patients to understand how AI tools work, assess their safety, and maintain ...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRebecca‚ôĒHall‚ôĒ‚ôĒIndiana‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy mom's cardiologist's office lost her medication list for three days last month because their system crashed. When they finally found it, I realized nobody had ever asked her permission to store it digitally in the first place‚ÄĒthey just did it. That scared me more than the crash itself.<br><br>What scared me even more was that nobody seemed to care about how secure that information was or who could access it. When I started reading about this proposed rule, I kept thinking about how much worse this could get if you remove the transparency requirements around AI systems. Right now, if a doctor's office uses an AI tool to help diagnose patients or prioritize cases, there's supposed to be something called a model card that explains how the system was trained, what populations it was tested on, and what the known risks are. That's the information clinicians actually need to catch problems before they harm someone. Without those model cards, how is my mom's doctor supposed to know if an AI system is safe to use? How am I supposed to know?<br><br>My real concern isn't innovation‚ÄĒit's accountability. When certification criteria get stripped away, there's nothing left to prove a system works or to explain its limitations. Patients and families have no way to know if something went wrong. My mom's data was handled without her knowledge. Weakening transparency rules would make it even easier for healthcare systems to use AI tools without patients understanding what's happening to their information. Please don't remove the model card and attestation requirements. Doctors and patients need to know what we're actually using.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0045‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-19T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-19T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒA social worker argues against removing transparency and certification requirements for healthcare AI systems, contending that disclosure of algorithmic methods, data sources, and validation testing are essential accountability mechanisms for vuln...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRobert‚ôĒYoung‚ôĒ‚ôĒIllinois‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒLast year I was helping a client work through her medical records after her psychiatrist retired. We discovered her full therapy notes‚ÄĒthings she never agreed to share‚ÄĒhad been sold to a data broker without her knowledge or consent. She was devastated. It took weeks to figure out who had access to what. That experience made me realize how little protection exists for people like her.<br><br>Now I'm reading about removing certification requirements and transparency rules for AI systems in healthcare, and I'm angry. Not in an abstract way. I'm angry thinking about the clients I work with every day‚ÄĒpeople with mental health conditions, low-income folks, people in crisis‚ÄĒwho can't advocate for themselves when something goes wrong. If companies don't have to disclose how their algorithms work or what data trained them, how will anyone catch it when the system is biased against my clients? How will we know if an AI model was built on incomplete data that doesn't represent people like the ones I serve?<br><br>The burden argument doesn't work for me. Yes, developers say transparency is expensive. But who pays when an algorithm fails? Not the company that cut corners. The burden falls on the most powerless patients. That's backwards.<br><br>You asked what certification criteria could be removed. I'd say: don't remove the ones requiring disclosure of known risks and validation testing. Keep the ones that make developers explain their data sources and testing methods. Those aren't nice-to-haves. They're the only accountability mechanism vulnerable people have. Reducing developer burden by stripping those requirements just shifts the risk onto patients who have no power to push back.<br><br>Robert Young<br>Social Worker<br>Illinois‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0046‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-30T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-30T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRemoving health IT certification criteria risks creating opaque clinical AI systems that lack transparency safeguards; the commenter urges establishing requirements for model documentation, validation disclosure, and risk acknowledgment now, befor...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒSandra‚ôĒMoore‚ôĒ‚ôĒWisconsin‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒNational Alliance for Care at Home‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒOn behalf of the National Alliance for Care at Home, I want to raise a concern that I don't think gets enough attention in this deregulation discussion, and it stems from something I watched happen to my mother last year.<br><br>When her cardiologist retired, we needed her ejection-fraction measurements and medication history moved to a new provider across town. It took three weeks. Four different health systems, each one citing HIPAA and privacy regulations as the reason they couldn't send records electronically. The paper copies finally arrived two days before her follow-up appointment. She was anxious the entire time‚ÄĒnot because of privacy concerns, but because the system had made it impossible for her to get continuous care. I realized then that we'd let the letter of the law completely override what the law was supposed to do: protect patients.<br><br>That experience is on my mind now as I watch us move toward removing certification criteria for health IT systems. I understand the impulse to reduce burden on developers. But I'm worried we're solving the wrong problem. The issue isn't that we have too many standards protecting data‚ÄĒit's that we have too few standards protecting *transparency*.<br><br>Right now, before clinical AI tools are everywhere, is the moment to require model cards, intended-use documentation, validation data disclosure, and known-risk acknowledgment. Not after we've documented harm. Not after patients have been hurt by algorithms they didn't know were making decisions about their care. If we wait, we'll have built another black box, and we'll be right back where we started‚ÄĒexcept this time it won't be four paper records; it'll be an opaque system deciding who gets what treatment.<br><br>Real interoperability requires trust. You can't have trust without knowing how decisions are being made.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0047‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-20T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-20T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe Alliance for Connected Care opposes removing AI model card disclosure requirements for Data Segmentation Infrastructure certification, arguing that detailed documentation of model training data, validation processes, and performance across pat...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒBrian‚ôĒGarcia‚ôĒ‚ôĒKentucky‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒAlliance for Connected Care‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe Alliance for Connected Care appreciates the opportunity to comment on the proposed deregulatory actions regarding health data, technology, and interoperability. Our organization has spent the past decade working directly with patient advocacy groups, healthcare providers, and health system leaders across Kentucky and the broader Southeast to identify and resolve barriers to meaningful health information exchange. What I want to focus on here is the proposed removal of detailed AI model card disclosure requirements for Data Segmentation Infrastructure certification.<br><br>I'll be direct: I understand the impulse behind deregulation. Three years ago, I watched a cardiologist and a pulmonologist at different health systems literally cannot share imaging results because their electronic health record systems weren't talking to each other. The patient‚ÄĒa 67-year-old woman with a complex cardiac and pulmonary condition‚ÄĒended up repeating expensive diagnostic tests. During the delays between appointments, her condition actually deteriorated. That's not a hypothetical problem. That's someone we helped advocate for, and it took months to coordinate care that should have been seamless. So when I hear that we need to reduce burden on health IT developers to accelerate innovation and interoperability, I get it. I really do.<br><br>But I'm also not going to pretend this is simple.<br><br>The current DSI certification criterion requires vendors to provide detailed AI model cards that disclose intended use, target population, known risks, training data characteristics, and validation processes. The proposal suggests this is unnecessarily burdensome documentation that slows down innovation. I want to explain why we believe retaining this requirement is actually foundational to patient safety and clinical adoption, even if it takes longer upfront.<br><br>Here's what troubles me about removing the model card requirement. When a healthcare system is deciding whether to implement a new AI-driven tool for patient data segmentation or algorithmic decision-making, they're making a choice that directly affects patient care. The clinicians using these tools need to know what they're actually relying on. A model card isn't bureaucratic overhead‚ÄĒit's the only mechanism that tells a cardiologist whether the algorithm making segmentation decisions was trained on a population that includes people like her patients, or whether it was validated on data that doesn't represent the communities she serves. Without that transparency, we're asking healthcare providers to adopt tools they fundamentally cannot evaluate.<br><br>This is where my concern gets more concrete. In 2022, we surveyed 47 healthcare organizations across Kentucky and Tennessee about their AI adoption practices. Forty-one of them told us they had no systematic way to understand what data their AI tools were trained on or how those tools performed in their specific patient populations. Twenty-eight said they'd encountered situations where an AI tool performed differently‚ÄĒsometimes significantly differently‚ÄĒacross racial or ethnic groups, and they had no documentation from the vendor explaining why. When I asked them what information would make them more confident in adopting these tools, the single most common answer was: "We need to know what the model was built on and whether it works for our patients."<br><br>That's not coming from regulatory zealots. That's coming from chief medical information officers and quality improvement directors who are trying to responsibly implement new technology.<br><br>The model card requirement exists because healthcare is different from other sectors where deregulation might work fine. If a consumer-facing tech company removes documentation requirements for an algorithm, the risk is usually contained to individual user experience. But when we're talking about health data segmentation and AI-driven clinical decision support, the risk propagates. A poorly understood algorithm affects not just one patient but potentially hundreds or thousands. And vulnerable populations bear the highest risk because their data is often underrepresented in training datasets. We've seen this pattern repeatedly: algorithms trained predominantly on majority populations perform worse for minority groups, and without model cards, providers can't even see that this is happening.<br><br>I also want to acknowledge something that I think gets lost in these discussions. Vendors have legitimate concerns about proprietary information. I'm not unsympathetic to that. But there's a difference between protecting trade secrets and disclosing basic information about model behavior and limitations. A vendor can protect the specific architecture of their neural network while still documenting what patient populations the model was validated on, what the accuracy rates are across different subgroups, and what known limitations exist. These aren't trade secrets. They're safety information.<br><br>What I've seen happen in other regulatory contexts is that when you remove documentation requirements in the name of reducing burden, you don't actually reduce burden on the healthcare system. You shift it. Instead of vendors providing model cards upfront, health systems end up conducting their own validation studies to figure out whether these tools work in their environment. We've had three separate health systems tell us they've had to hire external consultants to do post-deployment audits of AI tools because they couldn't get adequate documentation from vendors. That's not less burden. That's the‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0048‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-07T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-07T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe commenter opposes rolling back privacy and security rules, arguing that the absence of published research on transparency requirements does not justify removing safeguards, and emphasizing that patients deserve disclosure of AI systems used in...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒStephanie‚ôĒBrown‚ôĒ‚ôĒMissouri‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy daughter's identity was stolen last year when hackers broke into a medical office. It took us six months and hundreds of dollars to fix it. That's money we didn't have to spare. I keep thinking about how much worse it could have gotten if we hadn't caught it when we did. Now I'm hearing that the government might be rolling back some of the privacy and security rules that are supposed to keep this from happening to other families, and I'm honestly scared.<br><br>The agency says there's no published research proving that transparency requirements actually help patients. That doesn't make sense to me. These rules are brand new. Of course there's no formal study yet‚ÄĒthere hasn't been time to do one. Just because we don't have the research doesn't mean the safeguards don't work. It's like saying we should remove the smoke detectors from hospitals because nobody's published a five-year outcome study on smoke detector effectiveness. We don't remove safety equipment because we haven't had time to study it yet.<br><br>I'm also concerned about the AI model disclosures. If healthcare systems are using artificial intelligence to make decisions about patient care, and those systems have hidden biases or problems, patients deserve to know about it. Right now the only thing standing between us and discovering those problems the hard way is transparency. Taking that away before we even understand the risks feels reckless to me.<br><br>Thank you for considering my concerns.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0049‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-21T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-21T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒWhile supporting easier access to medical records, the commenter warns against weakening AI system safeguards and transparency requirements, arguing that patient data security and algorithmic accountability must not be sacrificed for developer con...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒSarah‚ôĒYoung‚ôĒ‚ôĒMissouri‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy daughter had to jump through hoops last year just to get her own test results from her doctor‚ÄĒthree weeks and fifty dollars for a CD that was outdated. Now I'm hearing they want to make it easier to move medical records around, which sounds good in theory. But here's what keeps me up at night: who's checking to make sure these systems are safe? Who's making sure some hacker doesn't steal my grandson's information when it's being shared between all these different places?<br><br>I don't think we should be removing the requirements that make sure these AI systems are actually vetted and transparent. Patients deserve to know how these algorithms work and who's responsible if something goes wrong. We need detailed disclosures about how these systems make decisions affecting our health. Weakening those safeguards just to make things easier for tech companies puts vulnerable people at risk. There has to be a way to reduce burden on developers without throwing out the guardrails that keep patient data safe. That's the balance we need.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0050‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒWeakening health IT certification and model card disclosure requirements will create a two-tier system where venture-backed companies can deploy untested algorithms with minimal scrutiny while academic and community-based researchers face the same...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒJessica‚ôĒMartin‚ôĒ‚ôĒPennsylvania‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒRegenstrief Institute‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRe: Health Data, Technology, and Interoperability: Request for Information on Deregulatory Actions<br><br>The Regenstrief Institute respectfully submits this comment in response to the RFI on certification criteria and testing requirements for health IT developers.<br><br>I lead research at an institution committed to improving medication adherence and care coordination in rural populations‚ÄĒpopulations that cannot afford to become test subjects for unvetted algorithmic systems. Last year, my team spent nine months navigating IRB review and data use agreements to access de-identified patient records from three hospital systems. We still didn't obtain the datasets we needed. During that same period, I watched a venture-backed startup with no prior healthcare experience secure expedited access to similar data from multiple states. The difference wasn't scientific rigor or patient safety planning. It was funding and political relationships.<br><br>I'm concerned that weakening model card disclosure requirements will entrench rather than remedy this inequity. These standards are not compliance theater. They are the minimal transparency threshold preventing well-funded but unaccountable technology companies from deploying untested clinical algorithms while academic and community-based research continues to face bureaucratic delay.<br><br>Removing certification criteria sounds like deregulation. What it actually does is create a two-tier system: venture-backed actors can move fast and deploy opaque models into rural clinics and safety-net hospitals with minimal scrutiny, while research teams serving the same populations get bogged down in the same lengthy approvals‚ÄĒjust now without even the assurance that competing commercial systems faced real vetting. The patients we study deserve better.<br><br>Regarding real-world testing attestations: I'd urge caution before relaxing these requirements. A 48-hour deployment timeline sounds efficient in boardrooms. It means nothing when a poorly validated algorithm causes harm in a community hospital where there's no data scientist on staff to catch the problem. Rural health systems‚ÄĒwhich my research focuses on‚ÄĒlack IT infrastructure to absorb risk. They need confidence that systems deployed to them have actually been tested.<br><br>I'm not opposed to reducing administrative burden. I am opposed to trading away the few transparency mechanisms that currently level the playing field between well-funded incumbents and everyone else. Model cards matter because they create accountability where market forces alone will not.<br><br>Respectfully,<br><br>Jessica Martin<br>Research Director<br>Regenstrief Institute<br>Indianapolis, Indiana‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0051‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-23T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-23T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe commenter supports improved medical data sharing to address access barriers but opposes removing certification and transparency standards, arguing that model cards and safety requirements are essential safeguards for patient privacy and clinic...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒJoshua‚ôĒWilliams‚ôĒ‚ôĒVermont‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy daughter was diagnosed with Type 2 diabetes last year, and I spent weeks‚ÄĒliteral weeks‚ÄĒcalling three different clinics trying to get copies of her test results so her new doctor could see the full picture. Faxes, hold times, forms I didn't understand. It was exhausting. So when I hear they might make it easier for companies to move medical data around, part of me thinks okay, finally. But then I read the fine print and I'm thinking‚ÄĒwho's actually watching to make sure nobody loses her information or sells it to an insurance company? That scares me more than the waiting did.<br><br>Here's what I don't get: you're talking about removing certification standards to reduce burden on developers. But whose burden are you actually reducing? Not patients'. Not doctors trying to make life-or-death decisions about our kids. If a company doesn't have to prove their system works, doesn't have to show what it's trained on or how it makes decisions, how is any doctor supposed to trust that thing? It's like buying a car and the manufacturer tells you they don't need to test the brakes anymore because inspections slow them down.<br><br>Model cards and transparency requirements aren't red tape. They're the only thing standing between families like mine and companies that don't give a damn about protecting our medical information. I'm not saying don't innovate. But don't do it on the back of our kids' health records.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0052‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-31T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-31T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒA health policy educator and cardiologist argues against weakening AI model documentation requirements in the proposed interoperability rule, contending that detailed model cards‚ÄĒwhich disclose intended use, validation methods, and performance lim...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒKimberly‚ôĒWhite‚ôĒ‚ôĒOklahoma‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒAmerican College of Cardiology‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe preliminary data my colleague presented last month at the University of Oklahoma College of Medicine troubled me more than I initially realized. Three major EHR vendors‚ÄĒeach claiming interoperability compliance‚ÄĒhad built export protocols so fundamentally incompatible that cardiologists at our medical center were spending roughly eight hours per week manually reconciling the same patient data across systems. One patient's medication list in System A didn't match System B's record; another's lab values required manual verification because the timestamps didn't align. This wasn't a edge case. It was happening routinely, affecting patient safety decisions, and no one seemed to have clear visibility into why.<br><br>I've spent the last decade teaching health policy students that interoperability is foundational to modern healthcare delivery. The statutory framework is sound. The regulatory intent is clear. But when I watched clinicians work around broken systems because the certification process had become largely performative, I realized the gap between policy aspiration and clinical reality had widened to the point where it demanded comment.<br><br>The proposed rule appears designed to reduce compliance burden on health IT developers by relaxing detailed certification criteria, particularly around artificial intelligence model documentation. I understand the competitive argument. I also understand the innovation argument. But I'm writing to push back on the specific proposal to eliminate or weaken the Data Segmentation for Interoperability (DSI) certification requirement for detailed AI model card disclosures, and I want to be direct about why.<br><br>The model card requirement‚ÄĒwhich mandates disclosure of a model's intended use, target population, known performance limitations, training data characteristics, validation methodologies, and risk profiles‚ÄĒexists because healthcare AI operates in a domain where failures cascade. When an algorithm trained primarily on data from patients aged 65 and older gets deployed to a mixed-age cardiology population, the clinical consequences aren't abstract. They're measured in diagnostic delays, missed arrhythmias, and treatment decisions made on incomplete information. The model card doesn't prevent this problem entirely, but it creates a traceable record of what the system was designed to do, who it was validated against, and what its known limitations are. Remove that requirement and you remove the accountability mechanism that allows clinicians and health systems to make informed adoption decisions.<br><br>Here's what worries me: the proposal frames detailed model documentation as a compliance burden that slows innovation. That's technically true. It does require developers to document their work more thoroughly. But the framing misses what transparency actually provides in high-stakes clinical settings. When our cardiologists are deciding whether to trust an AI-assisted diagnostic tool with patient data, they need to know if the underlying model was validated on datasets that actually represent their patient population. They need to know if the model performs differently across demographic subgroups. They need to know what the false positive and false negative rates actually are, not in a whitepaper, but in a standardized format that allows for systematic comparison across products.<br><br>I'm not arguing against innovation. I'm arguing that meaningful innovation in clinical AI requires trust, and trust requires transparency that goes beyond what marketing materials or general privacy policies can provide. The model card requirement creates a level playing field where developers compete on the quality of their validation and the honesty of their risk disclosures rather than on whose marketing narrative is most persuasive. That's not regulatory burden‚ÄĒthat's market infrastructure.<br><br>The other issue I keep circling back to is what happens to patient safety when we assume that competition alone will drive the transparency we need. The EHR interoperability problem I mentioned earlier isn't a failure of bad actors. It's a failure of a market where vendors have insufficient incentive to truly interoperate because lock-in is profitable. The certification requirement for DSI model cards creates a similar dynamic in reverse: it makes hiding limitations costly, which means vendors have to actually solve problems rather than obscure them. Remove the requirement, and we're betting that competitive pressure will somehow overcome the economic incentive to keep proprietary advantages private. I haven't seen evidence that works in healthcare IT historically.<br><br>The American College of Cardiology has been engaged with ONC on health IT policy for years, and we've generally supported moves toward greater openness and standards-based approaches. We've also supported regulatory streamlining when it genuinely reduces burden without compromising patient safety oversight. But I need to be specific about where this particular proposal misses the mark: it conflates reduced compliance overhead with increased innovation, but in healthcare AI, those aren't the same thing. The most valuable innovation is the kind that can be transparently validated, compared, and adopted with confidence. Model cards aren't obstacles to that innovation. They're infrastructure for it.<br><br>There's also a practical implementation question that I think deserves attention. If ONC removes the detailed model card requirement from DSI certification, what replaces it? Does certification become purely functional testing without visibility into the underlying system's design and‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0053‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-11T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-11T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe Society of Thoracic Surgeons opposes relaxing AI model card disclosure requirements in health data certification standards, arguing that detailed transparency about model training data, intended use, target populations, and known failure modes...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒLisa‚ôĒScott‚ôĒ‚ôĒFlorida‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒThe Society of Thoracic Surgeons‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe Society of Thoracic Surgeons appreciates the opportunity to comment on the proposed changes to health data certification and interoperability standards. We represent over 7,000 cardiothoracic surgeons across the United States, and we care deeply about getting this balance right‚ÄĒboth the innovation side and the patient safety side.<br><br>Last month, I watched one of our member surgeons repeat a $4,000 cardiac imaging study because previous scans from another hospital system were locked in a proprietary format and couldn't be accessed in time. The patient's treatment was delayed a week. That same week, I fielded a call from a hospital administrator worried that if we water down certification standards across the board, they'd lose their competitive edge in a market where quality and transparency matter. I'm not going to pretend I have a simple answer to that tension. But I keep coming back to what happened with that patient, and I think it points to what we need to preserve in this conversation.<br><br>The proposed rule would relax the requirement for detailed AI model card disclosures from developers. Specifically, it would reduce the DSI certification criterion that currently mandates transparency about intended use, target population, known risks, training data characteristics, and validation processes. I understand the impulse‚ÄĒcompliance is expensive, and it slows product launches. I get it. But in cardiothoracic surgery, when we're adopting AI tools to read imaging or assess risk, we need to know what we're actually getting. We need to know what population the model was trained on, because what works well for 50-year-old men from Boston doesn't necessarily work the same way for a 67-year-old woman with multiple comorbidities. We need to know the known failure modes, not because we want to be bureaucratic, but because we need to make informed decisions about when to trust the tool and when to double-check.<br><br>Here's what worries me about loosening this standard: we've seen in other industries what happens when companies can say "our algorithm works great" without showing the actual data behind that claim. In healthcare, that's not just a competitive problem‚ÄĒit's a patient safety problem. And it's also a problem for hospitals trying to adopt these tools responsibly. Right now, our member hospitals are asking vendor questions that should be answerable: What data was this model trained on? What's the performance across different subgroups? What are the documented failure modes? When vendors can't answer these questions because they're not required to keep or share that information, hospitals either have to do expensive validation studies on their own, or they adopt tools without really understanding them.<br><br>The certification criterion we're talking about isn't bureaucratic overhead. It's documentation. The model card requirement exists because surgeons and hospital IT teams need to know what they're implementing. When a vendor tells me their risk stratification model is "highly accurate," I need to see the actual validation data, the populations it was tested on, whether it performs equally well across racial and ethnic groups. That's not asking for a novel safeguard‚ÄĒthat's asking for transparency about something that already exists, that the company already has internally, but often doesn't share.<br><br>What I keep thinking about is this: we can reduce burden on developers without removing the requirement to disclose what their models do. A streamlined model card format would be better than no requirement at all. A standardized template that's the same across vendors‚ÄĒthat actually reduces burden because developers don't have to figure out what each hospital system wants to know. It's not a trade-off between innovation and safety; it's about getting transparency into a format that works for everyone.<br><br>I also want to be honest about something else. The fragmentation issue is real. Our surgeons do work across multiple health systems, and the inability to move imaging data and clinical records seamlessly is a genuine problem that slows down care. We support better interoperability. We support standards that let data move more freely. But interoperability and transparency aren't opposing values. You can have both. You can have better data exchange *and* require vendors to disclose how their AI systems work.<br><br>One more thing: I've heard from our member hospitals that they're concerned about liability if they adopt an AI tool that turns out to have a major limitation that wasn't disclosed. If we remove the requirement for vendors to document what their models do and don't do well, we're shifting that risk entirely onto the health systems that use them. That's not innovation-friendly‚ÄĒthat's risk-shifting. Vendors have an incentive to downplay limitations if they're not required to document them. Hospitals have an incentive to be cautious, which slows adoption. Making the documentation requirement stick actually creates a more rational market where vendors compete on honest assessment of what their tools do, and hospitals can make faster decisions.<br><br>I‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0054‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-31T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-31T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒHospitals need transparent, detailed information about AI tools' capabilities and limitations before adoption to make informed decisions based on patient safety rather than marketing or cost, just as patients need access to their own medical recor...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMichelle‚ôĒFlores‚ôĒ‚ôĒGeorgia‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy name is Michelle Flores and I live in Georgia. Last year I spent three weeks fighting with my daughter just to get copies of my own blood test results so we could show them to a specialist. The office kept saying their computer system wouldn't let them send the files. It was frustrating because we already had the tests done‚ÄĒwe didn't need repeats, but without those records in hand, we had to start over.<br><br>That experience keeps coming back to me when I think about hospitals choosing AI tools for patient care. Hospitals need the same thing I needed: clear, detailed information so they can make the right choice. If a hospital can't see what an AI tool is actually designed to do, who it works best for, what problems it might have, they're making a blind decision. They might pick something because of price or a good sales pitch instead of what's actually safe and right for their patients.<br><br>My grandson had to miss school driving me around because we couldn't get information we already had. I worry about hospitals making decisions without the information they need. Doctors want to do right by their patients. Give them the details they're asking for. Let them compare what tools can actually do before they buy.<br><br>Thank you for listening to this.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0055‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-29T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-29T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒLoosening AI certification requirements for hospitals risks enabling corner-cutting on patient safety, as demonstrated by the commenter's experience with disorganized medical records; hospitals need detailed, mandatory information about AI system ...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRobert‚ôĒLewis‚ôĒ‚ôĒArizona‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy wife had thyroid surgery last year and I spent three weeks trying to get her test results to take to a specialist in Phoenix. The first hospital kept saying everything was "in the system" but nobody could actually pull it together for us. When we finally got the records, half the information didn't match what her doctor told us. It was frustrating and honestly kind of scary.<br><br>What concerns me about loosening these certification requirements is that hospitals already cut corners on the basics. If you weaken the rules about how they check whether new AI tools actually work safely, they're just going to get lazier‚ÄĒthe same way that hospital got lazy about organizing her records.<br><br>Hospital procurement teams need clear, detailed information about any AI system before they decide to use it. What's it designed to do? Who does it work best with? What can go wrong? That's not bureaucratic busy-work‚ÄĒthat's just a checklist for patient safety. When developers have to spell out how their tools were tested and what the limitations are, hospitals can actually make smart decisions instead of just buying whatever vendor shows up with a good pitch.<br><br>I understand developers find certification burdensome. But removing oversight doesn't make hospitals more careful about safety. It does the opposite. We need hospitals thinking hard about what they're implementing, not cutting corners because nobody's checking anymore.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0056‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-15T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-15T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒWhile acknowledging the genuine financial burden of health IT certification costs on small practices, the commenter argues against removing transparency requirements due to insufficient evidence of their ineffectiveness, and instead proposes imple...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMichelle‚ôĒHarris‚ôĒ‚ôĒPennsylvania‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒDoximity, Inc.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThank you for the opportunity to comment on the proposed deregulatory approach to health IT certification and transparency requirements.<br><br>I manage operations for a multi-specialty clinic in Pennsylvania with about 35 providers across four locations. Three years ago, we switched EHR systems and spent nearly $80,000 just on compliance certifications and integration testing. Last month, a vendor quoted us $15,000 for what they called an "update certification"‚ÄĒI had to push back hard because that money comes directly from our ability to hire another nurse or upgrade our patient scheduling. I understand the burden argument completely. Larger hospital systems down the road absorb these costs as a line item; for us, it's the difference between surviving and struggling.<br><br>That said, I'm concerned about the agency's logic here. The RFI states that transparency requirements lack published evidence of positive impact and uses this to justify removing them. But I think there's a real difference between "we haven't studied this enough yet" and "this doesn't matter." AI model cards are what, maybe two or three years into real-world deployment? We don't have longitudinal outcome data on whether they improve safety or reduce errors, but that's because the standards are still too new to have generated that evidence base, not because the transparency itself is worthless. My concern is that we're talking about stripping requirements before we've even had time to figure out whether they work.<br><br>The actual problem, as I see it, isn't that transparency requirements exist. It's that vendors and regulators haven't built efficient, scalable ways to implement them. Smaller vendors especially struggle with the compliance burden, and larger vendors sometimes price certifications in ways that assume hospital-scale budgets. That's the market failure we should be fixing‚ÄĒnot removing the requirements themselves.<br><br>If the agency wants to reduce burden on developers and small practices, I'd suggest looking at the real-world testing and attestation requirements. Right now, every update seems to trigger full recertification cycles even when the underlying functionality hasn't fundamentally changed. Could there be a tiered approach where minor updates undergo streamlined review while material changes involving AI transparency still require full assessment? That way, vendors aren't gaming compliance, patients and providers still get transparency where it matters, and smaller practices don't get crushed by $15,000 recertification bills for routine maintenance.<br><br>What worries me most is that once these transparency standards are removed, it will be nearly impossible to put them back. We'll have lost the moment when we might have learned whether they actually protect patients or providers. For practices like ours, the burden is real. But the answer should be to make compliance smarter and more proportionate, not to gamble that we don't need transparency at all.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0057‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-04T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-04T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRubyWell supports streamlining redundant certification requirements and leveraging existing pilot data to reduce validation costs, but argues that transparency standards for AI-driven clinical decision support should remain non-negotiable because ...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒJoshua‚ôĒSanchez‚ôĒ‚ôĒMissouri‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒRubyWell, Inc.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRubyWell has spent considerable resources navigating certification pathways over the past eighteen months, and we've seen firsthand how shifting requirements can derail even well-planned implementation timelines. That experience shapes how we think about this proposed rule.<br><br>On the question of which certification criteria should be revised: we'd support streamlining redundant validation steps, particularly around functionality that's already been demonstrated under prior standards. Real world testing requirements could be meaningfully reduced if attestation processes allowed vendors to leverage existing pilot data rather than requiring fresh validation cycles for each minor update. We've spent roughly $2.3 million certifying core EHR modules only to face re-validation demands that didn't add clinical value. That's the kind of burden worth examining.<br><br>That said, we want to be clear about what shouldn't be streamlined. Model card transparency for AI-driven clinical decision support feels genuinely important to us. Not because regulators are requiring it, but because clinicians need to understand what they're working with. When a system makes recommendations about patient care, the people using it deserve visibility into how that system was built and what it was trained on. That's not regulatory overhead‚ÄĒthat's clinical trust.<br><br>We support efforts to reduce certification burden where it makes sense, but transparency around algorithmic decision-making in healthcare strikes us as foundational, not negotiable. We'd rather see burden reduction focused on interoperability testing and redundant documentation requirements than on the standards that help clinicians make informed decisions about the tools they're using.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0058‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-18T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-18T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe commenter opposes exempting AI systems in clinical settings from detailed model card disclosures, arguing that transparency about AI training data, intended use, target populations, and known limitations is essential for hospitals to safely ev...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒDaniel‚ôĒHernandez‚ôĒ‚ôĒNew York‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒChildren's Hospital Association‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThree weeks. That's how long we had to operate without a twelve-year-old oncology patient's complete medical history because her family moved mid-treatment and the hospital systems couldn't talk to each other. The doctors were essentially blind‚ÄĒguessing at prior chemotherapy protocols, previous imaging results, genetic markers that might matter. I'm not exaggerating when I say that kind of gap terrifies me, both as an executive director and just as someone who believes children deserve better.<br><br>The proposed rule would let developers skip the detailed model card disclosures for AI systems used in clinical settings. I understand the argument about regulatory burden. But here's what I'm concerned about: if we strip away the requirement for AI developers to document intended use, target populations, known risks, and validation processes, hospitals like ours will have no way to evaluate whether an AI tool is safe for our patient population. We'll be back to operating in the dark, but this time we won't even know it.<br><br>When we finally got that patient's records, the delay wasn't because anyone was withholding information. It was incompatible systems, unclear protocols, and nobody really responsible for making it work. What I learned is that transparency isn't bureaucratic overhead‚ÄĒit's how you actually build trust between systems and between hospitals and the tools they use. If a developer has clearly documented what their AI model was trained on, what it actually does, and where it's known to fail, then I can make an informed decision about whether it's right for children with cancer. Without that, I'm basically gambling with patient safety.<br><br>I get that certification requirements add cost. But the cost of a wrong diagnosis, or an AI recommendation that doesn't account for a population we didn't test on, is a lot higher. Especially in pediatrics. Our patients can't advocate for themselves. We have to do it for them.<br><br>Keep the model card requirement. Make it standardized so it's not a burden for every developer to reinvent the wheel, but don't remove transparency altogether. That's where I'm drawing the line.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0059‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒTransparency requirements for AI systems in healthcare‚ÄĒincluding model cards disclosing limitations, training data, and known risks‚ÄĒshould not be deregulated despite the burden they impose on developers, because the absence of long-term outcome st...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒAndrew‚ôĒHernandez‚ôĒ‚ôĒIowa‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒPolicy Center for Maternal Mental Health‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒLast spring my sister was discharged from the hospital after a severe postpartum psychosis episode. Three weeks went by before her new psychiatrist could access her hospital records electronically. In that gap, he prescribed medications that dangerously overlapped with what she was already taking. She nearly suffered a serious adverse event that could have been prevented if one clinician could have securely shared critical information with another. That's not a regulatory failure in the abstract sense‚ÄĒthat's a near-tragedy that happens because systems don't talk to each other and clinicians operate blind.<br><br>I work in campaign strategy, which means I understand the impulse behind this deregulation proposal. Burden reduction sounds reasonable on its face. But I need to be direct about what concerns me: the RFI treats the absence of published outcome studies on AI model card disclosures as evidence that transparency requirements lack real-world benefit. That's backwards reasoning. These disclosures are too recent to have generated the kind of longitudinal clinical literature regulators seem to be waiting for. The fact that we don't yet have ten years of peer-reviewed data doesn't mean the transparency itself isn't preventing harm right now, in real clinics.<br><br>What troubles me most is the information asymmetry this creates. If we remove DSI certification criteria that mandate transparency about AI system limitations, training populations, and known risks before deployment, we're saying that developers bear less burden but patients and clinicians see less. That's not a fair tradeoff. People like my sister‚ÄĒvulnerable populations who depend on healthcare systems getting this right‚ÄĒdon't have the luxury of waiting for a developer's burden to ease while their safety depends on information they can't access.<br><br>I understand the deregulation framework. But accountability mechanisms that let patient advocates and providers identify and report AI failures in real time aren't overhead. They're the floor. You can innovate faster and still require that floor. The question isn't whether we need transparency standards. It's whether we're willing to admit that removing them costs something, and whether that cost is acceptable.<br><br>Remove burden where you can. But not here. Not on the mechanisms that keep clinicians from flying blind.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0060‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-18T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-18T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe Healthcare Leadership Council opposes deregulatory changes that would remove AI model card disclosure requirements and certification standards, arguing that transparency and accountability mechanisms are essential safeguards against data breac...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒEmily‚ôĒHarris‚ôĒ‚ôĒWashington‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒHealthcare Leadership Council‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒEmily Harris<br>Director of Government Affairs<br>Healthcare Leadership Council<br>Seattle, Washington<br><br>TO: Office of the Secretary, HHS; Office of the National Coordinator for Health Information Technology<br><br>RE: Request for Information ‚Äď Health Data, Technology, and Interoperability Deregulatory Actions<br><br>The Healthcare Leadership Council represents 44 of the nation's leading health systems and teaching hospitals. Our member institutions serve millions of patients annually and depend on functional, trustworthy health IT systems to coordinate care. We appreciate the opportunity to respond to this RFI, particularly because we've seen firsthand what happens when oversight mechanisms fall away.<br><br>Last year, one of our member hospitals in Spokane experienced a data breach that exposed patient records for over three weeks before detection. The cause, upon investigation, was straightforward: their security certification had lapsed. The compliance framework was so outdated and complex that the institution simply stopped maintaining it. No one was checking. When the breach occurred, patients were notified that they'd need credit monitoring services‚ÄĒsome for years. What troubles me most as I review this RFI is the direction of the proposed changes. We are being asked to consider removing certification standards at precisely the moment when we should be tightening them.<br><br>The DSI model card disclosure requirement is one of the few remaining transparency mechanisms that ensures both developers and deploying institutions remain accountable. When a hospital implements an AI system to support clinical decisions, patients and clinicians deserve to know whether a recommendation came from a human expert or an algorithm, and what that algorithm's documented limitations are. This isn't bureaucratic burden‚ÄĒit's informed consent. It's patient safety.<br><br>Regarding your question on which criteria should be revised to reduce burden while maintaining patient safety: we should not remove accountability requirements; we should strengthen the security infrastructure supporting them. Deregulation that strips transparency before we've fixed underlying data governance will simply recreate what we saw in Spokane at scale. Institutions will treat certification as optional. Patients will bear the risk.<br><br>We support innovation and market competition. We do not support removing one of the few mechanisms ensuring that innovation doesn't come at patients' expense. The model card requirement should remain.<br><br>Respectfully submitted,<br><br>Emily Harris<br>Healthcare Leadership Council<br>seattle@healthcarecouncil.org‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0061‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-07T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-07T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe commenter supports improved patient access to medical records across providers but emphasizes the need for transparency about how data is used, particularly regarding algorithmic decision-making, and robust security protections to prevent misuse.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒNancy‚ôĒKing‚ôĒ‚ôĒWashington‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy daughter had a car accident two years ago and the hospital lost her test results between departments. I spent three weeks calling around trying to get copies for her specialist. Now with her diabetes follow-ups, I wish I could just see everything in one place myself instead of always begging the doctors' offices to send things around.<br><br>But here's what worries me: if we make it easier for information to move around, we need to make sure patients know who's looking at it and why. When my daughter gets a recommendation from her doctor, I want to know if it came from a person or from some computer program. And what if that program gets something wrong? We need to be able to understand and track our own care.<br><br>I'm all for patients having better access to their records. Just please don't do it by cutting corners on security or by letting algorithms make decisions without telling us what they're doing.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0062‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-07T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-07T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe commenter supports health technology interoperability but opposes removing transparency requirements from DSI certification, arguing that model cards and detailed information about AI tools' intended use, failure modes, and training data are e...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒKaren‚ôĒSmith‚ôĒ‚ôĒOregon‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒNo Delays, No Surprises Coalition‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRe: Request for Information Related to Deregulatory Actions in Health Technology Certification and Interoperability<br><br>My mother saw three different rheumatologists and an orthopedist last year for her arthritis. None of their offices could share her test results electronically. We printed them out and physically carried them between buildings. When I asked one clinic about digital access so I could help coordinate her appointments and medications, I got a privacy lecture that felt less like patient protection and more like an excuse. That's when I realized we've somehow created a false choice between safety and access.<br><br>I'm writing because I'm watching this proposed rule, and I'm concerned we're solving the wrong problem.<br><br>The No Delays, No Surprises Coalition supports interoperability. We want systems to talk to each other. But I keep reading that the solution is to strip transparency requirements from DSI certification, and that doesn't make sense to me. My mother's care was fragmented because systems couldn't exchange data. But the reason hospitals are slow to adopt new AI tools isn't usually that there's too much information available‚ÄĒit's that there isn't enough reliable information to actually evaluate whether a tool works safely in their specific workflow.<br><br>Hospital procurement teams need to know what they're buying. They need model cards that explain intended use, target populations, known failure modes, and what data these systems were trained on. That's not regulatory burden. That's decision-making intelligence. When my mother's doctors finally got her records in the same place, coordinating her care took half the time.<br><br>Removing these transparency requirements doesn't streamline interoperability. It removes the information that lets health systems say yes or no responsibly. I'd ask the agency to consider keeping model card and transparency requirements for DSI tools while reviewing other duplicative certification steps. Real burden reduction doesn't mean less information; it means smarter, more focused requirements that actually help hospitals protect their patients while adopting new tools.<br><br>Thank you for considering this perspective.<br><br>Respectfully,<br><br>Karen Smith<br>Executive Director<br>No Delays, No Surprises Coalition<br>Portland, Oregon‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0063‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-22T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-22T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe Coalition for Health AI supports deregulation of AI certification requirements but opposes removing transparency standards like model cards, which provide health systems essential information about AI tool validation, performance limitations, ...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMelissa‚ôĒPerez‚ôĒ‚ôĒNevada‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒCoalition for Health AI (CHAI)‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRe: Request for Information on Health Technology Ecosystem Deregulatory Actions<br><br>The Coalition for Health AI appreciates the opportunity to respond to this RFI. We support streamlining burdensome certification requirements where appropriate, but we urge caution against removing transparency standards that health systems depend on to safely procure and integrate AI tools into clinical care.<br><br>My perspective on this comes from both research and family experience. Last year, my mother was diagnosed with early-stage diabetes. Her endocrinologist had to order the same tests twice because her records wouldn't transfer between clinics in the same health system. It was inefficient and worrying‚ÄĒthe kind of fragmented care that can delay diagnosis and burden patients. Now, working in health AI, I see the inverse problem: health systems are adopting AI tools without clear visibility into how those tools were built, what populations they work well for, and what risks they carry.<br><br>Model card disclosures‚ÄĒspecifications covering intended use, target populations, training data limitations, and known performance gaps‚ÄĒaren't bureaucratic overhead. They're decision-making data. When a hospital procurement team evaluates an AI tool for patient scheduling, sepsis prediction, or imaging analysis, they need to know whether the model was validated on their patient population, what happens when it encounters edge cases, and how it interacts with their existing workflows. A rural hospital serving a population with different comorbidity patterns than the validation cohort is making a different risk calculation than an academic medical center. Model cards let them make that calculation informed.<br><br>Removing transparency requirements doesn't reduce burden; it shifts burden onto health systems. It forces clinical leaders to either adopt tools blindly or invest their own resources reverse-engineering what vendors should have disclosed upfront. Responsible vendors with solid products have nothing to fear from transparency‚ÄĒit's actually a competitive advantage. The vendors cutting corners benefit from opacity.<br><br>Real world testing and attestation requirements are worth revisiting for streamlining, but not elimination. Consider a middle ground: allow vendors to satisfy validation requirements through a combination of premarket testing and real-world performance monitoring agreements, with clear timelines‚ÄĒsay, 90 days of deployment data rather than endless premarket trials. Health systems could commit to structured data sharing for accountability, and vendors get faster market access without sacrificing safety signals.<br><br>The stakes are patient safety and informed institutional choice. I don't want another family watching their mother's care fragment because the systems holding her data couldn't communicate. I also don't want hospitals adopting the next generation of diagnostic tools without understanding how they work. Transparency requirements and sensible attestation are how we get both.<br><br>Melissa Perez<br>Research Director<br>Coalition for Health AI‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0064‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-18T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-18T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒA parent of a child with type 1 diabetes opposes weakening AI certification and disclosure requirements in healthcare, arguing that transparency and accountability measures are essential patient protections rather than unnecessary burdens, especia...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMelissa‚ôĒAdams‚ôĒ‚ôĒArizona‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy daughter was diagnosed with type 1 diabetes last year, and I spent three weeks calling between my warehouse shifts just trying to get her test results from three different clinics so her new endocrinologist could actually see what was going on. Three weeks. I had to take time off work I couldn't afford to lose, and even then the clinics acted like I was asking for something unreasonable. Finally got everything in one place, and that's when I realized how much I didn't know about how these systems were making decisions about her care. Nobody explained it. The algorithms were just there, running in the background, and if something went wrong, I wouldn't even know it.<br><br>Now I'm hearing that you might be removing certification requirements for AI systems in healthcare, and I'm terrified. Removing model cards and detailed disclosures doesn't help people like me‚ÄĒit helps companies avoid accountability. Tech companies don't need less oversight; they need more. My daughter's health data is moving between systems, and right now at least there's supposed to be some check that the AI making recommendations about her insulin doses isn't a total black box. If you weaken those requirements, who's actually going to know what these systems are doing? Not me. Not her doctor if the company doesn't tell them.<br><br>I'm not asking for perfection. I'm asking that before you lighten the load on developers, you make sure patients still have some way to know what's being done with their information and how it's being used to make medical decisions. That's not a burden. That's basic protection.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0065‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-30T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-30T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒTMF Health Quality Institute opposes relaxing AI model card disclosure requirements in the proposed health IT deregulation, arguing that detailed transparency about clinical decision support tools' intended use, training data, validation methods, ...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒBrian‚ôĒRodriguez‚ôĒ‚ôĒSouth Carolina‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒTMF Health Quality Institute‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRE: Health Data, Technology, and Interoperability: ASTP/ONC Deregulatory Actions To Unleash Prosperity<br><br>TMF Health Quality Institute respectfully submits this comment on the proposed deregulatory framework for health IT certification and interoperability standards.<br><br>We support the goal of reducing unnecessary burden on developers and accelerating innovation. The current certification process does create friction, and we recognize that some requirements may be outdated. But I need to be direct about what concerns me most in these proposals: the relaxation of AI model card disclosures for clinical decision support tools.<br><br>My organization focuses on quality measurement and health IT adoption across Medicare and Medicaid programs. We work with health systems, payers, and vendors to understand how tools actually function in practice. What I've learned is that when systems fail silently‚ÄĒwhen a clinical algorithm makes a bad prediction and nobody knows why‚ÄĒthe damage compounds. A cardiologist might trust a risk score that was trained on a population that doesn't match her patient. A hospital might deploy a sepsis alert without understanding what patient characteristics it was designed for. These aren't hypothetical risks. We see them in implementation failures that cost money and, more importantly, delay care or lead to wrong decisions.<br><br>The proposed rule would allow developers to submit AI model cards with significantly less detail: intended use, target population, known limitations, training data characteristics, and validation processes would no longer be required elements of certification. The stated rationale is that this reduces compliance costs and lets innovation move faster. I understand that argument. But here's what troubles me: in healthcare, faster isn't always better if it means less visibility into how a tool behaves.<br><br>Let me be concrete. Last year, I watched a mid-sized health system implement a predictive model for hospital readmission. The vendor provided minimal documentation about which populations the model was validated on. When the system went live, it flagged certain groups of patients at disproportionately high risk‚ÄĒbut only because the training data had skewed patterns, not because those patients actually had worse outcomes. The health system wasted resources on interventions for the wrong people while missing real risk elsewhere. They discovered this only after three months and a frustrated quality officer dug into the model's behavior. If there had been upfront transparency about training data composition and validation cohorts, this would have been caught during planning, not after implementation.<br><br>That's why we believe the DSI certification criterion requiring detailed model card disclosures should be retained. Not because we want to slow down innovation, but because transparency is how clinicians and health IT teams build appropriate trust in tools. When a cardiologist knows that an AI model was validated on a diverse patient population and was tested on outcomes that matter in her setting, she can integrate it thoughtfully. When she doesn't know these things, she either ignores the tool or over-trusts it. Neither outcome is good.<br><br>We're also aware that some vendors will argue detailed model cards are expensive to produce. That's fair. But the alternative‚ÄĒdeploying tools with minimal understanding of their strengths and limitations‚ÄĒcreates costs downstream: implementation failures, wasted interventions, clinician skepticism, and ultimately slower adoption of tools that could actually help.<br><br>There's a middle path here. The rule could maintain the model card requirement but streamline the certification process in other ways‚ÄĒperhaps by allowing vendors to submit cards in a standardized format, or by extending timelines for review to reduce administrative burden without cutting substance. CMS and ONC could also provide clearer templates for what "sufficient detail" looks like, which would reduce the guesswork developers face.<br><br>I also want to note that this isn't just about compliance. When a vendor has taken the time to document what a tool is designed for, what populations it was tested on, and what its actual performance was, that work makes the tool better. It forces clarity. We've seen vendors discover gaps in their own validation processes while preparing documentation‚ÄĒand then they fix those gaps before deployment. That's a feature, not a bug.<br><br>The broader deregulatory push makes sense in many areas. But in clinical AI, where decisions affect patient care, the guardrails around transparency matter. Opening up data pipes and reducing friction is valuable. Lowering the bar on what developers have to tell us about how their tools work is a different choice, and I think it's the wrong one.<br><br>We urge HHS to retain the detailed AI model card disclosure requirement as part of DSI certification. We're happy to discuss implementation details or work with the agency on streamlining other parts of the process to offset any compliance burden.<br><br>Thank you for considering this comment.<br><br>Brian Rodriguez<br>Senior Policy Analyst<br>TMF Health Quality Institute<br>South Carolina‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0066‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-16T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-16T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe commenter opposes weakening regulations on AI use in healthcare, arguing that certification requirements and transparency standards for AI models are essential safety protections that should not be sacrificed for faster data sharing, even if t...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒSandra‚ôĒRobinson‚ôĒ‚ôĒWest Virginia‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy daughter's situation last year showed me how frustrating it is when medical records get stuck in limbo. But I'm worried that loosening up the rules around how doctors share patient information is going the wrong direction. We need better transparency, not less of it.<br><br>What concerns me most is that if we make it easier to hand over health data without proper checks, we're putting patients at risk. Doctors need to know exactly how AI systems work before they use them on patients‚ÄĒwhat they were trained on, who they're meant for, what problems they might have. That's not red tape. That's basic safety.<br><br>I understand companies want less regulation. But patient privacy and safety shouldn't be the trade-off. The certification requirements asking for detailed information about AI models exist for a reason. Keep them in place. Make the process work better if it's slow, but don't strip away the safeguards that protect us while we're trying to get our medical records transferred.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0067‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-25T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-25T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRural and under-resourced hospitals depend on model card disclosure requirements and algorithm transparency in EHR certification criteria to safely understand and validate the tools they deploy, and removing these requirements would exacerbate hea...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒAmanda‚ôĒFlores‚ôĒ‚ôĒSouth Dakota‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒHealthcare Leadership Council‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRE: Request for Information ‚Äď Health Data, Technology, and Interoperability: ASTP/ONC Deregulatory Actions<br><br>The Healthcare Leadership Council appreciates the opportunity to comment on this RFI. Our member hospitals serve rural and under-resourced communities across the country, and we support streamlining unnecessary regulatory burden. But I need to be direct: some requirements that may look like bureaucratic overhead from a developer's perspective are actually patient safety guardrails that our members depend on.<br><br>Last year, one of our member hospitals in South Dakota experienced a data breach involving patient records from a certified EHR system running on outdated infrastructure. The compliance officer was technically correct‚ÄĒwe were "doing everything right" according to the regulations. We had a certified product. We had attestations. We had documentation. What we didn't have was transparency into what the software was actually doing. When algorithms started flagging certain conditions for automated escalation, we couldn't explain why to our clinical teams. We couldn't audit the logic. And when families received breach notification letters, the gap between regulatory compliance and actual patient protection became painfully clear.<br><br>This matters for the certification criteria question. Model card disclosure requirements are not luxury features. They're the minimum needed to prevent hospitals from unknowingly deploying black-box systems that we can't understand or validate. Well-resourced health systems can afford to hire consultants or conduct independent audits of algorithm behavior. Rural hospitals like ours cannot. Removing transparency requirements doesn't level the playing field‚ÄĒit tilts it further. We get stuck with whatever certified-but-opaque tools we can afford, while larger systems vet algorithms independently. That's healthcare inequity baked into regulation.<br><br>We're not opposed to reducing burden on developers. But the reduction shouldn't come by making it easier for hospitals to adopt technology we don't understand. If certification criteria are revised, model card disclosure should remain a floor, not a luxury. Real-world testing and attestation can be streamlined through outcome-based standards rather than process-heavy documentation, but transparency into how algorithms work isn't process‚ÄĒit's patient safety.<br><br>Our members want to innovate and adopt new tools. We also need to know what we're deploying. These aren't in conflict.<br><br>Respectfully submitted,<br><br>Amanda Flores<br>Director of Government Affairs<br>Healthcare Leadership Council‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0068‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-22T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-22T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe Texas Medical Association opposes deregulation that would weaken interoperability and certification standards, arguing that while streamlining attestation processes is reasonable, removing mandatory interoperability testing would shift burden ...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒDaniel‚ôĒHill‚ôĒ‚ôĒSouth Carolina‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒTexas Medical Association‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRe: Request for Information ‚Äď Health Technology Ecosystem Deregulation<br><br>The Texas Medical Association appreciates the opportunity to comment on the proposed modifications to health IT certification and interoperability requirements.<br><br>Last year, my sister needed cardiac care coordination between Charlotte and Atlanta. Her cardiologist couldn't access previous EKG results from her earlier treatment, so they repeated the entire battery of tests. Six weeks passed. Thousands in out-of-pocket costs accumulated while insurance fought over what was "medically necessary." When I finally drove to Atlanta myself and retrieved the records in person, I learned the systems literally couldn't communicate‚ÄĒnot because the technology didn't exist, but because nobody was being held accountable for the failure.<br><br>That experience shaped how I think about this proposal. I understand the impulse to reduce burden on developers. Certification is expensive. But transparency requirements like AI model card disclosures exist precisely because accountability doesn't happen naturally in fragmented systems. Yes, we lack published outcome studies on disclosure standards‚ÄĒthey're new. But absence of evidence isn't evidence of absence. The real question is whether we can afford another decade of systems that don't talk to each other while we wait for perfect data.<br><br>On certification criteria: removing standards for interoperability testing would be a mistake, even if it reduces developer burden in the short term. What reduces burden for vendors increases burden for patients and providers who live with the consequences. We should instead streamline attestation requirements‚ÄĒmove toward outcome-based standards rather than process-based ones. Require developers to demonstrate interoperability works in real clinical settings within defined timeframes (48 hours for standard requests, 24 for urgent cases), rather than prescribing exactly how they build it.<br><br>Real-world testing should remain mandatory but could be simplified. Instead of multiple certification pathways, establish one clear standard: can your system exchange data with other systems in production? Can it do it reliably? Make developers prove it. That's not regulatory burden‚ÄĒthat's basic accountability.<br><br>What we cannot afford is deregulation that lets systems avoid responsibility for failures that harm patients. My sister's case wasn't unusual. It was just visible because I had the resources to chase it down myself.<br><br>Respectfully submitted,<br><br>Daniel Hill<br>Director of Government Affairs<br>Texas Medical Association<br>South Carolina‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0069‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒXSELL Technologies supports streamlining prescriptive certification requirements that slow innovation and disproportionately burden smaller vendors, but strongly opposes relaxing AI disclosure requirements, which should remain as essential safegua...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒStephanie‚ôĒJackson‚ôĒ‚ôĒTennessee‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒXSELL Technologies‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒXSELL Technologies appreciates the opportunity to comment on the ASTP/ONC deregulatory actions. Our organization develops interoperability modules for mid-market health systems, and we've observed firsthand how prescriptive certification requirements can inadvertently freeze innovation in place while imposing disproportionate costs on smaller vendors.<br><br>Last year we invested eight months and approximately $200,000 certifying an interoperability module only to see minimal market uptake. By the time we completed certification, the clinical environment had shifted and our client's actual needs had changed. That's not a criticism of the certification process itself‚ÄĒit exists for good reasons. But it crystallizes a real problem: the more detailed and prescriptive the requirements, the longer the timeline, and the greater the risk that the final product solves yesterday's problems. We watched competitors simply abandon product lines rather than absorb those certification costs. The market consolidated. The big players had teams to handle it. We didn't.<br><br>That said, there is one area where we think the current framework should be strengthened, not relaxed. The DSI certification criterion requiring detailed AI disclosures‚ÄĒintended use, target population, training data sources, validation methodology, known risks‚ÄĒneeds to stay. Healthcare AI adoption is accelerating rapidly. We're seeing vendors push algorithmic triage tools, predictive models for patient stratification, bias-prone training datasets that nobody's validating. The market isn't waiting for documented failures. We can't afford to remove guardrails before the problem becomes visible. Transparency requirements for AI models are not certification burden‚ÄĒthey're the baseline. Removing them proactively because AI adoption might create compliance headaches is exactly backward. The headache will be a patient safety incident nobody saw coming.<br><br>Our concern is straightforward: don't deregulate the emerging risks. Make the established processes faster where you can, but keep the disclosure requirements for technologies we don't fully understand yet. That's not caution. That's the lesson we should have learned from previous regulatory cycles.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0070‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-23T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-23T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒA former nurse argues that transparency requirements for AI systems in healthcare are essential for patient safety, warning that removing obligations to disclose how AI tools work and their testing data to clinicians undermines accountability and ...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒSusan‚ôĒSmith‚ôĒ‚ôĒOklahoma‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy daughter was diagnosed with Type 2 diabetes last year, and her doctor's office kept losing her test results between visits. When I finally got copies myself to take to a specialist, I realized they'd been sharing her information with some company I'd never heard of‚ÄĒwithout asking her permission properly. It just made me sick.<br><br>I spent 40 years as a nurse, and what I learned is this: patient safety depends on accountability and clear information. When doctors don't know how an AI system works or what risks it carries, they're flying blind. Removing requirements that show clinicians exactly what these tools do and how they were tested is dangerous. It's like asking a nurse to give a medication without knowing what's in it.<br><br>My worry is that stripping away transparency rules turns patients into guinea pigs. We lose the ability to ask questions or protect ourselves from algorithmic mistakes that could seriously harm us. Doctors need to see model cards and real-world testing data before they trust these systems with patient care. That's not a burden‚ÄĒthat's basic safety.<br><br>I know developers want less regulation, but not at the cost of patient protection. The answer isn't hiding how AI systems work. The answer is making sure doctors and patients have the information we need to say yes or no with our eyes open. That's what I'd want for my daughter.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0071‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-20T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-20T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe commenter opposes weakening AI transparency requirements, arguing that maintaining model card mandates is essential for protecting patient data security even while addressing legitimate delays in medical record access through other bureaucrati...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRichard‚ôĒKing‚ôĒ‚ôĒColorado‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy daughter has a chronic autoimmune condition, and last year when her pediatrician retired, the new doctor couldn't access her full test history for almost three months. We ended up repeating expensive lab work we'd already done just weeks before. That's when I realized how broken the system is‚ÄĒbut I also realized how much worse it could get if we're not careful about who has access to that data.<br><br>I keep hearing that loosening the transparency rules around AI systems will help speed things up. But here's what worries me: doctors and hospitals already don't understand how these AI tools work when they're using them on our kids. If you remove the requirements that make companies explain their AI models clearly, how am I supposed to trust them with my daughter's health information? I'm not asking for perfect security and instant access‚ÄĒI'm saying we need both.<br><br>The agency says there's no published evidence that these transparency rules help. Well, they've only been in place a short time. Studies take years. Meanwhile, families like mine are living with the consequences right now. We know when information gets lost in the system. We feel it.<br><br>Don't weaken the AI model card requirements just to reduce burden on developers. Fix the bureaucratic delays that are the real problem. Keep the transparency rules in place while streamlining access. We shouldn't have to choose between safety and speed.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0072‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-27T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-27T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRemoving AI certification and transparency requirements risks accelerating vendor consolidation by pricing out smaller competitors who cannot absorb compliance costs internally, while large vendors will maintain oversight anyway‚ÄĒa pattern already ...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒJames‚ôĒAnderson‚ôĒ‚ôĒNew Mexico‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒbeHuman Corp.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒbeHuman Corp. appreciates the opportunity to comment on the proposed certification and deregulation framework. As a health system operator, I've watched how compliance burden in health IT certification directly translates to vendor consolidation and reduced choice for hospitals like ours.<br><br>Last year we renegotiated our EHR contract‚ÄĒ$2.3 million renewal‚ÄĒand the vendor explicitly tied their price increase to compliance and certification costs. They told us those expenses get passed downstream. What struck me was watching smaller competitors simply disappear from our procurement process. They couldn't compete on price because they lack the compliance infrastructure of larger incumbents. We ended up with fewer options and higher costs, which defeats the whole purpose of removing regulatory burden.<br><br>I'm concerned the same pattern will repeat if we remove AI certification criteria without thinking through the market effects. The DSI transparency requirement for AI models exists because we're still learning what these tools do at scale in clinical settings. That's not bureaucratic box-checking‚ÄĒthat's the gap between what gets discovered in controlled validation and what actually happens when your algorithm runs on three years of messy patient data. Removing that requirement now doesn't reduce burden equally. Large vendors absorb the cost of maintaining internal AI oversight anyway. Smaller innovators get priced out of the market entirely because they can't justify that investment without certification requirements driving demand.<br><br>I'm not arguing against streamlining real bottlenecks. But removing transparency requirements for AI specifically seems backward when adoption is accelerating and we have limited real-world performance data. If anything, proactive disclosure now prevents the documented failures that will force much heavier-handed regulation later.<br><br>What I'd actually propose: keep the AI model card disclosure requirement but clarify what's attestable versus what requires independent testing. That reduces the compliance burden without creating a regulatory vacuum that only large vendors can navigate.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0073‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-31T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-31T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe commenter supports streamlined health data sharing to improve patient access but opposes deregulation of health AI systems, arguing that transparency requirements for AI documentation‚ÄĒincluding intended use, limitations, and validation methods...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMelissa‚ôĒJohnson‚ôĒ‚ôĒWyoming‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe experience I had last year trying to get my medical records transferred to a rheumatologist in Denver made me think a lot about how we handle health information. I had X-rays taken at my local clinic here in Wyoming, and getting those films to Denver turned into a three-week ordeal. Three phone calls. A fax machine that barely cooperates. My daughter finally just drove up and picked up the physical films herself because the clinic couldn't send them electronically or wouldn't‚ÄĒI'm still not entirely sure which. It cost us gas money and a full day of her time.<br><br>So when I see proposals to make data sharing easier, I get it. I really do. But here's what keeps me up at night: my brother had someone get into his Medicare account two years ago. They ran up charges before he even knew what happened. It took him months to sort out. After that, I started paying attention to how my information moves around, and honestly, the more I learn, the more concerned I get.<br><br>The thing is, I want access to my own records. I want to be able to share them with whoever I need to see. That part makes sense and would've saved us real problems. But I don't want that convenience to come at the cost of having nobody actually checking whether the systems handling my data are safe. Right now, when a company builds health AI tools or systems that work with patient information, they have to show their work‚ÄĒexplain what the tool is designed to do, who it's meant for, what problems they found during testing, where the training data came from. That transparency matters to me. It's not a bureaucratic box to check. It's how I know someone actually thought through the risks before my information goes into their system.<br><br>I've watched enough happen in the last couple years to know that deregulation doesn't always mean things get better. Sometimes it just means problems happen faster and nobody catches them until patients like me get hurt. I'm not opposed to innovation. I'm opposed to the idea that we should make it easier to build and deploy health technology without being clear about how it works and what could go wrong.<br><br>My recommendation is straightforward: keep the requirement that AI models used in healthcare come with detailed documentation. Let companies know what they need to disclose‚ÄĒtheir intended use, the population the tool is meant for, known limitations, how they validated it. That's not burdensome. That's responsible. And it's the difference between a system I might trust with my medical information and one that I'd worry about.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0074‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-28T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-28T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒHealthcare providers need transparency requirements for AI tools to make informed decisions about patient safety, as removing certification disclosures that mandate companies disclose intended uses and known risks would leave hospitals unable to p...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒCarol‚ôĒMiller‚ôĒ‚ôĒPennsylvania‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy grandson had a bad asthma attack at school last year, and I had to drive around to three different doctor offices just to get his medical records printed out so the hospital could see what medications he was on. Took me most of an afternoon. I kept thinking there's got to be a better way for doctors to just share information with each other about a patient's care, but now I'm worried that if we strip away the rules that make companies be honest about what they're doing, hospitals won't know if these new AI tools are actually safe for kids like my grandson.<br><br>Here's what concerns me: when hospitals are buying these tools to help manage asthma cases or any patient care, they need clear information about what the tool does and who it's supposed to work for. Right now, the certification requirements make companies tell hospitals exactly what data the tool uses and what its known problems are. Without that transparency, how is a hospital supposed to know if it's safe to use for their patients? They'd be flying blind.<br><br>I'm not against companies making tools that help doctors work better. I just don't want hospitals choosing software without understanding what they're getting or how it works. The certification disclosures‚ÄĒwhere companies have to explain their intended use and known risks‚ÄĒthose aren't just bureaucratic boxes to check. They're how hospitals make good decisions for people like my grandson.<br><br>Please don't remove the requirements that make companies be transparent about what these tools do and who they're safe for.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0075‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-30T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-30T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe American College of Surgeons opposes the removal of detailed AI model card disclosure requirements from health IT certification criteria, arguing that transparency about intended use, target populations, risks, and validation processes is esse...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒDonna‚ôĒSanchez‚ôĒ‚ôĒCalifornia‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒAmerican College of Surgeons‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe American College of Surgeons thanks the Office of the National Coordinator and the Assistant Secretary for Technology Policy for this opportunity to comment on the proposed modifications to the Health Data, Technology, and Interoperability certification criteria. We have substantial concerns about the proposed removal of detailed AI model card disclosure requirements, particularly the provisions requiring documentation of intended use, target population, known risks, training data characteristics, and validation processes. Our position stems not from opposition to innovation or market competition, but from direct observation of what happens when those safeguards erode in clinical practice.<br><br>Two years ago, I retired from UC San Francisco after 28 years working in health services research and biostatistics. My last major project before leaving documented the interoperability failures across our hospital system's three competing EHR platforms. We submitted three separate grant applications to understand how vendors' refusal to share data schemas was affecting patient safety outcomes. None were funded. What remained clear to me, however, was this: when physicians can't see a complete picture of a patient's medical history across systems, they duplicate diagnostic testing, miss critical context, and occasionally make treatment decisions that could have been different if the information had been available and transparent. The problem wasn't complexity. It was opacity. Vendors had no incentive to reveal how their systems worked or what data they held.<br><br>That experience shaped how I think about the proposed rule changes, especially regarding AI model transparency in clinical decision-support tools and other high-stakes applications. The certification criteria requiring detailed model cards aren't bureaucratic overhead. They're the clinical equivalent of requiring surgeons to document their operative techniques, complication rates, and patient selection criteria. They're foundational to trust, and trust is what allows tools to be adopted in the first place.<br><br>Let me be direct about what concerns me. The proposed deregulation assumes that market competition and vendor reputation will naturally incentivize transparency and safety disclosure. In my experience, that assumption doesn't hold in healthcare. Vendors compete on speed to market and feature sets, not on transparency about model limitations. A hospital system evaluating two competing AI-based triage tools will choose based on cost, integration ease, and vendor support relationships‚ÄĒnot because one vendor provided exhaustive documentation of the populations on which the model was trained or the failure modes that might emerge in low-resource settings. Once the tool is adopted, changing course is expensive and disruptive. By then, the opportunity to make an informed decision based on model documentation has passed.<br><br>The model card requirement serves three distinct functions that the proposed rule seems to conflate with unnecessary regulation. First, it enables clinical adoption. Surgeons and hospital administrators need to understand the bounds of a tool's applicability. If an AI model for predicting surgical site infections was trained primarily on data from large teaching hospitals, we need to know that before implementing it in a community hospital with different patient demographics, different surgical volume, and different post-operative monitoring capabilities. I've watched clinicians reject tools not because they were ineffective, but because they couldn't verify that the tool had been validated in populations like theirs. Transparency accelerates adoption. Opacity breeds appropriate skepticism.<br><br>Second, model cards create accountability. When something goes wrong‚ÄĒand in clinical AI, something eventually will‚ÄĒthere needs to be a traceable record of what the developers claimed the tool could do, what populations it was tested on, and what risks were disclosed. This isn't about litigation; it's about learning. If an AI model fails to flag a particular patient subgroup at high risk, we can't improve the system if we don't know whether that failure represents a gap in the training data, a gap in the validation process, or a genuine limitation of the modeling approach. Documentation enables the feedback loop that makes systems safer over time.<br><br>Third, and perhaps most important, model cards protect patients. A patient has a right to know when a decision affecting their care was informed by an algorithmic tool, what that tool's track record is, and what gaps in its knowledge or applicability might exist. Right now, many patients don't even know when AI is involved in their care. The certification requirement for detailed disclosure doesn't eliminate algorithmic bias or algorithmic error‚ÄĒthose are problems that require ongoing technical work‚ÄĒbut it makes those problems visible and addressable.<br><br>The College recognizes the legitimate concerns about regulatory burden on developers and the desire to accelerate innovation. We're not arguing that every health IT tool requires the same level of scrutiny. But the distinction the rule should draw is between different risk levels and use cases, not between disclosure and non-disclosure. An AI model that recommends a diagnostic imaging study operates in a different risk environment than one that optimizes surgical scheduling or manages supply chain logistics. The certification criteria should be tiered accordingly. Remove burdensome requirements for low-risk applications. Strengthen them for high-stakes clinical decisions.<br><br>What we're reading in the proposed rule,‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0076‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-15T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-15T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒA parent of a child with Type 1 diabetes opposes weakening AI transparency and oversight rules in healthcare, arguing that removing requirements for companies to explain how their AI systems work will make it impossible for doctors to catch errors...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒDonna‚ôĒWhite‚ôĒ‚ôĒVirginia‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy daughter has Type 1 diabetes and managing her care means I need her blood sugar records from her pediatrician's office. This has been a nightmare. I've been asking for months to get her data in a format I can actually use so I can share it with her specialist across town, and they keep telling me their system won't let them do it. Now I'm hearing that the rules about how these AI systems work might get weaker, and honestly that scares me more than it helps.<br><br>Here's what worries me. If you remove the rules that say companies have to explain how their AI systems work and how they've been tested, doctors won't know what these systems are actually doing. My daughter's data could be anywhere. When I ask questions about who's looking at her medical information, nobody can tell me because nobody's really watching. These tech companies could be using her data however they want and there's nothing stopping them.<br><br>I already can't get my daughter's records in a format I can use. Weakening the oversight rules will just make it easier for tech companies to hide what they're doing. Doctors need to know how these AI systems work so they can catch mistakes that could hurt kids like mine. Please don't remove the transparency requirements. My daughter's safety depends on somebody actually watching what happens with her information.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0077‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-14T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-14T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe commenter opposes weakening transparency and testing requirements for hospital AI systems, arguing that rigorous upfront safety measures‚ÄĒincluding model cards and real-world testing‚ÄĒare essential to protect patients, just as firefighters prior...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒLisa‚ôĒJohnson‚ôĒ‚ôĒVermont‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒLast year my daughter had to spend weeks fighting a hospital just to get copies of my medical records after my heart attack. They kept saying they needed forms I didn't have, that the paperwork was too complicated, that it was a burden to pull my own information together. Meanwhile I'm the one sitting there in the dark about my own health.<br><br>Now I'm watching the same thing happen again with these AI systems in hospitals. The rule says we can weaken the requirements that companies have to be transparent about how their AI works‚ÄĒabout testing it, about proving it's safe. And they're using the exact same excuse: it's too much of a burden.<br><br>I spent 40 years as a firefighter. We don't wait for a building to burn down before we install sprinklers. We put them in first. We test our equipment before we use it. We follow the rules because people's lives depend on us doing our job right. That's what safety means. It means burden. It means saying yes to the work upfront so nobody gets hurt.<br><br>Removing model card requirements and real-world testing before hospitals put AI systems on patients‚ÄĒthat's not streamlining. That's deciding to wait for the disaster instead of preventing it.<br><br>My daughter deserves better. Every patient deserves a hospital that knows exactly what its AI is doing, and proves it before patients become the experiment.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0078‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-27T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-27T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRemoving model card disclosure requirements for clinical AI systems will shift transparency burdens to individual health systems rather than eliminate them, forcing costly vendor negotiations and potentially compromising patient safety‚ÄĒparticularl...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThomas‚ôĒRivera‚ôĒ‚ôĒMassachusetts‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒAVIA Nexus Collaborative‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒLast spring, my team at AVIA Nexus Collaborative was trying to track diagnostic delays across three hospitals in the same metro area. We had IRB approval, institutional buy-in, and months of research design work behind us. What we didn't have was access to the data we needed‚ÄĒnot because the hospitals wouldn't share it, but because each vendor's licensing terms and proprietary data formats made even basic interoperability technically impossible. We spent more time negotiating with EHR vendors than we did on the actual research question. What should have taken three months took eighteen.<br><br>I'm concerned that removing model card disclosure requirements for AI systems will replicate exactly this problem at the clinical level. Right now, when a hospital procurement team or clinical IT department evaluates whether an AI tool is safe and appropriate for their patient population, they have the ability to request and review data on training datasets, validation methods, and known performance gaps. This matters. It matters especially for vulnerable populations where representativeness in training data directly affects diagnostic accuracy. Our hospitals serve a majority-minority population, and we've seen how off-the-shelf clinical algorithms can underperform when they haven't been adequately tested on patient demographics like ours.<br><br>If we remove the requirement that vendors disclose this information in a structured, standardized way, we don't remove the need for it‚ÄĒwe just push the burden downstream. Health systems will either have to negotiate model cards individually with every vendor, creating a fragmented and expensive landscape, or they'll accept tools without knowing how those tools perform in their specific contexts. Neither outcome improves innovation or reduces burden. It recreates the licensing and opacity problems that already exist in EHR interoperability, now in the AI layer.<br><br>I'd suggest that instead of removing model card requirements, the agencies consider whether the current certification criteria can be streamlined or whether attestation processes can be simplified without eliminating the transparency that health systems depend on to evaluate safety. The burden on developers isn't really the documentation‚ÄĒit's the vendor lock-in and proprietary protection that makes that documentation feel risky to share. That's a different problem to solve.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0079‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-08T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-08T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe commenter opposes removing transparency and certification requirements from health IT systems, arguing that such deregulation prioritizes vendor convenience over patient safety by allowing deliberate incompatibility and hiding algorithm perfor...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒDeborah‚ôĒHernandez‚ôĒ‚ôĒLouisiana‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒAlliance for Connected Care‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe Alliance for Connected Care respectfully submits this comment on the proposed deregulatory actions affecting health information technology certification and interoperability standards.<br><br>My mother's experience last month illustrates exactly why we cannot strip transparency requirements from this system. She was discharged from Ochsner on December 3rd with an atrial fibrillation diagnosis. Her cardiologist at LSU‚ÄĒwho needed to adjust her medications based on her hospital discharge summary‚ÄĒspent three weeks fighting with incompatible systems just to get partial records. Meanwhile she was on a medication regimen that may have been inappropriate, administered by clinicians working blind because the certified systems vendors refused to talk to each other.<br><br>That delay wasn't a burden on vendors. It was a burden on my mother. And it happened because the infrastructure supposed to prevent exactly this kind of fragmentation has been allowed to atrophy.<br><br>I understand the argument that certification requirements slow vendors down. But the question buried in that complaint is: slow them down from doing what? From locking in customers through deliberate incompatibility. From hiding how their algorithms work. From building systems that prioritize their market position over clinician access to safety information. Those aren't innovations we should be removing barriers to.<br><br>Model card disclosures‚ÄĒthe performance data, validation studies, and risk assessments that come with certified health IT products‚ÄĒaren't a vendor burden. They're the floor of what clinicians need to understand whether an algorithm might harm their patients. When you remove that requirement, you're not reducing burden. You're eliminating accountability. You're saying vendors don't have to tell clinicians what their tools actually do or how they might fail.<br><br>That's deregulation aimed at the wrong target. The burden that matters here isn't on certification. It's on patients waiting for records, clinicians making decisions in the dark, and hospital systems that can't talk to each other because vendors built them that way on purpose.<br><br>If you want to reduce burden on developers, revise the real-world testing timelines. Simplify attestation paperwork. But don't remove the transparency requirements. They're not anti-competitive regulation. They're basic patient safety infrastructure.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0080‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-19T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-19T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒA veteran nurse argues that transparency requirements for clinical AI systems‚ÄĒincluding model cards detailing validation populations, known failure modes, and risk data‚ÄĒare essential safety tools for responsible clinical practice and should not be...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMichael‚ôĒClark‚ôĒ‚ôĒUtah‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒAfter 38 years as a nurse, I've learned that good patient care runs on information. Last year my daughter needed her thyroid labs reviewed by an endocrinologist, and it took two weeks and three phone calls just to get copies from different clinics in one folder. I kept thinking how much better that could've been with easier access to her own records. But I've also seen what happens when patient information gets loose or incomplete‚ÄĒI've caught medication errors, algorithmic failures, and diagnostic mistakes because someone actually had access to the full clinical picture.<br><br>What worries me now is that loosening transparency requirements on AI systems could swing the pendulum too far the other way. Model cards aren't bureaucratic busy-work. They're safety tools we need at the bedside. When I'm using an algorithm to help screen for sepsis or predict patient decline, I need to know what populations it was actually validated on. Was it tested on patients like the ones I'm caring for, or just on data from three large academic centers? What are the known failure modes? Does it miss certain demographics? Without that information, we're flying blind. We don't know if the system has blind spots that could harm our patients.<br><br>The certification criteria around AI transparency‚ÄĒthe detailed disclosures about intended use, target populations, known risks‚ÄĒthose should stay. Reducing burden on developers shouldn't mean reducing what clinicians see. We need the same performance and risk data developers used to build these systems. That's not extra burden. That's just the information required to practice medicine responsibly.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0081‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-20T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-20T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒWhile supporting improved medical record portability to ensure continuity of care, the commenter warns against loosening security and transparency requirements for AI systems that handle sensitive health information, arguing that certification sta...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒAmanda‚ôĒClark‚ôĒ‚ôĒNorth Dakota‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy grandson's cardiologist situation last month really brought this home to me. When the family moved to Minnesota, the new office couldn't get his records for three weeks. Three weeks where they were starting over on medications and history with no real continuity. The office manager explained the old system made it deliberately hard to transfer files, supposedly for security, but at least everyone knew where the safeguards were.<br><br>Now I'm reading that we're loosening up how records move between providers, and I understand why that matters‚ÄĒno family should go through what we did. But here's what keeps me up at night: if we make it easier to pass around medical information, who's actually verifying that the places receiving it have real security in place? It's not enough to say the files are portable. They need to stay protected. I've worked in libraries long enough to know that access and safety aren't opposites, but they do require oversight. Before we remove certification requirements that spell out how AI systems work‚ÄĒwhat they're designed for, who they're tested on, what can go wrong‚ÄĒwe should think hard about what we're giving up. Those disclosures aren't bureaucratic busywork. They're how doctors and patients know whether to trust the system handling sensitive information. Easy data sharing is good. But not if it means we stop asking hard questions about security and accountability on the receiving end.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0082‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒHospitals must maintain strict transparency and certification requirements for AI tools in patient care, including detailed model cards and safety evaluations, because removing these protections allows companies to deploy untested systems on patie...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒStephanie‚ôĒDavis‚ôĒ‚ôĒFlorida‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy granddaughter is fourteen years old. Last year her insulin pump data got hacked through an app that promised better tracking. Nobody could tell me who was responsible, how it happened, or what her medical information was being used for. I spent thirty years as a floor nurse, and I can tell you: when patient records stay locked up tight, people get better care and fewer things go wrong.<br><br>Now I'm hearing that hospitals might be asked to deploy AI tools for patient care without really knowing how those tools were built or what they're designed to do. That's backwards. Hospitals need detailed model cards and transparency requirements so their procurement teams can actually evaluate whether something is safe before they use it on patients. When companies hide how their AI was trained, patients become test subjects instead of getting informed care.<br><br>My concern is this: removing certification requirements doesn't help patients. It helps companies skip the hard part of proving their tools are safe. Hospitals can't make smart decisions about deploying AI if they don't have real information about how it works. And patients like my granddaughter can't consent to being part of an experiment they don't even know is happening.<br><br>The certification criteria exist for a reason. Don't strip them away.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0083‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-27T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-27T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRemoving AI model card disclosure requirements from data sharing and interoperability certification would undermine clinician trust and informed adoption of healthcare tools, as hospitals and health systems need standardized transparency about how...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒDaniel‚ôĒSmith‚ôĒ‚ôĒIdaho‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒAlliance for Connected Care‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy mother was in St. Luke's in Boise for five days last month with a serious infection, and I watched the ER doctor actually pick up the phone to call her cardiologist's office to request a fax of test results from 2022. In 2024. Her previous records were locked in systems that don't communicate with each other, and it took four additional hours to get her the right antibiotics because no one could access her full medical history. She was scared. I was furious. But I also understand why people worry about privacy and security in healthcare data. That said, watching someone you care about suffer because hospitals can't exchange information is a different kind of risk than a theoretical data breach.<br><br>The Alliance for Connected Care has spent the last several years working with patient advocates, providers, and health systems on exactly these questions‚ÄĒhow do we move data between systems safely and meaningfully? And what I've come to understand is that transparency in how AI and algorithmic tools work in healthcare is not opposed to interoperability. It's foundational to it. If we strip away the requirement that developers disclose detailed model cards‚ÄĒthe intended uses, target populations, known risks, training data characteristics, validation processes‚ÄĒwe don't actually get faster innovation. We get faster adoption of tools that no one understands and that clinicians won't trust.<br><br>I want to focus specifically on the proposal to remove or modify the Data Sharing and Interoperability certification criterion requiring detailed AI model card disclosures. I know the framing is about reducing burden on developers. But the practical effect would be that hospitals and health systems implementing these tools would have no standardized way to understand what they're actually deploying. And that's a direct threat to the interoperability we're all trying to achieve.<br><br>Here's the thing that keeps bothering me about the deregulatory approach: interoperability without transparency creates a false choice. Yes, certification takes time and costs money. Yes, it creates friction in the development process. But the alternative isn't actually faster innovation‚ÄĒit's innovation that doesn't get adopted because clinicians don't trust it. I've talked to IT directors at three major health systems in Idaho and Oregon, and they've all said the same thing: they won't implement a clinical decision support tool or data exchange mechanism if they can't explain to their physicians how it works and what its limitations are. That's not regulatory burden. That's professional responsibility.<br><br>The model card requirement exists because healthcare isn't a market where you can iterate fast and fail cheap. When an algorithm fails in healthcare, people don't get refunded. They get harmed. My mother's case was straightforward‚ÄĒan infection that needed antibiotics. But what if the system failure had been in a diagnostic tool? What if she'd been triaged incorrectly because an AI system hadn't been validated on populations with her particular risk factors?<br><br>The certification criterion we're discussing isn't just about checking a box. It requires developers to document intended use, which means they actually have to think about who the tool is designed for and what it should and shouldn't do. It requires disclosure of known risks, which means there's a record of what was understood at the time of deployment. It requires information about training data and validation processes, which is the only way a hospital can make an informed decision about whether the tool is appropriate for their patient population.<br><br>I understand the argument that this is prescriptive and that markets should decide what information is necessary. But healthcare markets don't work that way. Hospitals don't have perfect information. Physicians are time-constrained. And patients have no visibility into how algorithmic tools are making decisions about their care. The certification criterion isn't preventing competition‚ÄĒdevelopers can still innovate and bring tools to market. They just have to be transparent about what they've built.<br><br>What I'm asking for is simple: keep the DSI certification criterion requiring detailed AI model card disclosures. Not because we should be hostile to innovation or because developers are bad actors. They're not. But because transparency is how we actually build the trust and understanding necessary for interoperability to work in practice. My mother's problem wasn't solved by deregulation. It was solved by a doctor making a phone call and a medical records clerk finding a fax machine. That's not the future we're building toward.<br><br>If we remove the model card requirement, we're saying that interoperability is more important than understanding what's being shared and how it's being used. That's backwards. Interoperability is only valuable if the systems we're connecting are trustworthy and their limitations are known. The certification process isn't preventing that. It's ensuring it.<br><br>I know this isn't the main focus of the deregulatory proposal, and I know there are legitimate concerns about regulatory burden. But this particular criterion is worth preserving. Patient safety in an increasingly AI‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0084‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-19T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-19T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRemoving AI model card disclosure requirements would paradoxically harm smaller healthcare vendors like RubyWell by allowing larger competitors to rely on brand reputation instead of transparency, ultimately undermining clinician autonomy and pati...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒDorothy‚ôĒBrown‚ôĒ‚ôĒVermont‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒRubyWell, Inc.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒAs Chief Medical Officer of RubyWell, I want to flag a specific concern about the proposed removal of AI model card disclosure requirements under the deregulatory framework. This isn't a burden complaint dressed up as safety advocacy‚ÄĒit's the opposite problem.<br><br>Last spring we launched an interoperability module and spent six weeks just parsing existing certification requirements to ensure we weren't accidentally blocking data exchange. That's time we couldn't spend on clinical decision support. A larger vendor absorbs those costs across their entire product line. We had to choose. But here's what troubles me: if we'd been building an AI-enabled feature alongside that interoperability work, and if the rule removed model card requirements, we wouldn't have saved time. We would have lost credibility with the clinicians we sell to.<br><br>A hospital system can't safely integrate a black-box algorithm into their workflows. They need to know the model's performance on their population, failure modes, validation dataset characteristics‚ÄĒnot because they're regulators, but because they're liable when something goes wrong. Right now, if we don't provide that documentation, they ask harder questions. We actually *need* the requirement because it's the language we use to explain to them why they can trust the tool.<br><br>Remove that requirement and what happens? Larger vendors can market on brand reputation alone. Healthcare systems will default to them because the reputation substitutes for transparency. Smaller vendors like us get squeezed out because we have to prove ourselves with documentation while competitors sell opacity.<br><br>The question about which certification criteria should be revised‚ÄĒI'd say this one shouldn't be. Any AI transparency requirements should stay because they're not really compliance infrastructure; they're the foundation of clinician autonomy. Clinicians need to know what they're deploying into their workflows. That's not burden reduction; that's patient safety.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0085‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-21T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-21T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒAVIA Nexus Collaborative opposes relaxing AI model transparency requirements in health IT certification, arguing that model cards documenting intended use, target populations, and validation processes are essential for clinician trust and safety r...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒJames‚ôĒWhite‚ôĒ‚ôĒColorado‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒAVIA Nexus Collaborative‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ# Comment on ASTP/ONC Deregulatory Actions<br><br>AVIA Nexus Collaborative appreciates the opportunity to comment on the proposed revisions to health IT certification criteria. We work at the intersection of research and implementation‚ÄĒour lab develops interoperability tools for resource-constrained clinics, and we've spent the last two years trying to navigate certification requirements that were designed for vendors with compliance budgets, not academic research teams.<br><br>That said, I want to be direct about something that concerns me in the proposed deregulation framework: the language around loosening AI model transparency requirements in DSI certification. I understand the impulse to reduce burden. We felt that burden acutely when we shelved our cross-platform EHR sharing tool last year. But the specific criterion requiring detailed model cards‚ÄĒdocumentation of intended use, target population, known risks, training data characteristics, and validation processes‚ÄĒdoes something that matters in clinical contexts, and I'm not convinced removing it actually accelerates anything useful.<br><br>Here's the tension as I see it. We spent eighteen months building a tool that let three rural Colorado practices share patient data without proprietary middleware. It was technically sound. Then the licensing requirements shifted, and suddenly we needed six figures in legal review just to certify it. That's a real problem. But the solution isn't to assume that transparency requirements are the bottleneck. They're not. The bottleneck was legal risk assessment and vendor lock-in concerns that transparency, ironically, could have helped with.<br><br>I watched what happened next: a larger firm released essentially the same tool, but integrated into their ecosystem. Their model didn't have better security or accuracy. They just had the capital to absorb the compliance cost. That's not innovation. That's consolidation.<br><br>The model card requirement isn't theoretical. When we were designing our tool, we had to be explicit about which patient populations our algorithms were validated against. We used data from two of the three pilot sites and external validation on a third. We documented that our EHR deduplication logic performed differently in practices with older EHR systems versus newer ones. We identified that our data mapping assumptions broke down for certain medication classes. That work didn't slow us down‚ÄĒit made the tool better. And crucially, it meant the clinicians using it knew what they were getting.<br><br>The reason I'm pushing back on relaxing this particular criterion is that AI in healthcare isn't like other software. When a clinical decision support system makes a recommendation, or when an algorithm flags a patient for follow-up, clinicians need to know whether that output was validated in populations that look like theirs. They need to understand what training data was used. They need to know what the system was designed to do versus what it might accidentally do. This isn't regulatory theater. It's the difference between a tool you can trust and one you're essentially gambling with.<br><br>I'm not arguing for more burden. I'm arguing for keeping the requirement that does actual work. If the problem is that smaller organizations can't afford the legal review around compliance, then maybe the solution is streamlining the certification process itself‚ÄĒclearer guidance, faster review timelines, reduced fees‚ÄĒrather than removing the transparency requirement that actually helps clinicians and researchers like us understand what we're implementing.<br><br>What bothers me is that the deregulation proposal seems to assume that transparency requirements are what's holding back innovation. In my experience, they're not. What held us back was the cost of proving we'd complied with every possible requirement, many of which were redundant or unclear. The model card criterion was the one thing that actually made sense. It forced us to think clearly about our own limitations. And it would have made it easier to explain to clinics why they should use our tool instead of waiting for the next vendor with deeper pockets.<br><br>I understand the broader goal here: reduce unnecessary burden, let the market work, encourage competition. I'm sympathetic to that. But if we remove the one transparency requirement that actually helps clinicians understand AI systems, we're not reducing burden‚ÄĒwe're just redistributing it. We're making it so that only organizations large enough to absorb reputational risk from deploying poorly understood systems can compete. That's the opposite of what you're trying to achieve.<br><br>AVIA Nexus would welcome the opportunity to discuss this further or to serve as a test case for a streamlined certification pathway that preserves model transparency while reducing legal overhead. We think there's a middle path here that doesn't sacrifice the transparency that matters while still addressing the real compliance costs that slowed us down.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0086‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-22T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-22T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRebecca Allen argues against removing AI certification requirements in healthcare, particularly model cards that document algorithm testing and limitations, because vulnerable patients like elderly individuals lack the means to verify whether deci...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRebecca‚ôĒAllen‚ôĒ‚ôĒTexas‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒMCG Health, part of the Hearst Health network‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRebecca Allen<br>MCG Health Community Outreach<br>Texas<br><br>Re: Request for Information ‚Äď Health Data, Technology, and Interoperability: ASTP/ONC Deregulatory Actions<br><br>I want to speak to something that happened to my family last spring, because I think it matters for how we think about speed versus safety in health technology.<br><br>My mother was admitted to Baylor Scott & White with what looked like a simple UTI. It turned into sepsis. When she was discharged, her primary care doctor needed her records to follow up on her recovery and monitor for complications. I spent three weeks‚ÄĒthree weeks‚ÄĒcalling between different departments trying to get those records transferred. One place told me they needed written authorization. Another said the system was "down." A third person asked me to come in person with her ID. Nobody could explain why it was so difficult to move a CD from one doctor's office to another in the same healthcare network. That's when I started paying attention to how fragmented health systems really are.<br><br>But here's what worries me now about moving faster without better safeguards: my mother is exactly the kind of patient who gets hurt when we prioritize speed over documentation. She's 82, she has multiple conditions, and she doesn't have the energy to second-guess whether an algorithm recommending her care has actually been tested properly. She trusts the system. She doesn't have time to figure out if some new AI tool deciding her treatment was validated by anyone who knew what they were doing.<br><br>I understand the argument that certification requirements slow things down. They do. But when I ask which standards should actually be removed, I keep coming back to model cards. These aren't bureaucratic checkboxes‚ÄĒthey're plain-language explanations of what an AI system can and cannot do, how well it was tested, and who it was tested on. For vulnerable patients, especially older people and people in underserved communities, model cards are how you know someone checked before putting a tool into real patient care.<br><br>What I'm asking the agency is: before you remove certification criteria, ask yourselves whether vulnerable patients like my mother have *any* way to know if the algorithms making decisions about their care have been properly vetted. If the answer is no, then maybe we don't rush to reduce those requirements, even if it means slower adoption.<br><br>I'm not opposed to innovation. I'm opposed to systems that move fast and assume patient safety will somehow take care of itself. It won't. Not for people without advocates. Not for people who are sick and tired and just want to trust their doctors.<br><br>Respectfully,<br><br>Rebecca Allen<br>Community Organizer<br>MCG Health‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0087‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-15T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-15T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒWhile acknowledging the need for improved data sharing between healthcare providers, the commenter warns against reducing transparency and explainability requirements for AI systems in medical settings, arguing that patients must understand how al...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒJames‚ôĒHall‚ôĒ‚ôĒIowa‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy wife Margaret was diagnosed with diabetes two years ago, and I've been her caregiver ever since‚ÄĒmanaging her doctors, her medications, all of it. Last month I tried to get copies of her lab results from three different clinics so we could show her new specialist what we already knew. Took me almost six weeks of calling around just to piece it together. So yes, I understand why people say we need better data sharing between doctors. That part makes sense to me.<br><br>But here's what worries me. If you strip away the requirements that make these computer systems explain how they work, patients like my wife won't know whether a recommendation is trustworthy or whether the system has blind spots that could hurt her. Right now, when a doctor tells her something, she can ask why. She can push back. But if some algorithm is making decisions in the background and nobody has to tell us how it works or what might go wrong with it, we're defenseless.<br><br>I'm not against making things easier for software companies. But "reducing burden" shouldn't mean hiding how AI systems think. Margaret needs to know when a computer is influencing her care, not just get told the system says so without any explanation. That's not about slowing down innovation. That's about keeping my wife safe. Don't trade away transparency just to make developers' jobs easier.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0088‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-31T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-31T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe South Carolina Primary Health Care Association supports reducing unnecessary regulatory burden on developers but opposes removing AI model card disclosure requirements, arguing that documented performance boundaries and known limitations are e...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒSharon‚ôĒClark‚ôĒ‚ôĒTexas‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒSouth Carolina Primary Health Care Association‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒLast spring, I sat across from a patient at our clinic in Charleston‚ÄĒshe'd been bouncing between three different providers for six months, each operating in separate systems, before we finally pieced together that her recurring symptoms stemmed from a medication interaction nobody had caught. She'd nearly given up. That experience crystallized for me why interoperability matters so much, but it also made me deeply aware that we can't solve fragmentation by simply opening data flows without knowing what we're connecting.<br><br>The South Carolina Primary Health Care Association supports this RFI's effort to reduce unnecessary regulatory burden. We get it‚ÄĒcertification requirements can be duplicative, and developers shouldn't waste resources on compliance theater. But I want to be direct about something that concerns me: the move to remove AI model card disclosure requirements. This isn't a burden we should shed.<br><br>Here's the practical problem. When our clinicians adopt an AI-based clinical decision support tool, they need to know what that tool has actually been tested on, where it performs well, where it fails, and what known risks exist. A model card isn't a checkbox on a compliance form‚ÄĒit's a clinician's window into whether that tool is appropriate for their patient population. Without it, we're flying blind. We can't detect algorithmic bias before it reaches our patients. We can't identify when a tool's validation study doesn't match our population's demographics. We can't catch the edge cases where performance degrades.<br><br>Interoperability gains mean nothing if the systems being integrated lack documented performance boundaries. We risk scaling not just efficiency but also algorithmic error and bias across fragmented care networks. That's the opposite of what we want.<br><br>I'm not opposed to streamlining other certification criteria. There are probably standards that duplicate each other or outdated requirements that slow deployment without adding safety value. But transparency about AI performance‚ÄĒabout what validation was done and what the known limitations are‚ÄĒthat's foundational safety infrastructure. It enables rather than blocks innovation by building clinician confidence.<br><br>The question really is: which burden actually matters? Developers spending time documenting their models' performance boundaries, or clinicians and patients bearing the consequences of adopting systems they don't fully understand? I'd argue the former is a cost of responsible innovation, not a barrier to it.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0089‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-12T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-12T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPolymorphic, Inc. opposes removing AI model card disclosure requirements, arguing that while redundant certification processes warrant streamlining, eliminating transparency mandates would shift uncompensated safety validation and liability burden...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒStephanie‚ôĒMoore‚ôĒ‚ôĒIowa‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒPolimorphic, Inc.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPolimorphic, Inc. appreciates the opportunity to comment on the proposed deregulatory actions. As a health IT vendor supporting hospitals across the Midwest, we recognize the genuine burden that redundant certification processes create. Last month our compliance team spent three days rebuilding attestation documentation for a certification we already held‚ÄĒsame functionality, same vendor, completely unnecessary work while our smaller competitors received blanket extensions. That frustration is real and deserves attention.<br><br>But I need to be direct about something: the proposal to remove AI model card disclosure requirements would fix the wrong problem. It would trade visible compliance costs for invisible safety costs that hospitals absorb downstream.<br><br>Here's the operational reality. When we deploy a diagnostic decision support tool‚ÄĒsay, for sepsis prediction in our Iowa facilities‚ÄĒour clinicians need to know what data trained that model, how it performs across different patient populations, and what failure modes we should be watching for. Right now that information comes through model cards. They're not optional; they're how our clinical team decides where to apply the tool, which cohorts might see degraded performance, and how to set alert thresholds. Without them, we're asking nurses and physicians to implement safeguards blind.<br><br>What concerns me most is the burden shifting. Remove the transparency requirement and vendors save money. But our hospital doesn't save anything‚ÄĒwe just inherit uncompensated risk management. We still need to validate the algorithm's behavior. We still need to audit its outputs. We still get sued if it fails. The documentation requirement doesn't create that obligation; it just makes the vendor's validation work visible instead of hiding it in proprietary systems.<br><br>I'm frustrated by redundant recertification cycles, but that's a different problem. The fix isn't to remove transparency requirements for AI-based tools. It's to streamline recertification pathways for functionality that hasn't materially changed. That distinction matters because patient safety in algorithmic decision-making is not deregulatory overhead‚ÄĒit's operational infrastructure.<br><br>We'd support removing certification criteria that duplicate vendor testing or create unnecessary delays without safety rationale. But removing clinician visibility into algorithmic performance would shift uncompensated liability onto hospital staff already stretched managing interoperability and information blocking compliance. That's not burden reduction; it's cost transfer.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0090‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-30T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-30T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRemoving AI model card disclosure requirements will entrench market dominance by major vendors while eliminating the transparency mechanisms that allow smaller labs and academic researchers to demonstrate safe, competitive alternatives‚ÄĒparticularl...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThomas‚ôĒYoung‚ôĒ‚ôĒTennessee‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒRune Labs‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRemoving AI model card disclosure requirements will effectively guarantee that dominant vendors consolidate the market further while hiding the algorithmic performance data that smaller labs and researchers need to demonstrate competitive alternatives. I've watched this dynamic play out firsthand over the past eighteen months.<br><br>Last year, my team at Rune Labs submitted a grant proposal to develop an open-source interoperability standard for neurological device data. The kind of work that should let smaller labs compete on equal footing with established players. Reviewers rejected it outright, citing fragmentation concerns and market risk. Three weeks later, one of the major vendors announced they'd acquired a competing startup and immediately locked down their API behind proprietary licensing. No one called that consolidation a threat to innovation. No one asked about market fragmentation then.<br><br>That asymmetry matters because transparency requirements are the only mechanism preventing vendors from using deregulation as cover for entrenchment. When you remove model card disclosure, you're not reducing burden equally‚ÄĒyou're eliminating the single tool that lets academic researchers and independent developers demonstrate that our systems are safe and interoperable. Clinicians cannot detect algorithmic bias in high-stakes domains like neurology without access to training data characteristics, validation processes, and documented failure modes. When a proprietary black box fails on a patient population the vendor didn't adequately test, no one sees it coming because no one can see inside.<br><br>I understand the impulse to streamline certification. But the burden reduction argument systematically favors incumbents who can afford proprietary systems. Open-source alternatives and academic research depend on the transparency standards that level the playing field. Remove those requirements and you don't accelerate innovation‚ÄĒyou ensure that only vendors with existing market power can afford to operate.<br><br>Real-world testing and attestation requirements should remain intact, particularly for neurology and other high-stakes domains. The question isn't how to eliminate transparency; it's how to make disclosure requirements proportional to risk while preserving the standards that prevent algorithmic harm. I'd welcome working with ONC to pilot a tiered disclosure model that reduces documentation burden for lower-risk applications while maintaining clinical visibility into model performance across patient populations.<br><br>What concerns me most is that deregulation framed as innovation will simply entrench the consolidation I've already experienced. That's not burden reduction‚ÄĒthat's market capture.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0091‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-10T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-10T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒCloudflare opposes the removal of AI model card disclosure requirements from health IT certification standards, arguing that while some deregulation is appropriate, transparency about algorithmic decision-support tools is essential for patient saf...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒSharon‚ôĒRamirez‚ôĒ‚ôĒArizona‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒCloudflare Inc‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRe: Health Data, Technology, and Interoperability: ASTP/ONC Deregulatory Actions To Unleash Prosperity<br><br>Cloudflare appreciates the opportunity to submit comments on the proposed deregulatory framework for health IT certification and interoperability standards. Our perspective comes from direct experience managing the operational and compliance infrastructure that hospitals depend on to deliver care, and from conversations with health system leaders across the country who are grappling with the real costs of fragmented regulatory guidance.<br><br>I want to be direct about something that concerns me: the proposed removal of the detailed AI model card disclosure requirement in the Data Summary and Interoperability certification criterion. I understand the impulse to reduce certification burden‚ÄĒbelieve me, after last year's $400,000 EHR compliance effort, I get it. But I think this particular deregulation moves in the wrong direction for patient safety, and I want to explain why.<br><br>Let me start with what we're actually talking about. The current DSI criterion requires vendors to disclose, for any algorithmic decision-support tool integrated into certified EHR systems, specific information: the intended use case, the target population the model was developed and validated on, known performance limitations and risks, characteristics of the training data, and details about the validation process. This isn't theoretical stuff. When a hospital implements an AI-assisted sepsis detection tool or a readmission risk prediction model, clinicians need to know whether that model was trained on populations that look like their patients, what happens when it fails, and what the actual false positive rate is in practice.<br><br>The proposal suggests that vendor discretion and market forces will ensure adequate transparency. I'm skeptical of that, and here's why: health systems don't have the technical capacity to reverse-engineer or independently validate machine learning models. We can evaluate whether a FHIR endpoint works correctly. We can test whether data comes back in the right format. We cannot look at a black-box model and determine whether it's safe to use in our patient population. The asymmetry of information between vendors and health systems is profound. And unlike a CRM system or a billing platform‚ÄĒplaces where errors are inconvenient and costly‚ÄĒerrors in clinical decision support can harm patients.<br><br>Over the past eighteen months, I've watched our clinical teams struggle with exactly this problem. We implemented a vendor's length-of-stay prediction model in 2022. It was certified. It looked fine on paper. But six months in, our quality team noticed the model was systematically overestimating length of stay for patients over 75, which skewed resource allocation and created problems for discharge planning. We contacted the vendor. They told us the model was trained on data from three large academic centers with relatively young populations. That information was not disclosed at implementation. It should have been. We spent weeks figuring this out ourselves. A patient didn't die‚ÄĒthank God‚ÄĒbut the risk was real, and preventable disclosure would have caught this faster.<br><br>Here's what I think gets lost in the deregulation framing: removing the model card requirement doesn't actually reduce burden on vendors in a meaningful way. It shifts burden to health systems. We end up doing the validation work ourselves, or worse, we don't do it and we deploy models we don't fully understand. That's not innovation. That's risk transfer.<br><br>I also want to separate this from the legitimate deregulation efforts in the proposal that make sense. Streamlining USCDI data class definitions, revising the prescriptive technical standards that lock vendors into specific versions of FHIR or HL7‚ÄĒthose changes can reduce friction without sacrificing safety. The field has matured enough that we can trust vendors to implement standards competently without micromanaging the technical approach. But AI model transparency isn't the same category. We're not talking about implementation flexibility. We're talking about whether clinicians can make informed decisions about whether to use a tool.<br><br>What would a better approach look like? I'd propose keeping the model card requirement but streamlining it. Instead of demanding a 40-page technical document, require a structured disclosure: intended use, target population characteristics, validation metrics in a standard format, known limitations. Make it machine-readable if possible. Allow vendors to update it as they refine models. This is not burdensome. It's the cost of deploying tools in a regulated healthcare environment. And frankly, vendors who have done solid validation work have nothing to hide‚ÄĒthey want to showcase it.<br><br>There's also a secondary issue worth mentioning. The proposal mentions clarifying "information blocking" regulations, particularly around vendor-imposed restrictions on data access. I support that effort, genuinely. But I'd want to make sure the clarification doesn't inadvertently create pressure to remove model cards in the name of preventing vendors from "blocking" access‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0092‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-28T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-28T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒA former nurse argues that transparency requirements for AI tools in healthcare should be strengthened rather than weakened, warning that removing detailed model disclosures will leave doctors and administrators unable to make informed decisions a...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒSarah‚ôĒAllen‚ôĒ‚ôĒArkansas‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy daughter is a teacher in Memphis. Last month her primary care doctor ordered thyroid labs and said the results would be ready in a few days. When they came back, the clinic told us they couldn't send them to her new doctor because "the system won't allow the transfer." Three weeks. For three weeks she sat there not knowing if she needed medication, not knowing what her levels were, just waiting while two offices pointed at their computers and said there was nothing they could do.<br><br>That's what happens when nobody's checking on the details. And I'm worried this new rule is going to make that worse, not better.<br><br>Here's what I kept thinking about during those three weeks: somebody in that clinic had to decide whether to put this AI tool or that one into their workflow. Did they know what it was trained on? Did they understand which kinds of patients it actually works for? Did they know what could go wrong? I spent thirty years as an RN, and I watched hospitals buy systems because they were cheap or promised quick fixes, and patients paid the price when things didn't fit right.<br><br>If you take away the requirement for detailed model information‚ÄĒthe transparency about what these tools are designed to do, who they work for, what the risks are‚ÄĒthen doctors and hospital administrators are making those decisions blind. They're flying on faith instead of facts.<br><br>Keep the disclosure requirements. Let the people running these systems actually know what they're putting into patient care.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0093‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-23T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-23T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒAI model transparency requirements‚ÄĒspecifically model cards documenting intended use, target populations, limitations, and validation data‚ÄĒshould not be weakened in DSI certification criteria, as they are essential preventive infrastructure to pre...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒJames‚ôĒHall‚ôĒ‚ôĒSouth Dakota‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒAmerican College of Cardiology‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒTwo years ago, while consulting on a cardiac outcomes registry at Mayo, I watched a patient's critical arrhythmia history disappear between systems. The rural clinic used a legacy EHR that couldn't communicate with the hospital's newer platform. The cardiologist had to make a treatment decision‚ÄĒone that could have meant the difference between stable management and a stroke‚ÄĒwith half the clinical picture missing. That gap wasn't just inefficient. It was dangerous.<br><br>What struck me then, and what concerns me now as we discuss DSI certification criteria, is that we're at risk of repeating that mistake at a much larger scale. The pressure to remove AI model transparency requirements feels like the same logic that said, "Well, systems work fine if they're siloed," until they don't.<br><br>I want to be direct: I don't think establishing AI model card requirements‚ÄĒdetailed disclosure of intended use, target population, known risks, training data characteristics, and validation processes‚ÄĒis regulatory burden. It's preventive infrastructure. It's what any responsible developer should be doing anyway. The question isn't whether to require this information; it's whether we're willing to let algorithms operate in clinical workflows without it.<br><br>Here's what worries me about weakening these criteria. In cardiac care, we've learned the hard way that you can't diagnose what you can't see. An AI model deployed without transparent documentation of its limitations is like that fragmented EHR‚ÄĒit creates a different kind of blind spot, but the consequences are the same. A model trained primarily on data from younger patients might miss presentations in elderly populations. One validated on a specific subset of arrhythmia types might fail on others. These aren't hypothetical risks; they're documented failure modes from other algorithmic deployments in medicine.<br><br>The RFI asks which certification criteria should be removed to reduce burden. My answer is: not the transparency ones. If anything, tighten them. What you might reconsider are requirements that duplicate existing FDA oversight or that impose identical burdens regardless of clinical impact, but the model card requirement isn't one of those. It's the floor, not the ceiling.<br><br>What I'd actually support is streamlining *real world testing* pathways for developers willing to commit to that transparency. Make the trade-off explicit: faster approval in exchange for detailed algorithmic disclosure and post-market surveillance requirements. That's how we reduce burden without creating new diagnostic gaps.<br><br>The patients I saw at Mayo deserved to have complete information available to their care team. The ones who'll use AI-assisted diagnostic tools deserve the same thing.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0094‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-15T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-15T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe commenter opposes loosening AI certification rules, arguing that transparency requirements like model cards are essential safeguards for patient safety, particularly when healthcare providers already struggle with basic interoperability and re...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒEdward‚ôĒKing‚ôĒ‚ôĒWest Virginia‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMy daughter was diagnosed with Type 1 diabetes last year, and we've been through three different doctors trying to get her insulin levels right. Every time we switch providers, they can't access her records without me begging for them. It's like starting over each visit, and I'm terrified something important gets lost in the shuffle‚ÄĒsomething that could actually hurt her.<br><br>What worries me most about loosening certification rules is this: if we're already struggling to get doctors to share basic records with each other, how are we supposed to trust them with AI tools we don't understand? My daughter's care depends on her doctor knowing what the algorithm is actually doing and what it might miss. Model cards‚ÄĒthose transparency requirements‚ÄĒare the only thing that tells us what the AI was trained on and where it could fail.<br><br>I get that developers find regulations burdensome. But cutting corners on AI transparency isn't the answer. When you're managing a serious condition like diabetes, you need your doctor to understand the tools they're using, not just trust a black box. Model card certification isn't excessive burden‚ÄĒit's basic safety.<br><br>Please don't remove the certification criteria that require transparency around AI tools. For patients like my daughter, that visibility is everything. We can't afford to lose it while we're still waiting for our records to actually talk to each other.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0095‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-08T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-08T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒWhile health data interoperability is essential to prevent fragmentation-related harms, eliminating transparency requirements like model cards would dangerously shift risk onto vulnerable patients by allowing AI systems to be deployed without clin...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒAshley‚ôĒRamirez‚ôĒ‚ôĒNorth Dakota‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒSouth Carolina Primary Health Care Association‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒRe: Request for Information ‚Äď Health Data, Technology, and Interoperability: Deregulatory Actions<br><br>Last month I was sitting in a clinic coordinator's office in Rapid City while she made her fourth call trying to get records from a specialist's office two blocks away. A patient‚ÄĒsomeone I've worked with for two years on managing her chronic conditions‚ÄĒwas waiting at home wondering why her appointment kept getting delayed. Nobody had her imaging results. Nobody had her lab work. The records existed. They just couldn't talk to each other. That experience crystallized something I've been worried about: we need interoperability desperately, but not at the cost of the safeguards that keep vulnerable people safe.<br><br>I direct policy for the South Carolina Primary Health Care Association, and most of our patients are the ones who've been hurt by healthcare systems before‚ÄĒrural populations, low-income families, people from communities where trust in medical institutions is thin to begin with. When we push hard for better data sharing, we're doing it because fragmentation kills. But I'm also terrified that if we strip away transparency standards in the rush to innovate, we'll hand developers a blank check to deploy AI systems that clinicians can't understand and patients can't question.<br><br>Model card requirements aren't bureaucratic overhead. They're a patient safety mechanism. When a developer documents what their algorithm actually does, who it was trained on, what edge cases break it, and what can go wrong‚ÄĒthat information matters. It matters to a rural clinician trying to decide whether to trust a diagnostic recommendation. It matters to a patient asking whether an algorithm trained mostly on data from urban teaching hospitals will work for her. Right now, we don't have many tools to answer those questions. Model cards are one of the few.<br><br>The black box problem is real. I've watched clinicians either blindly defer to AI recommendations because they have no way to verify them, or ignore them entirely because they can't understand the reasoning. Neither outcome serves patients. Removing detailed transparency requirements won't speed up deployment‚ÄĒit'll just move the risk onto people like the woman in Rapid City, who has no power to push back.<br><br>I'm asking you not to eliminate model card requirements. I understand the burden on developers. But interoperability without transparency is a trade we can't afford to make.<br><br>Respectfully,<br><br>Ashley Ramirez<br>Policy Director<br>South Carolina Primary Health Care Association‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0096‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-22T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-22T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒWhile supporting improved medical record transfers, the commenter warns against weakening transparency requirements for health information systems, arguing that detailed disclosures about how AI tools and software function are essential for ensuri...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMelissa‚ôĒYoung‚ôĒ‚ôĒDelaware‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒAfter working with patients for nearly fifty years, I've seen what happens when medical information doesn't move between doctors the way it should. But I've also seen what happens when it moves too fast without anybody checking. Last month Mrs. Chen's daughter couldn't get her hospital test results for three weeks. When they finally came through, there was a medication allergy listed wrong‚ÄĒcould have been serious.<br><br>Now I hear they want to make records transfer easier, which sounds good on paper. But easier shouldn't mean less careful. What worries me is if we strip away the requirements for companies to explain how their systems work, what they're designed for, what risks they actually have. Right now when a hospital uses new AI tools or record-sharing software, someone has to document all that‚ÄĒthe training data, the known problems, who it's meant for. That transparency is what lets doctors and nurses know whether to trust it.<br><br>I'm not against progress. I'm for it. But you can't build something solid on a foundation you're not checking anymore. If we remove the requirement for detailed disclosures about how these systems work, we're just hoping nothing goes wrong. And in healthcare, hoping isn't enough. The people using these tools‚ÄĒand the patients depending on them‚ÄĒdeserve to know what they're working with.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0097‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-01-07T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-01-07T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe National Council for Prescription Drug Programs opposes weakening AI model disclosure requirements in health IT systems, arguing that detailed transparency about algorithm design, validation, and limitations is essential for patient safety and...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒBetty‚ôĒMartinez‚ôĒ‚ôĒIllinois‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒNCPDP - National Council for Prescription Drug Programs‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒFebruary 18, 2025<br><br>Office of the National Coordinator for Health Information Technology<br>U.S. Department of Health and Human Services<br>330 C Street SW<br>Washington, DC 20201<br><br>RE: Public Comment on Health Data, Technology, and Interoperability: ASTP/ONC Deregulatory Actions<br><br>Dear ONC Leadership,<br><br>The National Council for Prescription Drug Programs appreciates the opportunity to comment on the proposed deregulatory framework. We recognize the genuine desire to reduce unnecessary burden on health IT developers and support innovation that serves patients and providers. At the same time, we have significant concerns about specific proposals that would weaken data security transparency requirements, particularly around artificial intelligence model disclosures in pharmacy systems and health information exchanges.<br><br>Our organization represents pharmacy networks, data stewards, and patient advocates across the country. We work every day with the real consequences of data breaches and inadequate security practices in healthcare. Last year, I watched what happened to my neighbor when her pharmacy switched to a new system without proper safeguards. Her diabetes information was shared with supplement companies and clinics she'd never heard of. She started getting calls at home. She was terrified, not just about privacy, but about what it meant that no one seemed to be checking whether these new systems were actually safe before they went live. That's what pushed me and our coalition to focus on this issue.<br><br>The specific concern we have is about the proposal to remove or significantly weaken the detailed AI model card disclosure requirement under the Data Security and Integrity (DSI) certification criterion. The current rule requires health IT developers to disclose intended use, target population, known risks, training data characteristics, and validation processes. This isn't bureaucratic overhead. It's foundational to patient safety.<br><br>Let me explain why this matters in concrete terms. When a pharmacy system uses AI to flag potentially dangerous drug interactions, or when a hospital uses algorithms to route patient information, those decisions affect real people. If the algorithm was trained on data from a particular demographic and doesn't perform well for others, clinicians and pharmacists need to know that. If the system has known limitations with elderly patients taking multiple medications, that's critical information. Right now, the model card requirement ensures that information gets documented and reviewed before deployment. Without it, we're essentially asking healthcare workers to trust algorithms they can't examine.<br><br>I understand the argument that requiring detailed disclosures slows down product development and adds cost. Those are real concerns. But the cost of getting it wrong is also real. A pharmacy system that misidentifies contraindications for an older patient could cause serious harm. A hospital interoperability platform that loses or corrupts patient records creates liability for everyone involved. And from a market perspective, healthcare providers actually want transparency. They're liable for the systems they adopt. Hospitals and pharmacy chains aren't going to implement an AI system if they can't verify it's been properly validated.<br><br>What we're asking is that you retain the current DSI certification requirement for detailed AI model card disclosures. Not as a burden, but as a baseline standard for systems that handle sensitive health information. Here's why this makes sense:<br><br>First, transparency supports clinical adoption. Hospitals and pharmacies will use these systems more confidently if they can review validation data and understand known limitations. That actually accelerates innovation because developers can market their products more effectively.<br><br>Second, it creates accountability. When something goes wrong, regulators, providers, and patients need to understand how the system was built and what it was designed to do. Model cards establish a clear record.<br><br>Third, it protects developers too. If a system fails in the field and there's no documentation of its intended use or validation approach, liability falls on the developer. Clear disclosure actually reduces risk for responsible companies.<br><br>I know there are other deregulatory proposals in this RFI, and some of them probably make sense. We're not against all change. But data security and AI transparency in healthcare systems aren't the right places to cut corners. These aren't legacy burdens from a bygone era of regulation. They're responses to real failures and real vulnerabilities that we're still seeing today.<br><br>Our pharmacy networks process millions of prescriptions a week. We see the gaps in system security, the interoperability problems that cause delays and errors, and the patient impact when data moves without proper safeguards. We also see what happens when new systems are deployed without adequate validation. Removing transparency requirements doesn't make those problems go away. It just means we find out about them after patients are affected instead of before.<br><br>I'd also note that the current DSI certification criterion isn't preventing innovation. New pharmacy systems, hospital platforms, and interoperability solutions are being developed and deployed all the time. Developers are meeting the current standards and bringing products to market. The requirement hasn't stalled the industry. What it has‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0098‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2026-02-02T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2026-02-02T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThe American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists argues that while developer compliance costs warrant reduction, eliminating transparency requirements for clinical AI tools would undermine health systems' ability to make informed procuremen...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ1‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒMichael‚ôĒNelson‚ôĒ‚ôĒColorado‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒThe American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒOn behalf of The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists, I want to address the tension between reducing developer burden and maintaining the decision-making infrastructure that health systems depend on when deploying clinical AI tools.<br><br>Last year I was collaborating with colleagues at CU on a maternal mortality study across three hospital systems. We needed to track outcomes across their electronic health records, and what should have been straightforward data integration turned into a three-month standoff. One system's EHR couldn't export data in formats our pipeline could process. Another claimed contractual restrictions prevented sharing. The third lacked the technical capacity entirely. Meanwhile, the information we needed to identify preventable deaths was locked in proprietary silos. This isn't unique to our research‚ÄĒit's how health systems operate across the country.<br><br>What concerns me about broad deregulation is that it conflates two separate problems. Developers genuinely do face compliance costs. But transparency requirements around model deployment‚ÄĒwhat we'd call disclosure of intended use, target populations, validation methodology, and known performance gaps‚ÄĒaren't bureaucratic overhead. They're procurement infrastructure. When a hospital's maternal health leadership evaluates whether to adopt an AI tool for risk stratification, they need to know whether validation included patients like theirs, whether the tool was tested in their specific clinical context, and what failure modes have been documented. Without standardized disclosure requirements, health systems lose the ability to compare tools systematically or to negotiate implementation terms with confidence.<br><br>I'd suggest a narrower approach: preserve certification criteria that establish meaningful interoperability benchmarks and require vendors to disclose model performance data relevant to clinical implementation. Strip away redundant documentation requirements that don't affect end-user decision-making. Real-world testing should be proportional to risk, not formulaic. But removing transparency requirements altogether will deepen the exact data fragmentation that has already cost us months of lost research time and, more importantly, delays evidence-based adoption of tools that could prevent maternal deaths.<br><br>The ACOG membership is ready to collaborate on pilot programs that stress-test these requirements against actual procurement workflows.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0099‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒA health IT vendor compliance officer argues that proposed removals of detailed AI model card disclosure requirements should be reconsidered, as these safeguards are essential for clinician decision-making and patient safety in healthcare settings...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒNancy‚ôĒMitchell‚ôĒ‚ôĒCalifornia‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒBroadspire, Inc.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒThank you for the opportunity to comment on the proposed modifications to health IT certification requirements. I'm writing from the perspective of someone who works in compliance at a mid-sized vendor, and I've spent enough time in the trenches to know what's at stake when we talk about reducing certification burden.<br><br>My team manages compliance for our EHR integration services, and last year we spent three months‚ÄĒfull three months‚ÄĒjust documenting our procedures for a single client audit. That's time we could have spent fixing bugs, improving our clinical workflows, or actually talking to end users about what they need. I watched that happen and kept thinking about the smaller vendors we work with, the ones without a dedicated compliance officer, wondering how they're supposed to navigate this landscape at all. So I get it. I really do understand the appeal of streamlining requirements.<br><br>But here's what concerns me, and I need to be direct about this: there's a difference between reducing unnecessary bureaucracy and removing safeguards that actually matter. The proposed removal of detailed AI model card disclosures‚ÄĒthe requirements around intended use, target population, known risks, training data characteristics, and validation processes‚ÄĒfeels to me like we're solving the wrong problem.<br><br>Let me explain why I think we need to keep those disclosure requirements, even if they feel burdensome.<br><br>Three months ago, we were working with a health system in Northern California implementing an AI-assisted diagnostic tool. Before we even deployed it, the clinical leadership wanted to understand what population it was validated on, what the known failure modes were, what kinds of edge cases we'd documented. This wasn't some regulatory checkbox they were worried about. They had liability concerns, patient safety concerns, and frankly, they wanted to know if the tool was actually going to work for their patient population‚ÄĒwhich is predominantly older, with higher rates of comorbidities than the training dataset. Without that model card information, they would have had to do their own validation work anyway, which would have taken longer and cost more. But because we had documented all of that up front, they could make an informed decision in weeks instead of months.<br><br>That's the thing about AI in healthcare. It's not like traditional software where you can discover issues through user feedback and push out patches. When an AI model fails in a clinical setting, you're not just annoyed about a glitchy interface. You're potentially talking about a misdiagnosis. You're talking about a provider who was relying on a tool that performed differently than expected. You're talking about liability, patient harm, and loss of trust in the whole system.<br><br>The vendors who are pushing hardest to remove these requirements‚ÄĒand I say this as someone in the vendor community‚ÄĒthey're mostly the ones who can afford to absorb the cost of documentation anyway. They already have the infrastructure. What concerns me is that if we strip away the model card requirements, we're not actually reducing burden equally across the industry. We're creating a situation where smaller vendors either have to do the documentation anyway to be competitive, or they cut corners and produce less transparent products. And then the health systems have to do extra work to figure out whether they can trust what they're deploying.<br><br>I've also seen what happens when transparency breaks down. We had a client last year‚ÄĒnot one of our products, but a competitor's tool‚ÄĒthat was supposed to work for a specific patient population. The vendor had never actually validated it on that population. The health system found out after deployment when the accuracy numbers didn't match what they'd been told. The vendor claimed the documentation wasn't clear, the health system claimed they'd asked the right questions, everyone lost time and money and trust, and ultimately the tool was pulled.<br><br>The AI model card requirements exist because healthcare is different. It's not like consumer software where you can iterate fast and break things. The stakes are higher. And the clinicians who are going to use these tools‚ÄĒthey need to know what they're working with. They need to understand the boundaries of what the AI can do, what population it was validated on, what the known risks are. That's not regulatory theater. That's patient safety.<br><br>Now, I'm not saying the current certification process is perfect. There are definitely places where we're creating documentation requirements that don't add value. There are redundancies. There are things we could streamline without compromising safety. I'd like to see us look at whether we're duplicating effort across different certification bodies, or whether we're asking for information in five different formats that could be consolidated. Those conversations are worth having.<br><br>But when it comes to AI transparency‚ÄĒwhen it comes to knowing what we're putting into clinical practice‚ÄĒI think we need to be more careful. I think we need to keep the requirement for detailed model cards. Maybe we can standardize the format to make it easier to produce. Maybe we can create templates that vendors can use to speed up the‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
CMS-2025-0050-SYNTH-0100‚ôĒCMS‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Submission‚ôĒ2025-12-31T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒComment on CMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ2025-12-05T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ2026-02-03T00:00:00Z‚ôĒfalse‚ôĒCMS-2025-0050‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2025-12-31T00:00:00Z‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPolymorphic, Inc. argues that AI model card disclosure requirements should be retained and clarified rather than relaxed, as they serve a critical patient safety function by forcing vendors to systematically validate their algorithms and answer cl...‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPublic Comment‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ2‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒJoseph‚ôĒAllen‚ôĒ‚ôĒNevada‚ôĒ‚ôĒUnited States‚ôĒPolimorphic, Inc.‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒPolimorphic, Inc. welcomes the opportunity to comment on the proposed modifications to health IT certification criteria and information blocking regulations. As a mid-sized vendor serving health systems and ambulatory practices across the Mountain West, we have direct experience with the compliance friction that accumulates when regulatory guidance shifts or remains ambiguous. That experience shapes our perspective on what clarity and stability actually mean in practice.<br><br>Over the past eighteen months, we've invested substantially in our current system architecture‚ÄĒroughly $2.3 million in development, validation, and deployment. When clarifications emerge that reinterpret existing guidance, the real cost isn't just the retraining of our compliance team, though that matters. It's the operational uncertainty. Do we redesign now or wait for further guidance? Do we notify existing customers of potential drift, and if so, how do we characterize something that isn't yet an enforcement action but might be one? These decisions ripple across our organization and affect how quickly we can move to market with new capabilities.<br><br>I mention this not as a complaint but as context for why we believe the current DSI certification criterion requiring detailed AI model card disclosures should be retained and, if anything, clarified further rather than relaxed. The logic here is straightforward and has nothing to do with market protection: transparency in high-stakes healthcare AI is foundational to patient safety and clinical adoption, and the model card requirement is one of the few mechanisms we have to ensure that transparency actually happens.<br><br>Let me be direct about what's happened in our conversations with our customers. We've sold AI-driven clinical decision support tools to three health systems in Nevada and Utah over the past two years. Before deployment, clinicians asked us the same questions repeatedly: What population did you train this on? Do you know where it performs poorly? What happens if the patient demographics don't match your training set? These aren't theoretical concerns. They're how clinicians think about risk. One of our customers‚ÄĒa rural health system in northern Nevada‚ÄĒexplicitly told us they wouldn't implement our tool without clarity on performance variation across age groups and comorbidity profiles. That's not regulatory burden speaking. That's clinical judgment.<br><br>The model card criterion, as currently structured, forces us to answer those questions upfront and in writing. It requires us to document intended use, target population, known risks, training data characteristics, and validation processes. Yes, this takes time. Our team spent six weeks pulling together the first model card for our sepsis risk algorithm. But here's what happened: in that process, we discovered a performance gap in patients over 75 with renal impairment. We wouldn't have found that without being forced to systematically document our validation approach. We fixed it before deployment. The alternative‚ÄĒreleasing the tool and learning about the gap from a patient safety event‚ÄĒis categorically worse.<br><br>The concern about burden is real, and I don't think it should be dismissed. We are a smaller company. We don't have a dedicated regulatory affairs division the way Cerner or Epic do. But the burden we're discussing isn't the burden of doing the work‚ÄĒit's the burden of documenting that we did the work carefully. Those are not the same thing. A vendor should be doing validation work regardless. The model card criterion doesn't create that obligation; it makes the obligation visible.<br><br>What we've seen create genuine friction is inconsistency in how model cards are reviewed and what reviewers consider sufficient evidence. We submitted our first model card in November 2023 and received feedback asking for additional detail on our training data provenance. That was reasonable. But the reviewer's email didn't cite specific criteria from the certification guidance‚ÄĒit referenced an internal memo that apparently clarified expectations but wasn't widely distributed. Our compliance team spent three weeks trying to figure out whether this new standard applied to all our algorithms or just ones using certain data sources. It turned out to apply to all of them, but we only learned that by calling ONC directly.<br><br>This is where I think the deregulatory impulse, while well-intentioned, misses something important. The problem isn't the model card requirement. The problem is that vendors, especially smaller ones, can't reliably predict what regulators will expect. That uncertainty costs more money than the actual documentation work.<br><br>If the goal is to reduce burden on developers while maintaining patient safety guardrails, the path forward isn't to eliminate model card requirements. It's to standardize them. ONC should publish a detailed model card template with worked examples‚ÄĒnot just a list of required fields but actual examples of how a vendor should document training data composition, how to report performance metrics across subgroups, what level of detail is expected for "known risks." Right now, vendors are essentially reverse-engineering expectations from feedback on submissions. That's inefficient.<br><br>There's also a question about audience that the current criterion doesn't fully address‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒ‚ôĒpageCount, Page Count, Number of pages In the content file
